<FIRST>u w AM-BRF--InfantAbducted     10-24 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Infant Abducted,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baby Abducted From Hospital Returned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An infant abducted from a hospital pediatric
ward was returned safely on Tuesday, about 24 hours after he was
reported missing, and a woman who recently lost her own baby was
arrested, authorities said.
   The infant, now 19 days old, appeared to have been well cared
for and was in excellent condition, according to Ann Chisholm, a
spokeswoman for D.C. General Hospital.
   Lisa P. Oliver, 23, of Washington, was charged with kidnapping,
police said. She was scheduled for a D.C. Superior Court appearance
on Wednesday. Oliver recently lost a baby of her own and
desperately wanted another, D.C. Police Chief Deputy Alfonso Gibson
said.
   ``She did have a child that she had lost,'' Gibson said.
``Apparently, she had a cradle and all of the necessities that's
needed to care for an infant.''
   The baby, who was up for adoption, was taken by a woman posing
as hospital volunteer, police said.
   Police spokesman Quintin Peterson said detectives were led to
Ms. Oliver after receiving tips from neighbors. Someone saw Ms.
Oliver with a baby Tuesday, and knowing that she didn't have a
child, called the police. She was arrested at her home, authorities
said.
   Hospital officials said Tuesday new security measures were being
considered.
   ``We are certainly going to take a look at some changes with
regard to the check-in procedures and the identification of
volunteers,'' Ms. Chisholm said.
</TEXT>
