<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Magnitude     10-24 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Magnitude,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magnitude Raised to 7.1 After Additional Readings Studied</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The magnitude of the deadly earthquake
that pelted Northern California last week was increased from 6.9 to
a 7.1 after seismologists studied additional monitoring charts,
geophysicists said.
   The quake was recorded at 5:04 p.m. PDT on Oct. 17 and was
blamed for the deaths of dozens of people, injuries to thousands
and damage in excess of $7 billion.
   Besides altering the Richter scale reading, the U.S. Geological
Survey altered the epicenter and focal depth.
   ``The revised magnitude was based on more clearly defined data
that was recorded at 18 selected seismic stations all over the
world,'' Waverly Person, director of the USGS National Earthquake
Information Service in Golden, Colo., said in a statement Tuesday.
   ``The original magnitude of 6.9 was based on more localized
seismic readings,'' the statement sid.
   The temblor was the largest quake to occur along the San Andreas
Fault since the 1906 San Francisco quake, Waverly said. That quake
has been estimated at 8.3 on the Richter scale of ground motion,
although monitoring equipment had not been invented at that time.
   Thousands of aftershocks have rattled the Bay Area region in the
week since the main quake.
   The epicenter of the quake was moved one mile northeast but was
still in the Loma Prieta area, said USGS Geophysicist Andrew Pitt.
   Geologically, the most significant change in readings was the
focal depth, originally measured at 12 kilometers but now believed
to have been 18 kilometers, Pitt said.
   ``You measure from the surface down. It started at a depth of 18
kilometers and broke upward horizontally,'' he explained.
</TEXT>
