<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 2357EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Graves     10-24 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Graves,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Rocks Santa Cruz-Area Cemeteries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATSONVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffins were jostled and tombstones
were toppled by the hundreds in graveyards when the earth groaned
during last week's 7.1-magnitude earthquake.
   The Virgin Mary and other religious icons, sentinals over a
century-old graveyard near midtown here, tumbled to the ground and
cemetery managers called off all burials until repairs can be made.
   ``Some of the marble monuments are shattered and they will be
very difficult to repair. The granite ones we can stand up again,
though,'' said Everett Dias, manager for the five Santa Cruz
County-operated cemeteries.
   The five cemeteries _ Valley Catholic, Valley, Pioneer,
Watsonville Catholic and Day Valley _ hold 20,000 bodies dating to
1860.
   Hardest hit was Valley Catholic Cemetery on Freedom Boulevard. A
huge pepper tree is the centerpiece of the two-acre garden of
marble and granite where most graves bear the inscription: ``Rest
in Peace.''
   ``We suffered extensive damage to the upright stones in four
cemeteries,'' said Dias. Valley Cemetery was spared damage because
only flat markers are allowed.
   Dias said the cemeteries had received dozens of telephone calls
from concerned relatives. Graveyard officials assured them repairs
would be swift.
   Dias said cemetery workers were trying to clear away debris and
repair damage. On a cold and rainy Tuesday one week after the
disaster, there were no visitors in the cemetery.
   ``At this time we are holding off on burials to the end of the
week,'' he said. ``We have holding vaults for them now.''
   He estimated up to 500 markers were toppled in the quake that
killed dozens, injured thousands and caused more than $7 billion in
damage to Northern California.
   The aged Valley Catholic Cemetery was littered with fractured
madonnas and Jesus statues. The face of a 3-foot-tall marble Mary
Magdalen was buried in the grass. Ornate marble crosses were
shattered to bits.
   Many concrete-covered gravesites were cracked. In some cases,
there had been cave-ins.
   Well-manicured lawns surrounded family plots where concrete and
plastic flowers were bleached by the sun and upended by the quake.
   The four-space Stolieh family crypt is only half full. The two
empty crypts have shattered granite doors.
   An ornate, 10-foot-tall marble marker honoring Josephine M.
Dail, who died Jan. 31, 1888, toppled. The tombstone of Cary
Freirmuth, who died in 1929, was upside down and in the mud.
   The marble cross over Thereza Gonzalves' grave was shattered. It
had withstood the 1906 San Francisco quake. She died Oct. 13, 1885.
   Patrick Mahoney died April 19, 1874. His marble marker was also
destroyed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
