<FIRST>r w PM-HUD-Demery     10-24 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Demery,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former HUD Official Says He Did Nothing Wrong in Advising Bush Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former top housing official says he did
nothing improper in providing campaign debate advice to George Bush
last year while administering a program now at the center of the
HUD scandal.
   Former assistant housing secretary Thomas T. Demery provided
debating points on housing, using documents from computer files in
his office at the Department of Housing and Urban Development,
according to Demery and documents released by the department Monday
under the Freedom of Information Act.
   Demery's contact with the Bush campaign was Republican
consultant Paul Manafort, who has admitted to Congress that he
practiced ``influence-peddling'' at HUD.
   Manafort is a partner in a disputed New Jersey housing
development that received more than $31 million in federal
subsidies. He has acknowledged to congressional investigators that
he lobbied HUD on more than 20 other projects.
   Demery, in an interview, said he did not believe Bush used the
debate material.
   In other documents, Demery said he delivered campaign speeches
for Bush, sometimes while traveling on HUD business.
   Demery administered the department's Section 8 Moderate
Rehabilitation program, which provided lucrative subsidy grants
sought by developers, including Manafort and Manafort's clients.
   Alleged abuses of the moderate rehabilitation program, including
the steering of lucrative subsidy grants to politically favored
developers, triggered further investigations of HUD programs by
congressional committees, and the Justice Department says it is
investigating HUD activities across the nation.
   In the interview, Demery acknowledged providing tips for Bush's
debates with Democrat Michael Dukakis. He contended there was
nothing improper about providing political advice while working at
HUD because he was a presidential appointee, named by President
Reagan.
   In one document, he said that Dukakis, the governor of
Massachusetts, ``has presided over de facto segregation'' in Boston
public housing and said the city ``still contains some of the last
vestiges of segregation in America today.''
   Demery was sharply criticized in a HUD audit report issued by
inspector general Paul Adams last May. The audit charged favoritism
in the awarding of moderate rehabilitation grants and questioned
his efforts to raise money from developers and others dealing with
HUD for a favored charity, FOOD for Africa.
   Demery contends others made the subsidy decisions and that his
activities for the charity were proper.
   Demery's files contained letters he wrote to Adams last year
defending his actions and questioning the investigation.
   He wrote one letter to FBI Director William Sessions complaining
about the inspector general's investigation, but he said Monday he
never mailed it. Demery's letter charged that his mail had been
intercepted and the documents involving his personal finances
eventually were obtained by the inspector general.
   Other documents show that Demery complained to then-Secretary
Samuel Pierce about the activities of Hunter Cushing, then deputy
assistant secretary for multi-family housing, and reprimanded
Cushing directly for poor work.
   Demery contends that although Cushing reported to him, Cushing
was engaged in political work and worked with Deborah Gore Dean,
Pierce's former top aide. Dean, Pierce and Cushing have all refused
to testify before congressional investigators, citing their
constitutional rights against self-incrimination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
