<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0121EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SFQuake-FEMA     10-24 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-FEMA,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Aid Offered for Everything From Home-Rebuilding to Mental Counseling</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: May be updated with House action on aid bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The billions of dollars that Congress wants to
give California's earthquake victims will be used for a range of
relief and recovery programs, from home-rebuilding loans to mental
health counseling.
   Families whose homes are uninhabitable can seek money to pay for
temporary housing, while special loans are available to small
businesses that need quick capital and local governments can get
aid in repairing public buildings and parks.
   Congress is rushing to approve a $2.85 billion aid package for
the San Francisco Bay area, and members say more money could come
later.
   Shortly after the earthquake struck California a week ago,
President Bush signed a disaster declaration that freed up $273
million for emergency programs, but members of Congress immediately
said a major aid package would be needed. Sen. Alan Cranston,
D-Calif., estimated the damage at $7 billion, but said Monday that
he didn't expect the federal government to pay that much.
   Under some federal programs, the state of California will kick
in 25 percent of the cost. Others are fully funded by the federal
government.
   FEMA, which coordinates recovery programs, provided the
following information about available programs. The amount of money
spent on each program depends on how many applications are received.
   The Department of Transportation gives money for the repair or
reconstruction of highways.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>The president's disaster relief fund, administered by FEMA,</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   includes:
   _Temporary housing assistance: Reasonable payments for families
whose homes are uninhabitable. Aid is available for 18 months, with
payments based on prevailing rental rates.
   _Home repairs: Payments to make minor repairs to make housing
usable.
   _Individual and family grants: Up to $10,400 per individual or
family to meet serious disaster needs and expenses not covered by
other federal assistance programs. The federal government pays 75
percent; the state the rest.
   _Disaster unemployment assistance: Benefit payments for up to 26
weeks, based on state benefit rates, for workers who lost their
jobs because of the disaster or others who are not covered by state
compensation.
   _Crisis counseling: The National Institute of Mental Health
provides short-term counseling for mental health problems.
   _Public property: Reimbursable payments to local governments of
at least 75 percent of the eligible costs for the repair and
replacement of damaged public facilities such as roads, bridges,
utilities, buildings and parks.
   _Community disaster loans: The loans are not to exceed 25
percent of the annual operating budget of any local government
which has suffered a substantial loss of tax or other revenue as a
result of a major disaster.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>The Small Business Administration has two programs:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Disaster loans: Low-interest loans of 4 percent to 8 percent to
cover uninsured private and business property losses. Ceilings are
$100,000 for primary residence; $20,000 for personal property, and
$500,000 for businesses. Length of repayment can be extended 30
years.
   _Economic injury disaster loans: Up to $500,000 for small
businesses that suffered disaster-related cash flow problems and
need loans for working capital. This loan, in combination with a
physical property loan, cannot exceed $500,000.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>The Department of Agriculture offers three programs:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Emergency loans: The Farmers Home Administration gives loans to
cover physical property and production losses. Limits are 80
percent of the sum of the calculated production loss, and-or 100
percent of the actual physical property loss, or $500,000,
whichever is less. Interest rates vary between 5 percent and 8
percent.
   _Emergency conservation: Payments of up to $200,000 for repair
of items such as permanent fencing, debris removal or irrigation
systems.
   _Emergency watershed protection: Financial aid to eliminate the
imminent threat to life due to damage to a watershed. Money is
available to governments.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>The Department of Education has two programs:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Grants to public schools damaged by a disaster.
   _Grants for maintenance and operation expenses, such as
replacement of equipment, debris removal and minor building repairs.
</TEXT>
