<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0122EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearDeals     10-24 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Deals,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Utilities Report Deals With Nuclear Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least three electric utilities admit making
deals with nuclear plant workers that could be seen as rewarding
them for not reporting potential safety problems, government
records show.
   All three companies insisted in letters to the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission that the labor settlements were legal and
proper, but they acknowledged some provisions might be viewed as
``silence-for-money'' deals.
   Duke Power Co. of Charlotte, N.C.; GPU Nuclear Corp. of
Parsippany, N.J.; and Omaha Public Power District of Omaha, Neb.,
disclosed the agreements in response to an NRC inquiry last spring
aimed at determining if such deals are common in the industry.
   Congress has criticized the NRC for failing to explicitly outlaw
such settlements.
   The controversy stemmed from a Senate investigation last spring
of two labor settlements between builders of the Comanche Peak
nuclear power plant in Texas and workers who received payments in
return for keeping quiet about potential safety hazards.
   The Labor Department later ruled that such settlement provisions
were unacceptable, but the NRC commissioners have been unable to
agree how and whether to outlaw them.
   In April, the NRC sent letters to all nuclear utilities and
their contractors asking to be told of any labor settlements that
restricted an employee's ability to report safety information to
the NRC.
   A review Monday of the written responses from the utilities and
contractors showed all denied having any such restrictions.
However, the three companies said they had settlements with
provisions that might be construed by others as limiting a worker's
ability to raise safety concerns.
   Duke Power was the only utility to provide specific information
about a settlement. It said it felt compelled to report the case to
the NRC ``in light of the sensitivity of the issue,'' even though
it believes the settlement was proper.
   The case involves an April 21, 1988, settlement with former
employee Howard Samuel Nunn Jr., who filed a civil suit against
Duke after he was dismissed in October 1983.
   In a passage similar to a provision of the Comanche Peak
settlement, the Duke settlement stipulated that Nunn ``will not
voluntarily appear as a witness'' in any legal or administrative
proceeding involving Duke. It also said he would not ``seek to
induce any government agency'' to take any action against Duke.
   Duke told the NRC these passages were designed to settle the
Nunn suit. The deal ``clearly left Mr. Nunn free ... to bring any
concerns to the NRC ... if he so desired,'' Duke wrote to the
commission.
   Duke said it wrote to Nunn in July saying he is free to bring
any safety matter to the NRC. Duke operates three plants in North
Carolina and South Carolina.
   GPU Nuclear and Omaha Public Power, in separate letters to the
NRC, said that while they found no restrictive clauses in their
labor settlements, the language in four settlement agreements might
be viewed as restricting the individual's ability to raise
potential safety issues with the NRC.
   The utilities provided no details, but said they advised the
people involved to disregard any settlement language that they
thought limited their ability to raise safety issues.
   GPU Nuclear owns the Three Mile Island nuclear station in
Pennsylvania and the Oyster Creek plant in New Jersey. Omaha Public
Power owns the Fort Calhoun nuclear plant in Nebraska.
   Bob Newlin, an NRC spokesman, said Monday the commission wrote
letters to people involved in questionable settlements. A few of
them wrote back to the NRC about safety issues, but Newlin said he
could not provide details.
   Five other companies said that while they saw no problems with
any of their labor settlement deals, they wrote to people involved
in 11 cases to emphasize that they were under no limits in
contacting the NRC about safety issues.
   The five are Pacific Gas &amp; Electric Co. of San Francisco,
Houston Lighting and Power Co., Georgia Power Co. of Atlanta,
Carolina Power &amp; Light Co. of Raleigh, N.C., and Bechtel Corp. of
San Francisco.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
