<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     10-24 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Still Waiting for Disaster Relief Checks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most farmers who planted a second crop after
freezing weather and drought destroyed their winter wheat or cotton
are still waiting for disaster relief checks from the Agriculture
Department, says Sen. Phil Gramm.
   ``For people who are waiting for their checks, this is getting
to be a problem and I'm eager to do something,'' said Gramm,
R-Texas.
   Gramm and other Great Plains lawmakers contend USDA's
regulations implementing an $895 million drought relief bill
unfairly cut payments to farmers who planted a second crop.
   USDA officials said Monday that farmers who rotated their
traditional spring crop to land where winter wheat was destroyed by
drought or freezing weather are entitled to disaster payments.
   ``It doesn't solve the problem most people have with their
second crop,'' Gramm said.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, called the decision by the
Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service good news, but
agreed it doesn't go far enough in reversing USDA regulations that
would cut disaster assistance to many other farmers who had also
planted a second crop.
   A Senate aide said the USDA's decision Monday apparently applies
only to winter wheat farmers who would traditionally plant a second
crop, such as milo, on non-wheat acres in the spring.
   Those farmers who planted their second crop on the wheat acres
instead, to take advantage of fertilizer already on the land, won't
see their disaster checks cut, the aide said.
   The decision doesn't cover hundreds of cotton farmers who also
planted a second crop, or farmers who planted non-traditional
second crops on their wheat acreage or in addition to their wheat
acreage, officials said.
   Legislators and USDA have been wrangling over the regulations on
``ghost acres'' for two months, and one Senate aide said the
decision came because ``we had to force their hand on this.''
   Bentsen said farmers from Texas, Kansas, Oklahoma and elsewhere
on the Great Plains planted milo or cotton on their failed wheat
acres this year, but were told by ASCS that their disaster checks
would be reduced if they instead planted their spring cotton or
milo crops on the winter wheat land.
   ``Had they planted the spring crop normally, without rotating it
to the failed wheat acres, there would be no reduction in the
disaster checks,'' Bentsen said. ``It is obviously unfair to
penalize farmers when they are following normal farming practices
by simply rotating their crops on the farm.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Agriculture
Committee says he'll talk with Agriculture Secretary Clayton
Yeutter and Mexican Agriculture Secretary Jorge de la Vega on
Wednesday about Mexico's refusal to accept livestock from privately
operated inspection centers.
   Rep. Kika de la Garza, D-Texas, and Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas
raised their concerns about the bottlenecks at Texas centers with
Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari during his recent state
visit to Washington.
   The Mexican government will accept only livestock that has been
inspected at one of five Texas state operated facilities along the
border, though 23 privately run pens are available.
   Gramm said the state facilities operate only during normal
business hours, while slaughter livestock are typically shipped
through commercial facilities at any time of night or day.
   ``My people don't want to be forced to deal with the government
when private pens are available,'' Gramm said Monday.
   ``We have sent clear signals to the Mexican Embassy that there
is going to be congressional action'' unless they can ``come back
and deal with what they perceive to be a small problem,'' Gramm
said.
   Steve Poore, a spokesman for USDA's Animal and Plant Health
Inspection Service, said the five pens in Texas are the only
shipment facilities on the 2,000-mile border formally approved by
Mexico, although a few animals may have been shipped unofficially
at other points.
   The agency has suggested that Mexico consider approving about 30
other pens in California, Arizona, New Mexico and Texas.
   ``Mexico is going to inspect the pens we have suggested and
decide which ones to approve,'' he said.
   Janna Evans, another agency spokeswoman, said Mexico may make a
decision within a week to 10 days.
</TEXT>
