<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-ObsceneArt     10-24 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Obscene Art,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Interior Bill Banning Obscene Art</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal funds may not be used for material
judged to be obscene by two government agencies, under a bill
signed by President Bush.
   The bill became the focal point of dispute in Congress because
of protests over the use of taxpayer money to display Robert
Mapplethorpe's photographs with homosexual subjects and Andres
Serrano's photo of a crucifix in a jar of urine.
   The measure, signed Monday, stipulates that federal funds may
not be used for materials judged to be obscene by the National
Endowment of the Arts and the National Endowment of the Humanities.
   The $11.4 billion Interior Department spending bill for fiscal
1990 also bars oil and gas drilling in 84 million acres off the
shores of California, Alaska, the Gulf of Mexico near Florida's
Everglades and the East Coast.
   Bush expressed reservations about extending for another year the
moratorium on oil and gas leasing and exploration on the Outer
Continental Shelf. However, he said the overall benefits of the
bill outweighed his concerns.
   Rep. Ralph S. Regula, R-Ohio, the ranking Republican on the
House Appropriations subcommittee on the interior, praised the
action on obscene art and said he shared Bush's reservation on the
restrictions on offshore drilling.
   ``We're up to about 50 percent plus imported oil now to meet our
needs. I'm not for drilling every square foot. There's fragile
areas off of Florida and California we should protect. ... But
there are other areas that logically should be drilled and are
still included in the moratoria for aesthetic reasons.''
   The moratorium means ``we can't look at these 84 million acres
even in the event of a national (energy) emergency,'' he said.
</TEXT>
