<FIRST>r w PM-US-Lebanon     10-24 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Lebanon,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Welcomes Arab Plan For Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is hailing a peace
plan approved by Lebanon's Parliament but rejected by a Christian
leader and the two main militias of the Shiite Moslem sect.
   President Bush ``congratulates the Lebanese deputies for their
courage and statesmanship, which have yielded an extraordinary
opportunity to bring lasting peace in Lebanon,'' White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Monday.
   ``This is the first step toward restoration of a sovereign,
unified, and independent Lebanon, free of all foreign forces,'' he
said.
   Gen. Michel Aoun put his Christian forces on alert after
complaining that the plan didn't provide a timetable for the
withdrawal of the 40,000 Syrian troops from Lebanon.
   ``What the deputies approved in Taif is a crime I will not
accept,'' he said of the accord, approved Sunday by a special
parliamentary session in the Saudi Arabian city.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret D. Tutwiler said the
United States ``warmly welcomes'' the accord. However, she said
there had been no change in U.S. policy calling for the withdrawal
of Syrian troops that control a vast portion of Lebanon, and
Israeli forces that hold a security belt in the South.
   The pro-Syrian mainstream Shiite Amal militia and the
pro-Iranian fundamentalist Hezbollah, or Party of God, which is
believed to be holding eight American hostages, rejected the accord
because they want a bigger representation in a new parliament.
   Apart from the troops issue, U.S. policy has called for a larger
role for Moslems in running Lebanon's government. Power is split
fairly evenly between Christians and Moslems.
