<FIRST>r i PM-China-Spying     10-24 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Spying,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Canton Residents Jailed On Charges Of Spying During Demonstrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two residents of the southern Chinese city of
Canton have been sentenced to jail on charges of spying for Taiwan
during the spring pro-democracy demonstrations, an official report
said.
   The Guangzhou (Canton) Municipal Mid-level Court on Monday
sentenced Zhang Yi and Wu Jidong to 13 years and 10 years in prison
respectively on charges they spied for the Kuomintang, or
Nationalist Party, that rules Taiwan, the China News Service
reported.
   The news agency claimed the two had worked for the Kuomintang
since October 1988. It said Zhang received 1,200 Chinese yuan
($323) for his services and Wu was paid 100,000 Japanese yen ($700).
   Kuomintang agents _ identified only by the surnames Zhou, Wang
and Wu _ trained Wu and Zhang to be spies, provided them with
espionage equipment and ordered them to report on student
demonstrations and protest fasts taking place in Beijing and
Canton, the report said.
   The Nationalist Chinese government on Taiwan claims to be the
sole rightful ruler of all China even though it lost a civil war to
the Communist Chinese 40 years ago. Beijing views Taiwan as a
renegade province.
   China announced nearly three weeks after crushing the
student-led pro-democracy movement in early June the arrest of 13
men on allegations of spying for Taiwan to instigate the protests.
It said the men were Chinese nationals recruited by Nationalist
military intelligence officers.
   Taiwan denied the arrested men were Nationalist spies.
   There was no immediate Nationalist reaction to the latest
allegations of spying by the two Cantonese men.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
