<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0209EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--BostonLight     10-24 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Boston Light,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>273-Year-Old Lighthouse to be Staffed for at Least One More Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 273-year-old Boston Light, the nation's oldest
lighthouse, has received federal funds for someone to light the
lamp for at least another year.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and Coast Guard Adm. Richard
Rybacki said Monday the money will postpone plans to reassign
Boston Lights' three-man crew and automate the lighthouse this
fall. The automation was to be part of a nationwide program to
upgrade lighthouses.
   In the Coast Guard's fiscal 1990 appropriation, $100,000 that
was earmarked for automating the lighthouse on Little Brewster
Island will be used instead for staffing. Boston Light was first
lit in 1716.
   ``There are some benefits having a lighthouse manned by the
Coast Guard. It's a traditional thing and the places are very
valuable national treasures,'' said Coast Guard Lt. Paul Wolf.
``However, technology has allowed us to do the automation work so
there isn't a need for someone to go and light the lamp anymore.''
</TEXT>
