<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     10-24 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Urged to Retain Medicare Coverage for Exams</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress should salvage Medicare coverage of
mammograms from the catastrophic health insurance program the House
recently voted to repeal because the tests help prevent breast
cancer deaths, women's health activists say.
   ``It's time for women to take their health care into their own
hands,'' said Deborah Dingell, chairwoman of the National Women's
Health Resources Center. ``If this were a man's issue, it wouldn't
be a problem.''
   The comments came after a ceremony Monday honoring people who
have raised awareness about breast cancer, which strikes one in 10
American women.
   Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, was cited for her efforts in
Congress, such as including mammography tests in the Medicare
Catastrophic Coverage Act of 1988. She urged that Congress be
lobbied to accept a Senate provision retaining coverage for breast
cancer tests.
   House and Senate negotiators are trying to work out differences
on the program. The mammography program would initially cost $60
million but would ultimately save millions of dollars through early
detection that would save hospitalization costs, Ms. Oakar said.
</TEXT>
