<SECOND>PM-People-Humperdinck,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Humperdinck's Star on Hollywood Sidewalk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romantic crooner Engelbert Humperdinck was
cheered by 500 fans as officials dedicated a star bearing the
entertainer's name on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.
   The star commemorating the smooth-voiced singer's contributions
to the music industry was dedicated Monday and was the 1,901st on
the walk.
   ``America has blessed me in so many ways,'' said Humperdinck,
who was born Arnold George Dorsey and grew up in Britain. ``This is
a tremendous honor after 23 years in the business.''
   Following the ceremony, about 300 fans from some of his 250 fan
clubs around the world gave a party for the 52-year-old singer, who
was accompanied by his wife and four children.
   Humperdinck has had 15 of his albums go platinum, including two
in West Germany during the past two years, and has 42 gold records.
A platinum record means sales of at least a million records and a
gold record means sales of 500,000. He has won two Grammy awards.
   His best-known records include ``Release Me'' and ``After the
Lovin'.''
