<DOCNO> AP891024-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0221EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Survivor     10-24 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Survivor,0863</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Day in the Life of Buck Helm</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto OAS1</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The night before Buck Helm unknowingly
drove his aging car into a concrete death trap, the burly
longshoreman slept as usual in the rusty yellow panel truck he kept
parked by the docks, co-workers said.
   The morning before he defied death at the hands of a killer
earthquake, he'd been a winner at tonk, the card game of the docks
played at a quarter a hand.
   At 5:04 p.m. on Oct. 17, the magnitude 6.9 earthquake caused a
1\-mile-long section of Interstate 880 to cave in around him,
killing dozens of motorists and pinning Helm across the front seat
of his tiny Chevrolet Sprint. For the next 90 hours, he remained
trapped under the crumbled concrete.
   On Monday, the 57-year-old survivor surprised his doctors at
Highland General Hospital by nodding his head to indicate he felt
no pain.
   Dr. Floyd Huen, medical director of the hospital, said Helm's
condition could be upgraded from very serious to serious if he
continued recovering at the present rate.
   ``When he was asked about whether he was hurting anywhere, he
shook his head and everbody was incredulous,'' Huen said.
   After work a week ago today, Helm jumped into his silver Sprint
and drove into what would become the heart of the disaster,
according to a ship's clerk at the Port of Oakland's Charles P.
Howard Terminal.
   Four days later, astonished rescue workers pulled him out of the
crumbled interstate.
   Helm's children and former wife have been at the hospital since
he was rescued Saturday.
   ``Buck and I was married 16 years and we have some beautiful
children,'' said his ex-wife, Lorrie, flanked by daughter Desiree,
12, sons Jeffery, 16, and Marc, 22, and Marc's fiancee, Audra.
``We've always been the best of friends no matter what.
   ``He's always been there when I needed him,'' she told
reporters. ``This is when he needs us.''
   Desiree was afraid her father had been killed because he hadn't
called to say he was safe.
   Marc is waiting for the day his father comes home and tells the
kids to clean house, the way he used to, or goes back to building a
rock wall in the yard.
   ``I'm sure when he was in there he was saying, `There's no way,'
'' Marc said. He is sure his father kept repeating: ```My daughter,
she's going to get married (some day), she's going to graduate. My
son's in college. My other son's going to be going to college.'
   ``Just no way he was going to give up,'' Marc said.
   Helm, 5-foot-11 and 230 pounds, can't talk because a respirator
tube has been run down his throat.
   After a news conference, Helm's ex-wife took a 15-minute tour of
the freeway where her former husband survived beyond all odds. She
was escorted by police officers.
   ``She said, `Oh, my God. I don't see how anyone could make it
out alive.' And then she reflected on it a minute and said, `Well,
if anyone could, Buck could,''' said police Sgt. Jack Huth.
   Fellow dockworkers disagreed as to whether Helm was headed to
The Oaks Clubroom in neighboring Emeryville, where he played
lowball poker once a week, or to Berkeley where he enjoyed exotic
foods.
   Basil Parker, a ship's clerk, passed Helm on the freeway on his
way home to Berkeley before he heard the roar and saw the clouds of
dust behind him after the freeway caved in.
   ``If he was going to The Oaks, he would have just gone up Market
to San Pablo,'' Parker said. ``I would have to assume the man was
going to Berkeley.''
   Wherever he was headed, it was in a tiny car that had more than
200,000 miles on it because of all the weekend trips he'd made to
visit his family in Weaverville, 250 miles north of San Francisco,
co-workers said.
   ``You'd look at it and think that any collision would kill the
occupant,'' said Ralph Bucher, chief clerk at the terminal where
Helm works.
   Helm also kept a panel truck at the docks and slept in it many a
night. On the left side of the truck, they said, Helm had painted
in orange the words ``Weaverville Flash,'' referring to the
Northern California logging town.
   On the right side, he painted a cartoon bunny and ``Desiree's
Delight,'' after the daughter he called his rabbit.
   Inside, Helm had a mattress, a Snoopy sleeping bag, two alarm
clocks, some clothes, and a panel of photographs of his children,
including one of Desiree in a huge pair of football shoulderpads.
   ``He has tried living down in this area,'' Bucher said. ``He
basically figured that rather than being in business for himself he
was better off with that weekly paycheck and acted to go back to
the mountains and go through the routine of commuting on weekends
to and from and basically living on the docks during the week.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
