<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0234EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Editor     10-24 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Editor,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Editor Defies Pressure to Resign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The editor of the Soviet Union's most popular
newspaper says Communist officials want to scare the press into
toeing the party line by making an example of him for straying.
   But Vladislav A. Starkov says he will resist pressure to quit.
   The editor-in-chief of the weekly Arguments and Facts appealed
to Western public opinion on Monday from the office President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev had suggested he vacate.
   ``It's a great injustice and a violation of all my journalistic
rights,'' Starkov said in an interview of the attack on how he has
run the paper.
   He said he was the victim of unspecified high party officials
who were trying to make an example of him ``to frighten the whole
press.''
   Starkov said officials have forced him to cancel a planned trip
to Canada on Saturday, and that he was afraid he might also have to
forgo a trip to New York scheduled for Oct. 25.
   Eleven days ago, Gorbachev criticized several top Soviet editors
as inflaming passions and hurting reform efforst by allegedly
overplaying the country's economic and ethnic troubles.
   He reportedly said Starkov should resign over a poll his paper
carried implying that human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov is
more popular than Gorbachev.
   ``Mikhail Sergeyevich told me that in my place he would
resign,'' said Starkov. ``But I took it as a warning, not a direct
firing order.''
   Despite this, Starkov reiterated his strong support for
perestroika, Gorbachev's program of economic and political reform.
   ``The most insulting thing for me in all this is that I'm being
considered almost an enemy of Gorbachev, or an enemy of
perestroika,'' he said. ``There was never anything like that.''
   Starkov said, however, that officials have not been suffiently
making clear the proper line the press should take.
   ``There is a struggle on. I understand I'm a victim of that
struggle, and Arguments and Facts fell between the stones of a
treadmill.''
   The stocky, 49-year-old editor who has headed Arguments and
Facts for 10 years said that although the weekly had made mistakes,
he stands behind it.
   The Soviet press has carried only one vaguely worded story about
the closed-door meeting at which Gorbachev rebuked the editors, and
nothing at all about the call for Starkov to resign.
   Arguments and Facts is published by Znaniye _ Russian for
``knowledge'' _ a national society that sponsors lectures, books
and periodicals and is not under direct government control. But
Starkov said the ruling Communist Party could order Znaniye to fire
him.
   He would not specify who was pressing him to resign, but he said
party officials were trying to get him to agree to a ``promotion''
to the State Publishing Committee or the parliament.
   The Arguments and Facts staff of 20 reporters and editors and
was surprised their newspaper was picked out for censure, said
deputy editor-in-chief Alexander Meshchersky.
   ``We not only criticize but try to find solutions,'' he said.
``If we have pursued an erroneous editorial policy then 26 million
people are wrong.''
   With a circulation of 26 million and annual profit of about $39
million, Arguments and Facts is the most widely read Soviet
newspaper.
   It aims to tell people what they want to know, from rumors of a
price hike on gasoline to the history of Soviet espionage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-BayBridge     10-24 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Bay Bridge,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Portion of Damaged Section Removed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERIANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An upper section of the Bay Bridge that
crashed onto a lower deck in last week's earthquake is too badly
damaged to be used again, state transportation officials said.
   ``It's too bent up and unsuitable,'' said Jim Larson, spokesman
for the California Department of Transportation. But he added the
decision Monday to build a new section won't add any time to the
estimated four weeks that the main link between Oakland and San
Francisco will be closed.
   The damaged upper section is 74 feet long and 50 feet wide and
weighs 200 tons. The section was cut in half by concrete saws and
blow torches beginning Saturday to make it easier to move.
   Workers on Monday completed the dangerous job of removing the
upper section by crane and lowering it 200 feet to a barge. The two
pieces were shipped to nearby Alameda.
   Workers also lowered part of the bottom deck that was damaged
and cracked when the upper deck collapsed onto it, and planned to
complete that project today.
   For four weeks and perhaps longer, thousands of commuters who
depend on the bridge will have to find alternate routes across San
Francisco Bay.
   The 8.5-mile-long bridge, which opened in 1936, normally carries
260,000 vehicles per day. Officials say repairs will cost up to $1
million.
   Nationally broadcast pictures of the broken bridge, with the
upper deck dangling like an open trap door, provided the first
graphic illustration of the magnitude of the 6.9 Richter scale
quake. One woman died when she drove her car into the gap.
   The bridge also had been in the logo created for the 1989 World
Series between the San Francisco Giants and the Oakland Athletics.
But its closure contributed to Sunday's decision to delay
resumption of the championship until Friday, as officials attempt
to reduce traffic problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
