<DOCNO> AP891024-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0416EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle     10-24 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlantis Astronauts Return Home, Galileo Probe Continues On Long
Journey</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto EAB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlantis' five astronauts were home
with most of today off, while their ``amazingly clean'' spaceship
remained in California for servicing after a successful mission
that sent the Galileo to Jupiter.
   The Galileo probe, said to be operating flawlessly, has traveled
more than 1.1 million miles since deployment about 6{ hours after
Wednesday's blastoff. The $1.5-billion, nuclear-powered probe's
2.4-billion-mile trip will take six years.
   The long-delayed odyssey to Jupiter will include one sweep past
Venus and two by Earth to gain momentum from the planets' gravity.
Once it reaches Jupiter, Galileo will fire a probe into the Jovian
atmosphere and then orbit the largest planet for 22 months.
   Atlantis returned to Earth on Monday with a picture-perfect
landing that occurred three hours early at Edwards Air Force Base,
Calif., to avoid higher winds predicted for the afternoon. Winds
moments before touchdown were only about 4{ mph.
   ``Atlantis, congratulations on an outstanding mission,'' Ken
Cameron radioed from the Johnson Space Center in Houston. ``You've
extended the shuttle's reach to the outer planets.''
   ``It's nice to be home,'' replied shuttle commander Donald E.
Williams, who guided the 97-ton winged spaceship to a pinpoint
landing on a hard clay runway in the Mojave Desert.
   The 9:32 a.m. PDT landing ended a 1.7 million-mile-mission that
unofficially lasted 4 days, 23 hours and 41 minutes. The mission's
main purpose was launching Galileo, which scientists hope will find
clues to the formation of the universe and provide the best look
yet at another planet.
   About 20,000 people were at Edwards to watch the landing. The
crowd was small compared to past touchdowns because of the weekday
landing, officials said.
   About 45 minutes after landing, the astronauts emerged from the
shuttle and performed the traditional walkaround inspection with
NASA officials. The other crew members are pilot Mike McCulley, and
mission specialists Ellen Baker, Shannon Lucid and Franklin
Chang-Diaz.
   ``The vehicle looks amazingly clean,'' said William Lenoir, an
acting associate administrator of the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration. ``We did not see, with a quick inspection,
any significant tile damage _ a little nick here and a nick there.''
   The black tiles protect the shuttle during its fiery re-entry
into the atmosphere.
   Later in the afternoon, the astronauts left Edwards aboard two
Gulfstream jets for their home base in Houston.
   The crew members and their spouses arrived at Houston's
Ellington Field at about 6:30 p.m., where they were greeted by
their children and 300 cheering friends and co-workers.
   ``This is obviously one of the highest points in my life so
far,'' Williams told the crowd. ``It's super.''
   The astronauts have most of today off, but were expected to the
space center this afternoon to look over film they took during
their mission, said spokesman Jeff Carr. They return to work
Wednesday to begin a week of formal briefings about their flight.
   Atlantis will ride piggyback on a modified Boeing 747 for a
two-day trip to Cape Canaveral, Fla., this weekend.
   After deploying Galileo, the crew turned their attention to
several science and medical experiments, including one that
measured the Earth's protective ozone layer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0417EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Evangelist     10-24 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Evangelist,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Evangelist Tours Muddy Tent Encampment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATSONVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slogging through muddy tent
encampments teeming with earthquake refugees, evangelist Billy
Graham told frightened victims not to let their faith be rattled.
   ``I think we have to recognize that God is a god of love and he
doesn't allow a thing like this to happen without a purpose,'' the
preacher said while traveling by a Salvation Army sedan.
   ``I don't know what the purpose is. It's a mystery to me. I've
never figured out all these disasters from the biblical point of
view.''
   Watsonville Mayor Elizabeth Murphy met with Graham at the city's
disaster center, where the preacher led a brief prayer of thanks
for all the volunteers who have worked to salvage what remains of
the community.
   The mayor said she was pleased Graham came. ``We want to get
people in the churches. We feel it does a great deal to get another
power to help you out,'' she said.
   Salvation Army disaster Capt. Jeni Gregory described ``pockets
of misery'' in dozens of small tent cities sprinkled throughout
this agricultural community. She said there could be as many as
5,000 refugees, many of them homeless, but many just too frightened
to go back to their homes despite inspections declaring them safe.
   An agricultural community of 27,000, Watsonville is known as the
hub that produces much of the nation's lettuce and salad greens. It
took a big hit when the 6.9-magnitude quake struck a week ago
today. A total of 175 homes were destroyed, 930 homes were damaged,
17 commercial buildings were destroyed and 47 businesses sustained
damage.
   Residential damage was placed at $88 million, structural damage
to businesses at $34 million.
   Graham shook hands with dozens of people waiting for food Monday
in a pouring rain outside a Salvation Army distributiton center.
Many had only cardboard boxes for umbrellas and plastic food wrap
for raincoats.
   ``We appreciate you coming here,'' said Mario Guzman, 34.
   Later, Graham flew to Oakland where he gave the Salvation Army a
$100,000 check for earthquake relief and toured the site of the
collapsed Interstate 880.
   ``Yes sir, there's somebody up there that's stronger than we are
and stronger than anything we can build,'' the evangelist remarked
as he gazed up at the concrete rubble.
   He called the disaster ``almost an unbelievable thing,'' and
said ``it's a miracle to me there weren't more people killed than
there were.''
   Glancing at a nearby section of freeway deemed so dangerous it
must be leveled, Graham said: ``It makes me think of the Tower of
Babel and how it came crashing down.''
   But he said he did not mean to suggest the tragedy was God's
Judgment. ``These are natural disasters,'' Graham said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0418EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FBI-Spy     10-24 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FBI-Spy,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former FBI Agent Being Released on Bail While Awaiting Spy Retrial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former FBI agent Richard Miller, imprisoned
since 1986, won permission for his release on $357,000 bail while
he awaits a new trial on charges he handed over secrets to his
Soviet lover.
   U.S. District Judge David Kenyon set bail on the order of the
9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which ruled that Miller had not
been shown to be a flight risk.
   ``The spirit of the order of the appeals court is that they
directed this court to set a bond that Mr. Miller can meet,''
Kenyon said at a hearing Monday.
   Miller was ordered returned to Los Angeles from the federal
prison in Rochester, Minn., while papers are processed for his
release.
   His brother, sister and a friend agreed to post property worth
$357,757 to assure his appearance at court proceedings. Kenyon did
not require that any cash be posted.
   ``We're pleased that he will be getting out,'' defense attorney
Stanley Greenberg said outside court. ``It's a little later than we
would have liked. But better late than never.''
   Kenyon scheduled a hearing for Monday to determine when Miller's
third espionage trial will be held. The first jury deadlocked in
1985. A second jury convicted him in June 1986, and Kenyon
sentenced him to two life terms plus 50 years.
   Miller's conviction was reversed in April on grounds that jurors
were allowed to hear too much about lie detector tests that Miller
failed.
   Kenyon at first refused to allow Miller's release on bail,
saying he might flee. But the appeals court disagreed.
   The corpulent Miller, who battled the FBI over his weight and
other problems during a lackluster 20-year career with the agency,
was depicted by prosecutors at his trial as a bitter, vengeful
failure easily recruited as a Soviet spy.
   His attorneys said Miller was a well-meaning FBI misfit who
dreamed of redeeming his career by infiltrating a Soviet spy
network.
   Among those who testified against him was a co-defendant,
Svetlana Ogorodnikov, who became his lover and allegedly enticed
him into spying. Mrs. Ogorodnikov and her husband, Nikolay, pleaded
guilty to spying and are serving prison terms.
   Miller was excommunicated by the Mormon church. His wife, Paula,
divorced him following his conviction and has since remarried. She
was last reported living in the Philippines. Some of their eight
children continue to live with their mother, Greenberg said, and at
least two are on Mormon missions overseas.
   Under terms of his release, Miller would be placed in the
custody of Albert Sayers, a former FBI agent and private
investigator who worked on the defense.
   Miller also will be forbidden to leave the Los Angeles area
without permission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0418EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DrugCzar-Hollywood     10-24 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Czar-Hollywood,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Urges More Anti-Drug Messages in TV Programming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug czar William Bennett urged TV
industry leaders to incorporate more anti-drug messages into their
programming, and called drug abuse a graver catastrophe than the
Northern California earthquake.
   ``While Santa Cruz was the epicenter of that disaster ... Los
Angeles is the epicenter of a social disaster _ drugs,'' Bennett
told members of the Academy of Television Arts &amp; Sciences.
   Bennett, director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy,
told a group of studio executives they should help fight the war on
drugs by sending anti-drug messages to their viewers.
   ``It seems to me we can do better than Pablum ... and better
than good entertainment,'' he said Monday. ``I am not the cultural
commissar. It is your business to decide what is on your shows.''
   He said progress has been made in the depiction of drugs on
television and in movies, with illegal substances being portrayed
unfavorably.
   He also praised the efforts of Hollywood to set an example of
``chic sobriety,'' but said that for every glamour capital ``there
is a Watts.''
   Following his speech, Bennett was asked by entertainer Ben
Vereen if he believed anti-drug messages delivered by former drug
abusers were sending mixed messages to children. Vereen is a former
drug abuser who recently has visited elementary schools to urge
pupils to stay off drugs.
   ``I think kids need to hear what hell has been like,'' Bennett
said. ``But they also need to hear from people who have never used
drugs.''
</TEXT>
