<DOCNO> AP891024-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0419EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Honduras-Crash     10-24 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honduras-Crash,0764</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Say Severe Downdraft May Have Caused Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators are looking at
atmospheric turbulence during the difficult approach to
Tegucigalpa's airport as a possible cause of a plane crash that
killed 131 people, sources close to the probe say.
   Some sources say an atmospheric phenomenon called a ``rolling
wave,'' which can occur when wind whistles over mountains, could
have created a severe downdraft or turbulence that left the plane
1,800 feet below its assigned altitude before Saturday's crash.
   Co-pilot Reiniero Canales, in an interview on Honduran radio,
said the Boeing 727 was making a normal approach on instruments
through clouds when, ``Suddenly we hit something. It was all so
fast we didn't have time to react.''
   The crash of TAN-SAHSA Flight 414, which originated in San Jose,
Costa Rica with a stopover in Managua, Nicaragua, killed 131 people
and left 15 survivors, including pilot and co-pilot.
   The U.S. Embassy said 12 Americans were presumed dead; the three
American survivors have been airlifted to hospitals in the United
States and all are expected to survive.
   Investigators questioned tower and air control workers and made
an aerial survey of the crash site Monday.
   The site, heavily damaged by looters, was cleared late Monday to
allow inspection by a team from the National Transportation Safety
Board, Boeing Co. and Pratt &amp; Whitney, the engine manufacturer.
   The investigators also planned to question the crew of the last
previous plane to land at Tegucigalpa to see if they also
experienced turbulence.
   Barry Trotter, leader of the U.S. team, emphasized that he was
in Honduras to assist the Hondurans in conducting the investigation.
   ``They are giving us every facility to help them,'' he said.
   Relatives of the dead continued to gather at the morgue as
forensic experts tried to identify charred corpses. The Sandinista
Air Force sent a plane to pick up the bodies of Nicaraguan victims.
   Relatives also pored over the wreckage as the search for remains
continued. One man burst into tears when he found a photo of wife.
   The Honduran Minister of Defense, Col. Wilfredo Sanchez, looking
gaunt and unshaven, was at the site for a second straight day
searching for his daughter Fanny's personal effects.
   ``I'm not here to direct. I'm just looking,'' he said, clicking
a set of charred keys in his hands.
   When Sanchez, whose son was killed in an air force accident last
year, spotted a suspected looter he grabbed the man and ordered
police to get him ``out of my sight.''
   Col. Marco Tulio Rivera, head of the Honduran Civil Aeronautics
Authority, said pilot Raul Argueta radioed the tower at 7:52 a.m.
that he was at 7,500 feet seven miles from the airport, precisely
on target.
   The pilot was supposed to descend to 6,700 feet at the five-mile
mark, 1,800 feet above the 4,900-foot Cerro de Hule.
   ``What happened in those last few seconds is what we have to
figure out,'' said Rivera, who added that Argueta had not yet been
interviewed because of his injuries.
   Sources familiar with the investigation, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said other causes being looked at included possible
engine failure or a false altimeter reading.
   Rivera said it was unlikely that a piece of the plane's roof
might have blown off, as happened to an Aloha Air jet over Hawaii
in 1988.
   A Boeing Co. spokesman said the plane, which was leased from
Contiental Airlines, had taken off and landed 52,019 times, about
average for a 21-year-old plane. A high number of takeoff-anding
``cycles'' has sometimes been seen as a factor in accidents caused
by metal fatigue.
   Sources said repeated accounts of severe turbulence before the
crash jibed with the theory of a ``rolling wave'' downdraft.
   They explained that the 50 mph wind flowing south over the Cerro
de Hule would follow the contour of the land until it hit another
mountain behind the Cerro. The wind could then be pushed up and
over itself, turning in violent eddies that cause an airplane to
lose lift and drop thousands of feet in seconds.
   The approach to Tegucigalpa is notorious among veteran Central
American travelers because the airport is set at the bottom of a
ring of mountains, as if it were at the bottom of a soup bowl, and
the mountains are frequently obscured by racing clouds.
   ``It's a pretty hairy approach,'' said one source familiar with
the probe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0422EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChildRape     10-24 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Rape,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sets Trial Date for Boys Accused of Raping 12-Year-Old Girl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YPSILANTI, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7-year-old boy, slumping in a chair
and holding his mother's hand, was ordered to stand trial on a rape
charge in an attack on a 12-year-old girl.
   The 7 year old and two 12-year-old boys, all from Ypsilanti,
face one count each of first-degree criminal sexual conduct
involving accomplices, Assistant Prosecutor John Stanowski said
Monday after Probate Judge John Kirkendall set Nov. 22 as the trial
date.
   Two other defendants, boys ages 7 and 9, didn't appear at their
arraignment last week and were being sought, said the Washtenaw
County assistant prosecutor.
   ``This is not sexual experimentation between two young people of
the opposite sex,'' Stanowski said. ``This is a gang-type offense.
Two were holding her down while the third one ... knew the private
areas of a woman and was fondling and molesting her.
   ``I was aghast that kids that age were involved,'' Stanowski
said.
   Robert Reizner, a lawyer for the 7 year old, said his client was
too young to face charges.
   ``There is a common-law presumption that children under the age
of 6 are conclusively presumed not to be able to have any criminal
intent,'' Reizner said. ``This child at the time of the alleged
event was maybe a month and a half over (7 years old).''
   The attack occurred July 16, authorities said. The girl was
knocked down and kicked in the head, Stanowski said. During the
attack, the girl's 11-year-old cousin tried to stop the boys, but
they ``fended her off,'' Stanowski said.
   ``If these kids were adults they would be facing life,''
Stanowski said. ``Because they are juveniles ... there's a whole
different avenue the court may take as far as the disposition.''
   Stanowski said the boys could be put on probation and ordered to
undergo counseling, placed in foster homes or assigned to
in-patient mental health care if they are convicted.
   Stanowski said one of the 12-year-old boys also is charged with
assault with a dangerous weapon in a knife attack on the same girl
in August.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0424EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Shevardnadze-Excerpts     10-24 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shevardnadze-Excerpts,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Excerpts from Shevardnadze's Speech</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Shevardnadze, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze's speech Monday to the Supreme Soviet, as
translated by The Associated Press:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   RADAR STATION
   The power of perestroika does not in itself insure us against
mistakes. It's important not to hide them, to admit them and
correct them.
   In this respect, the Krasnoyarsk radar installation issue is
very significant. It took us four years to get to the bottom of it.
   We were charged with violation of the ABM treaty because of the
station. It took the government quite a while to learn all the
truth of the project. Finally, we saw it clearly: The station had
been built on the wrong site, not where it should have been.
   All these years, we have been working hard to keep up the ABM
treaty as a foundation for strategic stability. We have been
looking for options and having very complicated debates on the
interpretation of each article of the treaty and its supplements'
contents.
   And all the while, there stood the station, the size of an
Egyptian pyramid, representing, to put it bluntly, a violation of
the ABM treaty.
   At last we resolved this issue and announced we would dismantle
the station. This has brought some discontent in the country, as if
we were forgoing our own interests.
   In fact, we are saving the ABM treaty and opening the way to the
conclusion of the treaty on strategic weapons, and we're gaining
the legal and moral right to demand clarity on the question of
American installations in Greenland and England which were
modernized, we understand, in violation of the treaty.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WARSAW PACT COUNTRIES
   Here, there have been historic, qualitative changes. We are
building our relations with them on the basis of sovereign
equality, the impermissibility of any intervention and the
recognition of each country's absolute freedom of choice.
   And here is where Soviet diplomacy faces the deepest
restructuring in essence, methods and style.
   In some of them, new, alternative forces are entering the
political arena. No one is leading them there. They are coming
because that's what the people want. And these states do not cease
to be our neighbors, our allies, our friends. All our obligations
remain in force.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AFGHANISTAN
   When more than 100 U.N. members for a number of years were
condemning our action, what other evidence did we need to realize
that we had set ourselves against all of humanity, violated norms
of behavior, ignored universal human values?
   I am referring of course to our military engagement in
Afghanistan. It should teach us a lesson that in this case, gross
violations of our own laws, intraparty and civil norms and ethics
were allowed.
   At the time I am speaking about, M.S. Gorbachev and I were
candidate (non-voting) members of the Politburo. I found out about
what had happened from radio and newspaper reports. A decision that
had very serious consequences for our country was made behind the
back of the party and the people. We were confronted with a fait
accompli.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MILITARY WITHDRAWAL
   For the first time in many years, not a single Soviet soldier is
participating _ nor, I'm sure, will participate _ in military
actions anywhere in the world.
   We have now put forth the initiative of curtailing all of our
military bases abroad as well as our military presence there by the
year 2000. We are prepared to head toward the dissolution of the
military-political blocs in Europe on a mutual basis.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HUMAN RIGHTS
   It's shameful to admit that, not long ago, we would say,
``so-called human rights,'' and claimed we didn't have any problems
with them.
   In the addressing and solving of humanitarian issues, we have
made a genuine, psychological, political, legal breakthrough, and
reached world standards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0427EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BoyLost     10-24 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boy Lost,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Searchers Hunt for Boy in Cold, Stormy Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHEMULT, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of searchers hunted in cold, snowy
weather for a 9-year-old boy lost since Sunday with his horse in
the central Oregon canyons.
   Melvin Bundy, a spokesman for the Klamath County search and
rescue unit, said darkness and the poor weather forced 70 people to
temporarily stop their search Monday night, but an expanded,
helicopter-aided search was planned for today.
   Nathan Madsen was reported missing by his family Sunday
afternoon after he disappeared during a cattle roundup, said Chuck
Hoy, a spokesman for the rescue unit.
   Hoy said searchers were growing increasingly worried about the
boy as the weather deteriorated late Monday afternoon. The cold,
wet conditions posed an extreme danger of exposure to the boy, he
said.
   ``It's getting scary now,'' he said. ``It's snowing like the
devil.''
   Hoy said searchers spent a second night in the rugged timberland
along the Little Deschutes River north of Chemult, which is 160
miles south-southwest of Portland.
   Hoy said rain and sleet that fell late Sunday and early Monday
had erased any tracks searchers might have followed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0430EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PolishPressProtestsLithuania'sTravelRestriction     10-24
0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>Polish Press Protests Lithuania's Travel Restriction</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland's press is condemning Lithuania's
decision to restrict travel to the Soviet Baltic republic by Poles,
many of whom have been buying up precious goods there and shipping
them home.
   Polish newspapers said the move was political. Monday's editions
of the communist youth newspaper Sztandar Mlodych called the
decision ``a kind of political schizophrenia.''
   The dispute, while economic in origin, underscores how the
decline of strict Communist Party control in Eastern Europe is
allowing long-repressed nationalist tensions to emerge.
   On Friday, Lithuania restricted Poles and other East bloc
residents to one visit a year, specified that currency be changed
to rubles when entering the republic, cut train service from
Vilnius and Warsaw to one daily and prohibited visitors from
mailing home parcels.
   The measures were to prevent scarce goods in Lithuania from
being bought out by visitors. In the Soviet Union, goods from
school composition books to meat are in short supply because of the
country's economic difficulties.
   Many Poles, themselves in the throes of economic crisis, are
expert at finding goods in neighboring countries that can be bought
cheaply and sold at home or in other Warsaw Pact nations.
   The pro-Solidarity newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza ran a dispatch on
the restrictions under the headline, ``Stop Tourist.''
   Sztandar Mlodych said, ``Erecting at our borders more and more
obstructive barriers ... represents a kind of political
schizophrenia.''
   The newspaper said the decision clearly was directed at Poland.
The rules about parcels and train service mention Poland
specifically and the number of visitors from all other East bloc
countries together is less than half the number from Poland
annually.
   The histories of the East bloc neighbors are closely connected
and the two are at the forefront of change in the Communist world.
   In the past year, the Solidarity movement in Poland and the
Sajudis movement in Lithuania have supported one another in their
parallel efforts to increase independence from Moscow.
   In the past, Poles have expressed concern about the treatment of
the ethnic Polish minority in Lithuania.
   The Soviet republic holds bitter memories of historic Polish
dominance, including a 1920 invasion in which Poland seized
Lithuania's capital of Vilnius and held it until 1939.
   About 8 percent of Lithuania's 3.5 million population are ethnic
Poles. Poland and Lithuania were allied from the 14th century
through the Jagiellonian dynasty, then formed a commonwealth from
1569 until 1795 when Lithuania and most of Poland succumbed to
Russian rule.
   Over the centuries, the gentry in Lithuanian became
Polish-speaking while the peasantry spoke Lithuanian, the country's
native language.
   In the late 19th century, a Lithuanian nationalist movement
emerged to fight Polish cultural and Russian political domination.
   In September 1939, both Lithuania and eastern Poland were
occupied by the Soviet Union. Poland regained statehood after World
War II, but Lithuania remained a Soviet republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0431EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Reagan     10-24 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reagan,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Tosses First Ball of Japan Series Game</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A capacity crowd of 56,000 cheered today as former
President Reagan tossed the first pitch of the third game of
Japan's version of the World Series, narrowly missing a Kintetsu
Buffaloes batter.
   Winding up about halfway between home plate and the pitcher's
mound, Reagan, a former sportscaster, fired off a throw that barely
cleared batter Daijiro Ohishi's backside.
   Reagan, wearing a blue suit, laughed and waved to the crowd.
Some people chanted, ``Reagan, Reagan.''
   The former presideint is in Japan on a nine-day visit at the
invitation of the Japanese government and Japan's largest media
conglomerate, Fujisankei Communications Group.
   Fujisankei reportedly is spending about $7 million on the trip,
which aims at improving ties between the United States and Japan.
Fujisankei officials have refused comment on reports Reagan and his
wife Nancy will earn $2 million.
   On Monday, Reagan met with Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu and
Emperor Akihito. He received one of Japan's highest awards, the
Grand Cordon of the Supreme Order of the Chrysanthemum, for
promoting free trade and friendship.
   As Reagan entered the field at the Tokyo Dome for the Japan
Series game between the Yomiuri Giants and Kintetsu Buffaloes, an
announcer asked the audience to make donations to victims of last
week's San Francisco earthquake ``to promote U.S.-Japanese
relations.''
   The temblor, which measured 6.9 on the Richter scale, struck
shortly before the scheduled start of the third game of the World
Series in San Francisco. At least 60 people were killed and damage
is estimated at $7 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0434EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Lithuania     10-24 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Lithuania,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Press Protest Travel Restrictions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0476 to RESTORE slugline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
