<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0446EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Legislature     10-24 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Legislature,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Session Planned to Consider Earthquake Relief</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special legislative session will be called
in the next 14 days to evaluate earthquake damage and arrange for
relief that could include a temporary increase in sales or gasoline
taxes, the governor said.
   After meeting with top lawmakers for 90 minutes Monday,
Deukmejian said: ``We certainly did discuss that,'' referring to
the tax increases.
   ``The final decision on that will depend in large part on the
extent of the damages together with the expected action of the
federal government,'' he said.
   The earthquake struck the San Francisco Bay area a week ago
today, killing dozens, injuring thousands and causing up to $7
billion damage.
   The governor said he would meet with Assembly Speaker Willie
Brown and Senate Majority leader David Roberti, both Democrats;
Senate Minority Leader Ken Maddy and Assembly Minority Leader Ross
Johnson next Monday to try to put together a special session agenda.
   The Appropriations Committee of the U.S. House of
Representatives approved a $2.85 billion aid package Monday _ $1
billion less than the amount sought by California's congressional
delegation.
   The governor said he and legislative leaders discussed the
possibility of holding an earlier, special election to consider a
ballot measure currently slated for June 1990. That proposal would
liberalize the state's spending limit and pave the way for a
gradual 9-cent gasoline tax increase.
   But he said no decision had been made on that question.
   The state temporarily raised the gasoline tax twice during the
1960s to repair roads damaged by storms and floods, but legislative
leaders said they would prefer a sales-tax boost.
   Brown said it would take a large increase in the gasoline tax to
generate the same amount of money that a 1-cent sales tax increase
would provide.
   Johnson said he might support the idea of a standby tax increase
that would be triggered if officials determined at a later date
that the funds were needed.
   Johnson also criticized the idea of moving up the election on
the spending limit-gasoline tax measure, saying legislators and the
governor might need all the time available to convince voters to
approve the proposal.
   The Legislature completed its 1989 session on Sept. 16 and is
not due to return to the Capitol until January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
