<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0529EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Radicals     10-24 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Radicals,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Radicals Convicted In Deaths of Seven Riot Troopers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today convicted 71 radical
students in connection with the burning death of seven policemen
and relatives of the dead troopers and of the defendants scuffled
in the courtroom.
   About 2,000 riot policemen were deployed around the District
Criminal Court in southern Pusan as the convictions and sentences
were read to the students, all from Pusan's Donghui University,
where the troopers were killed.
   Angry relatives of the dead policemen protested when students
were not sentenced to death. Relatives of the students and of the
troopers pushed and shoved and traded insults after the sentencing.
   Some defendants left the hearing before sentencing, saying they
didn't care about the penalty. They said police commanders were
responsible for the deaths because they ordered a raid on the
campus.
   As the judge began reading the verdicts, students in the gallery
sang dissident songs and shouted ``Clarify the truth.''
   Of the 71 students, one was sentenced to life in prison, three
received 15 years in prison and 31 others received sentences
ranging from one to 13 years. The remaining 36 received suspended
sentences.
   Both prosecution and defense lawyers said they would appeal the
sentences. People convicted of murder in South Korea can be
sentenced to death by hanging, but Judge Kim Myung-kil said the
students appeared not to have intended to kill anyone.
   Seven riot troopers were burned to death at Donghui University
during a campus battle. The troopers were trying to rescue five
police officers held hostage by radical students.
   Students set fire to a barricade drenched in paint thinner as
the troopers climbed over it. Several officers, wrapped in flames,
leaped from windows while others were burned to death or choked to
death by smoke. One student was critically injured.
   The deaths shocked South Koreans and the government ordered a
crackdown on radical students and dissidents to halt violent
protests. The radicals, who want the overthrow of the government
and removal of U.S. troops from South Korea, have little support
among the people because of their violent tactics.
   The prosecution had demanded the death penalty for three
students they said led the violence.
   ``We refuse trial!'' shouted the defendants as they arrived at
the courtroom. When some students defiantly refused to leave the
buses, they were dragged off by prison guards.
</TEXT>
