<FIRST>r p PM-NYCPolitics     10-24 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Politics,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polls Show Dinkins Support Slipping in Bid for NYC Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New polls show support for Democrat mayoral
candidate David Dinkins has eroded, and one survey put his lead
over Republican Rudolph Giuliani at only 4 points.
   Less than two weeks ago, a poll showed Dinkins leading Guiliani
by 19 points.
   Political analysts said Dinkins' apparent loss of support may be
due to controversy last week about the handling of his finances,
including discrepancies in the stated value of stock he transferred
to his son. The issue rekindled questions about Dinkins' failure to
pay taxes from 1969 to 1973.
   In a poll of 501 registered voters conducted Sunday for the
Daily News and WABC-TV and released Monday, 45 percent picked
Dinkins, compared with 41 percent for Giuliani. The survey's margin
of error was plus or minus 5 percentage points.
   Less than two weeks earlier, a Daily News-WABC-TV poll showed
Dinkins with 53 percent to Giuliani's 34 percent.
   The survey indicated that the biggest shift occurred among
Jewish voters, who last week favored Dinkins by 10 points. Now, 44
percent of Jewish voters supported Giuliani and 26 percent
supported Dinkins. Twenty-six percent of Jewish voters were
undecided.
   The election is scheduled for Nov. 7.
   Asked at a campaign stop to comment, Dinkins said he had
``anticipated there would be some fall-off, given the negative
campaigning of recent time.'' But he said he didn't put much stock
in the poll.
   ``I don't know that this barometer is an accurate one,'' he
said, noting that polls before the primary showed him and Mayor
Edward I. Koch neck-and-neck. Dinkins won the primary easily.
   A poll conducted for the weekly New York Observer found Dinkins'
support at 47 percent, compared with 27 percent for Giuliani and 25
percent undecided. The gap between the candidates had narrowed to
20 points from 33 points since the last Observer survey.
   Johnson-Singer Inc., which separately does polling for the
Dinkins campaign, telephoned 500 registered voters Friday through
Sunday for the Observer. The issue with the survey was due out
Wednesday.
   The polls were the first since the Sept. 12 Democratic primary
to show Dinkins' support at less than 50 percent.
   Independent pollster Lee Miringoff, head of the Marist Institute
of Public Opinion in Poughkeepsie, said the decline in support in
both polls showed that Dinkins had been hurt, but it remains to be
seen whether the damage will be lasting.
   Asked to comment on the polls, Guiliani said he believed
Dinkins' financial problems _ as well as the revelation that
Dinkins had paid $9,500 to convicted kidnapper Sonny Carson for a
get-out-the-vote drive before the primary _ has brought people to
his campaign, which had been close to running out of money in this
heavily Democratic city.
</TEXT>
