<FIRST>r a PM-SF-Quake-MossLanding     10-24 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF-Quake-Moss Landing,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Destroys Moss Landing Lab</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSS LANDING, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last week's earthquake destroyed the
Moss Landing Marine Laboratories, northern California's most
important oceanographic center.
   ``There really isn't any other place to go for blue ocean
oceanography, it was a world-class center,'' said James Kelly, dean
of science and professor of oceanography at San Francisco State
University.
   W. Ann Reynolds, chancellor of the California State University
system, said she has applied for disaster relief from the state and
federal governments to begin rebuilding.
   The loss, estimated at $8 million, included laboratories, a
library, electronic equipment and a museum.
   Moss Landing, 20 miles south of Santa Cruz and 100 miles south
of San Francisco, was used by researchers from six campuses _ San
Francisco, Hayward, San Jose, Stanislaus, Fresno and Sacramento.
   The nearest comparable laboratories are at the University of
California-Scripps Oceanographic Centers in San Diego and at the
University of Washington, neither of which do research off northern
California.
