<FIRST>r w PM-Barry-Poll     10-24 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barry-Poll,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: 54 Percent Think Mayor Should Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than half of District of Columbia
residents think Mayor Marion Barry should resign, according to a
new poll that finds Barry would lose badly in races against Jesse
Jackson and former police chief Maurice Turner.
   The poll, conducted for WRC-TV and radio station WKYS, found 54
percent of city residents believe the scandal-plagued Barry should
leave office. That figure is up from 41 percent who said in a
similar poll in February that Barry should resign.
   The random telephone survey of 508 adult residents earlier this
month found 35 percent believe Barry, reportedly the target of
ongoing federal investigations, should remain in office and 11
percent were undecided.
   The poll released Monday also showed Barry, who is running for a
fourth term next year, with weak support when matched one-on-one
against two of the key figures in the city's political picture.
   Asked to choose between Barry and Turner, 53 percent of the
residents chose Turner and 28 percent supported Barry, with 19
percent undecided. Turner has not formally announced his candidacy
but has been endorsed by the local Republican Party.
   Barry's support is even weaker when placed solely against
Jackson, who led 65-18 percent with the rest undecided. Jackson is
not running for mayor, but has been reported to be willing to enter
the race if Barry does not run.
   Barry leads the five announced Democratic candidates with 19
percent in the poll of residents. But the other four Democrats got
between 9 percent and 14 percent and 36 of the residents were
undecided when asked to pick among those candidates.
   The survey was conducted by Hitlin Research Associates Oct. 5
through Oct. 19 and had a margin of error was plus or minus 4.5
percentage points. It was not limited to registered voters.
   Barry has seen his political support erode since his friendship
was disclosed late last year with convicted drug dealer Charles
Lewis.
</TEXT>
