<HEAD>Two Guerrillas Killed by Israeli-Backed Militia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with second guerrilla body found;
Pickup 6th pvs, `No organization ... '</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli-backed militiamen shot and killed two
armed guerrillas during a firefight in Israel's self-declared
``security zone'' in south Lebanon, military sources said today.
   The gunbattle occurred late Monday when a post of the South
Lebanon Army militia came under a barrage of small artillery fire
near Kafr Hunah, 15 miles north of the Israeli border, the sources
said.
   ``SLA soldiers returned fire and a terrorist was killed. No SLA
forces were injured,'' said one source on condition of anonymity.
   The Israeli army sources said a reconaissance patrol found an
AK-47 assault rifle and an explosive charge near one guerrilla's
body.
   The patrol found a second body on a later sweep, the sources
said.
   They were unable to say if the victims were Palestinian or
Lebanese. Both Palestinian and Lebanese militias have attacked
Israeli soldiers and their militia allies in the Israeli-controlled
zone in south Lebanon.
   No organization has claimed responsibility for the attack on the
South Lebanon Army, which is trained, armed and financed by Israel.
   An Israeli army spokesman, who cannot be identified according to
regulations, said it is believed more guerrillas took part in the
clash but managed to escape. He said no Israeli troops were
involved.
   Foreign reports have said about 500 Israeli soldiers patrol the
2.5-to-12-mile-wide security zone together with the militia force
made up mostly of Lebanese Christians.
   Israel carved out the buffer zone to protect its northern border
against attack in June 1985 when it withdrew the bulk of its troops
from Lebanon after a three-year occupation.
