<HEAD>Rain, Snow Fall on West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fair weather prevailed across most of the nation early today,
while rain and snow brought signs of winter to the West.
   Snow advisories were in effect today for the northern and
southern Sierra Nevada and for the mountains of northeastern
California. At least 6 inches of snow fell Monday on parts of the
Sierra Nevada.
   The storm forced closure of state Highway 120 into Yosemite and
prompted the California Highway Patrol to require drivers to put
chains on their vehicle wheels when traveling on mountain roads,
including state Highways 80 and 50.
   The storm also encouraged eager skiers, said Marilyn Graham, an
operator for the Hyatt Lake Tahoe hotel.
   ``If there's a big storm like this, they naturally think it's
ski time,'' she said.
   Scattered showers and a few thunderstorms were expected today in
the San Francisco Bay area. On Monday heavy rain complicated the
area's cleanup from last week's earthquake.
   Strong and gusty winds also were over parts of the West, with 40
mph winds reported at Ontario, Ore., on Monday evening. A wind
advisory was in effect today for the Owens Valley of Southern
California.
   Elsewhere, sunny skies brightened the Plains and the Mississippi
Valley Monday. Temperatures warmed into the 70s and 80s, rising to
the 90s in parts of Texas.
   The high for the nation Monday was 92 degrees in Texas at
Laredo, Mineral Wells and San Angelo.
   Other reports at 3 a.m. EDT today:
