<FIRST>r i PM-Walesa-Chile     10-24 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walesa-Chile,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Cancels Chile Trip After Banned Labor Leaders Pardoned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said today
he canceled a trip to Chile after military President Augusto
Pinochet pardoned two banned union leaders the Polish union chief
had planned to meet.
   Walesa told reporters at Solidarity headquarters in the Baltic
port of Gdansk that his scheduled visit to Chile this week was no
longer necessary. He said there were more pressing problems in
Poland.
   The Solidarity leader said his visit to Chile would be
rescheduled.
   In a surprise move Monday, Gen. Pinochet pardoned Manuel Bustos
and Arturo Martinez just four days before Walesa was to arrive.
Walesa had called on Pinochet to free the union officials.
   The pardon permits the men to leave the provincial towns where
they have lived in internal exile for the past 404 days.
   Bustos and Martinez were sentenced last year to 541 days of
confinement for calling a 1987 general strike to protest the
Pinochet government. The army commander took power in a bloody 1973
military coup.
   Bustos is president of the United Worker's Central, the nation's
largest labor federation, and Martinez is the group's vice
president. The Central invited Walesa to Chile, where he had
planned to spend three days.
   Walesa was prohibited from traveling outside the country after
the Dec. 13, 1981 martial-law crackdown, but since the Solidarity
union was legalized again on April 17 he has made several trips
abroad.
   The Solidarity leader is scheduled to travel to Canada and the
United States in mid-November.
</TEXT>
