<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-Pennsylvania     10-24 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Pennsylvania,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Predict Victory for Abortion-Control Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the pro-choice and
anti-abortion factions are predicting that some form of tougher
abortion controls will be passed in the House.
   The House is expected to begin debate on the proposed controls
this afternoon.
   The debate follows setbacks for abortion opponents in Florida
and Illinois, where legislative committees defeated restrictive
proposals. National pro-choice and anti-abortion leaders have
viewed Pennsylvania as a key battleground since the U.S. Supreme
Court's Webster decision in July that gave states more authority to
regulate abortion issues.
   A proposal by Rep. Stephen Freind, the Legislature's leading
abortion opponent, would prohibit abortion after the 24th week of
pregnancy except under threat of ``substantial and irreversible
impairment of bodily function'' to the mother. Two doctors would
have to approve the abortion.
   The legislation also would prohibit abortions based on the
fetus' sex, require a 24-hour waiting period to obtain an abortion
and require women to inform their husbands if they plan to get an
abortion.
   Democratic Rep. Karen Ritter of Lehigh, who leads the pro-choice
caucus in the House, said her group needs to sway about 40 members
to defeat Freind's proposal.
   If Freind's proposal wins House approval, pro-choice lawmakers
plan to try to weaken the bill with 20 to 30 amendments on issues
ranging from restoration of unrestricted Medicaid funding to
removal of the 24-week ban.
   Ms. Ritter and Freind both said they expected some amendments to
pass, but he declined to say which ones might have a chance.
   Pro-choice groups plan to hold a candlelight vigil on the
Capitol steps today during the debate.
   The Senate is not expected to take up the abortion legislation
until the week of Nov. 13. Democratic Gov. Robert P. Casey supports
the House proposal.
</TEXT>
