<FIRST>r a PM-HerculesMurals     10-24 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hercules Murals,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speaker Changes Stance; `Hercules' Murals Will Stay in House for
Now</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Murals depicting Hercules that some
opponents consider pornographic will remain in the Washington
House, at least for now, after the House speaker decided to support
them.
   The Democratic speaker, Joe King, said recent attacks on
``obscene'' art by U.S. Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., helped change his
mind about the black, gray and white murals called ``Twelve Labors
of Hercules.''
   King, who opposed the pair of murals until earlier this year,
made a motion Monday in the House Executive Rules Committee to keep
them in the House chamber. The motion was approved on a vote of
3-2, and King said he expected the decision to stand.
   ``Helms really recast the way I look at this,'' he said. ``I'm
not for regulating free expression by censoring art. I think (art
censorship) raises really ominous threats and I was no longer
comfortable allowing the murals to come down.''
   The murals were put up in the House chamber in 1982, but they
were shrouded in draperies until July, when King ordered them
uncovered. The murals were scheduled to be removed in December
because some lawmakers complained they were inappropriate and even
pornographic.
   The creator of the murals, Michael Spafford, said he was
``shocked and extremely pleased'' by the turnaround and found
King's change of heart ``truly courageous.''
   The murals, which face each other across the top of the House
chamber, portray the mythological figure's performance of 12
labors, including the removal of Amazon queen Hyppolyta's girdle.
   One opponent of the murals, Republican state Rep. Mike Padden,
said he will continue to fight the art when the Legislature
reconvenes in January.
   Of the murals, he said: ``They appear to be numerous outlines in
black and white of people in various stages of copulation.''
   Spafford has denied any sexual content.
   Spafford, commissioned by the state to create the murals, said
he hoped he would now be allowed to complete his original plan for
a set of four.
</TEXT>
