<FIRST>r a PM-Children'sHealth     10-24 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children's Health,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pediatrics Chief Says Lack of Kids' Health Care a National Disgrace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One-third of the nation's poor youths lack proper
immunization against disease, said the American Academy of
Pediatrics' chief in urging that children's health issues become a
top national priority.
   To address what it considers a national crisis, the academy is
drafting federal legislation that would guarantee access to quality
health care for all children and pregnant women, even the
uninsured, academy President Dr. Donald Schiff said Monday at the
organization's 58th annual meeting.
   Schiff, a University of Colorado pediatrics professor in Denver,
cited other statistics as well to describe what he called ``a
national disgrace.'' They include:
   _One of every three poor children is not immunized by age 2
against measles, rubella (German measles) or mumps.
   _One of every 10 children under age 4 has not seen a physician
within the past year.
   _The nation's infant mortality rate is 22nd among western
industrial nations, and lags behind countries such as Singapore,
Spain and Hong Kong.
   As many as 16 million people through age 21 are without health
insurance, said Dr. Marvin Kolb, chairman of the AAP's Council on
Government Affairs.
   Marian Wright Edelman, founder of the Children's Defense Fund
and a nationally known lobbyist for children's issues, agreed that
the state of children's health is acute.
   ``We have a child emergency and crisis that's going to bring our
nation to its knees,'' she said in a keynote address to several
hundred pediatricians at the six-day meeting that ends Thursday..
   Ms. Edelman's group, a non-profit advocacy organization based in
Washington, D.C., is working with the academy to fine tune a $12
billion proposal aimed at guaranteeing access to quality health
care for all the nation's children and pregnant women.
   The proposed legislation would provide funds to improve
employer-based health insurance for covering employees and their
dependents.
   But more importantly, for uninsured children and pregnant women,
a parallel system would be created providing private health
insurance through a state-administered fund, Schiff said.
   The academy, a 37,000-member group based in Elk Grove Village,
Ill., is looking for a congressional sponsor and expects the
measure to be formally introduced early next year, Schiff said.
   Ms. Edelman blamed the ``crisis'' in health care for children in
part on Bush administration policies that favor such things as
bailing out the banking industry and lowering the capital gains tax
over funding child-care issues.
   To remain competitive with other industrialized countries that
stress health care for children, the United States must make a
similar commitment, Ms. Edelman said.
   ``It's not only inhumane,'' she said, ``it's bad fiscal policy
not to invest in child care.''
</TEXT>
