<FIRST>r a PM-MissingArtifacts     10-24 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missing Artifacts,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Investigating Missing American Indian Artifacts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI is investigating the disappearance of
American Indian artifacts from a museum and their possible sale to
collectors, museum officials and private dealers said.
   An inventory six months ago of Southwest Museum's 200,000 pieces
indicated more than 25 objects were missing from a storage area,
said Jerome Selmer, the museum's executive director.
   Selmer would not say what was missing or estimate the value of
the art. He said the FBI located several items that had yet to be
returned to the museum.
   An FBI official confirmed the agency was investigating because
stolen goods may have been moved between states. He provided no
other details.
   The museum near downtown Los Angeles has a highly regarded
collection of American Indian art, tools, clothing and other
artifacts.
   Dealers in New Mexico, a center of trading in Indian artworks,
said FBI agents showed them photographs of blankets, pots, baskets
and kachina dolls the agents said were from the museum.
   Malcolm Grimmer, co-owner of the Morningstar Gallery in Santa
Fe, N.M., was quoted by the Los Angeles Times today as saying he
almost bought a share of a stolen pot that the FBI later
confiscated from a friend.
   The friend, who Grimmer would not identify, paid $24,000 for the
pot earlier this year and did not know it was stolen, Grimmer said.
   The Southwest Museum was founded in 1907 by historian and
American Indian expert Charles Lummis.
</TEXT>
