<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0501 10-24 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0501,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Commander Rejects Peace Plan, But Other Christian Leaders
Favor It</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with pro-Aoun demonstration against
plan, Aoun comment, main Christian political party backs accord and main
Christian militia considers it. Pickup 15th graf `Lebanon's pro-Syrian...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young Christian followers of Gen. Michel
Aoun today burned tires and demonstrated in Lebanon's Christian
enclave against Parliament's peace plan that shifts political power
to the Moslem majority.
   However, the right-wing Phalange Party, the main Christian
political organization in Lebanon, declared support for the peace
plan worked out by Lebanese legislators during three weeks of
discussions in Taif, Saudi Arabia.
   The Lebanese forces, the main Christian militia, did not reject
the plan aimed at ending 14 years of civil war, saying it had
positive points.
   Aoun had ordered his 20,000 troops on alert, after he rejected
the peace plan because it does not include a clear timetable for
the withdrawal of Syria's 40,000 troops from Lebanon.
   Salim Hoss, head of the rival Moslem government, also must
approve the plan. He made no immediate comment, but senior aides
said on condition of anonymity that he supports the Taif accords.
   Smoke billowed from the burning tires as schools, banks,
government offices and other businesses closed, abiding by a strike
call by Aoun's Christian cabinet.
   About 10,000 youths, mainly students, demonstrated in Christian
east Beirut.
   ``We sacrifice our blood for the general!'' the demonstrators
chanted as many of them waved huge posters of the 54-year-old
Maronite Catholic soldier.
   ``Yes, yes to the general. No, no to Taif!'' the demonstrators
said as they headed to Aoun's headquarters at the bomb-ravaged
presidential palace in suburban Baabda, east of Beirut.
   Addressing the demonstrators, Aoun said the accord's wording of
a Syrian withdrawal ``is very vague, from now until eternity.''
   Moslems have argued that the Syrian presence was their only
guarantee that political reforms would occur.
   ``We don't want to give away our beloved land,'' Aoun said in
his 15-minute address. He has said the Lebanese people should vote
on the accord and offered to step down if they support the
parliamentary plan.
   The Phalange Party, in a statement published by the daily paper
As-Safir and other newspapers, called for a ``unified Christian
stand to pursue implementation of the Taif plan.''
   Phalangist leader George Saadeh, who also heads the Lebanese
Front alliance of right-wing Christian forces, was one of the
legislators who worked out the peace plan.
   The Lebanese forces, the main Christian militia in the civil
war, said it was holding contacts with Aoun and other Christian
leaders to formulate a ``unified Christian stand on the Taif
accord.''
   When Lebanon received independence in 1943, the majority
Christians were given a 6-to-5 advantage over Moslems in all
government posts. Moslems now make up more than 50 percent of the
nation's population.
   Lebanon's pro-Syrian Moslem and leftist militias have expressed
dissatisfaction with the peace plan, mainly for not giving them as
much power in running the nation's affairs as they had requested.
   The Progressive Socialist Party of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt
and the mainstream Shiite Moslem Amal militia called meetings to
formulate their stands on the accord.
   Jumblatt, Syria's main ally in Lebanon, said Monday he was not
happy with the accord but would accept it ``upon Syria's request.''
   Amal, headed by Nabih Berri, also rejected the plan because it
did not provide greater representation in parliament for the 1.2
million Shiites, Lebanon's largest single sect.
   Under the plan, the 99-seat chamber will be expanded to 108,
equally divided between Moslems and Christians. Amal had demanded
the number be increased to 128 and hoped to get most of the
additional seats.
   At least 930 people were killed and 2,744 wounded in six months
of fierce artillery duels between Aoun's forces and Syrian gunners
until an Arab League-sponsored cease-fire took hold Sept. 22.
   The latest outbreak began in March after Aoun blockaded illegal
militia-run ports and the Moslem-Syrian alliance responded by
shelling the Christian enclave.
</TEXT>
