<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Traffic 1stLd-Writethru a0480 10-24 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Traffic, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0480,665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to restore keyword line; Leads with 6 grafs to
Update with morning commute moving well, prompting concern good news will
prompt people did give up ferries, trains; BART sets record; Picks up 5th
graf pvs, ``Agnos said ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mayor: Commuters Must Cooperate 'Til Christmas to Ease Gridlock</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The San Francisco Bay area's 3 million
commuters must cooperate until Christmas with officials urging them
to use car pools or ride buses, trains or ferries to avoid
gridlock, Mayor Art Agnos says.
   ``So far it has been very smooth,'' said Agnos, who boarded an
FBI helicopter to get an aerial view of commuter traffic Monday
evening. ``There is congestion, but not anything that created
gridlock.''
   Despite foul weather, commuters got through without crippling
problems on the first full workday since the earthquake. The
California Highway Patrol reported more traffic congestion but
fewer accidents than normal.
   And early today, skies were clear and traffic on freeways and
bridges moving well, transit officials said, prompting a fear that
the good news may invite a return to normal driving patterns later
in the week.
   ``We are concerned. We can only wait and see what happens. If
every one went back to their normal routine, we would have the
gridlock everyone is talking about,'' Sgt. Lisa Homen of the Golden
Gate Transportation District, which manages the famous bridge, said
today.
   The Bay Area Rapid Transit system set a single-day record
Monday, with 261,901 passengers, 39 percent more than on the
previous Monday and a record for a single day.
   Agnos said some drivers were traveling alone _ something
Metropolitan Transportation Chairman Rod Diridon termed an
``anti-social act.''
   But the mayor said many others ``have obviously made a decision
to follow the advice'' to use alternative transportation while road
and bridge repairs are made.
   ``It's just a continuation of the extraordinary cooperation and
fantastic attitude'' of area residents, said Agnos, adding that
people have refrained from looting and strangers are helping one
another.
   ``The spirit and character of our city has never been brighter
than it is is today,'' he said. ``If people will maintain this
commitment, we're going to be in great shape.''
   Agnos also said several thousand commuters took advantage of the
quick addition of 14 ferries. Rough water on the bay made some
passengers seasick, but Agnos added the gale-like weather was
unusual and the ride wouldn't be that rough all the time.
   One ferry was turned back Monday because of rough waters,
authorities said. The Union Ferry Building, the terminus of many
ferries bound for San Francisco, was closed for an hour because of
high waves and the boats were diverted to a pier about a mile away.
   On a 6 a.m. ferry from Oakland to San Francisco, what should
have been a 30-minute crossing took 55 minutes through heavy swells
that occasionally washed over the deck of the boat.
   ``I've just been through hell, but heck, I have to admit I made
it through it,'' said passenger John Trowbridge, 27, of Alameda.
``It can only get better, this can't get much worse.''
   ``Everybody's just going to have to go into slow motion. That
includes all the bosses,'' said Karen Meyer, 42, of Oakland.
   The fleet of ferries was called into service to help make up for
the collapse of a section of the 8.5-mile double-deck San
Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge. A 50-foot section of the upper deck
fell like a trap door onto the lower deck during the quake,
knocking the bridge out of commission for at least four weeks.
   Without the 10-lane bridge, 65,000 rush-hour motorists had to
find other ways to and from work. About 260,000 cars use the bridge
daily.
   Extra subway trains and ferries can accommodate an additional
45,000 riders. Other bridges must handle the rest of the traffic
that normally crosses the bridge.
   On the Oakland side of the Bay Bridge, a 1\ mile section of
Interstate 880 collapsed.
   Other freeways also are devastated, including the Embarcadero
Freeway along the waterfront in San Francisco and a five-mile
stretch of Interstate 280 in San Francisco was closed.
</TEXT>
