<HEAD>DEA Agents Shoot, Kill Suspect In Midtown NYC Tourist Spot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `He was...' with one graf to UPDATE with identity
of dead man.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH NEFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Undercover federal agents shot and killed a
suspected drug dealer near St. Patrick's Cathedral after the man
drove off during a drug deal, authorities said.
   Monday evening's shooting occurred on a street in the middle of
Rockefeller Center less than 100 feet from Fifth Avenue after two
agents arranged to buy four pounds of cocaine from the suspect in a
car, said Drug Enforcement Administration spokeswoman Mary Cooper.
   Once the agents saw the cocaine, they signaled other agents, who
closed in, Cooper said. As the agents identified themselves, the
suspect began to speed off in his Mercedes-Benz, she said.
   One of the agents thrust his arm through a partly open window
and was dragged about 100 feet, the spokeswoman said.
   The agent fired two shots and rolled off the car into the
street, and another agent fired at least one shot, Cooper said.
   The suspect's car crashed into the back of a bus.
   More than 100 people watched as the suspect was handcuffed on
the ground next to the car, then treated for a bullet wound to the
chest. The suspect was unarmed, Cooper said.
   John Lowery, 23, of the Bronx was pronounced dead at Bellevue
Hospital, said Peter Schectman, a hospital administrator.
   The agent, wearing a jacket that said, ``Nobody Gives Me A Raw
Deal,'' suffered hand and knee injuries and was taken to Bellevue
Hospital, said a police spokesman, Sgt. Peter Berry. He later
returned to the shooting scene.
