<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1036EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ExxonSuit     10-24 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Suit,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Suit Alleges State Impeded Spill Response</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. has sued the state of
Alaska charging that cleanup of the nation's worst oil spill was
hindered because the state opposed the use of oil-dispersing
chemicals.
   A state official said Exxon was trying to rewrite history, and
that the state had approved the use of chemicals before the spill.
   Exxon said it will seek reimbursement from the state for cleanup
costs and damage claims that the company believes were worsened by
the state's conduct. No amounts were specified.
   The case, filed Monday in Anchorage Superior Court, is a
counterclaim to a lawsuit the state filed in August against Exxon
and Alyeska Pipeline Service Co., the industry consortium that
operates the trans-Alaska oil pipeline and the Valdez oil terminal.
   The state's lawsuit alleges that negligence was involved in the
March 24 wreck of the Exxon Valdez and the subsequent oil cleanup,
and that the oil industry misrepresented its ability to deal with a
major spill in Prince William Sound, which leads from Valdez to the
open sea.
   Exxon's counterclaim says immediate use of chemicals to break
oil into droplets was a key part of a spill contingency plan
approved by the state.
   Nevertheless, the suit alleges, the state persistently opposed
the use of chemical dispersants after the Exxon Valdez ran aground
and ripped its hull open, spilling nearly 11 million gallons of
crude oil.
   Dennis Kelso, the state Commissioner of Environmental
Conservation, said Monday that he had not examined the lawsuit, but
that it appeared to be an effort to mislead the public about what
he contends was a lack of oil industry preparedness for a major
spill.
   The state did not oppose the use of dispersants in the area
described by Exxon, Kelso said. He said the industry hadn't
stockpiled enough dispersants in south-central Alaska to do any
good.
   ``Exxon wasn't prepared to use (dispersants) and now they're
trying to rewrite the history of the spill and make it appear that
someone else was the problem,'' Kelso said.
   Before the spill, state and federal regulators agreed that at
the discretion of the Coast Guard, dispersants could be used in the
central part of Prince William Sound without further state
consultation, Exxon said.
   Kelso said the state did not renege on that agreement.
   The Coast Guard authorized use of the chemicals on the evening
of March 26, but by that time it was too dark to work, Exxon said.
During the night, a storm blew much of the oil out of the targeted
zone, the company said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
