<FIRST>r i PM-Austria-Czechoslovakia     10-24 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Austria-Czechoslovakia,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovak Premier Accuses Vienna Media Of Directing Demos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakian Premier Ladislav Adamec
today accused Austrian media of directing anti-government
demonstrations in his country and said a pro-democracy protest
planned for Saturday probably will be banned.
   Adamec said the Communist government in Prague, seen in the West
as one of eastern Europe's hard-liners, is open to criticism.
   ``But we expect honest treatment,'' he told reporters after
arriving on a two-day visit. ``We notice an absence of objectivity
in some of the reporting on Czechoslovakia.''
   In an interview with Austrian reporters before his visit, Adamec
accused Austria's government television of helping to organize
banned demonstrations in Prague.
   Asked by an Austrian television reporter to explain the comment,
Adamec said, ``I didn't say that exactly. But it's true that at a
series of demonstrations, directives have come from various media
in Vienna.''
   Over the past year, Austrian and West German television crews
have been beaten by riot police dispersing banned protests in an
apparent effort to curb their coverage. Their broadcasts can be
received in several parts of Czechoslovakia.
   Charter 77 and other independent groups have announced plans for
a peaceful demonstration Saturday to mark the 71st anniversary of
Czechoslovak independence.
   Adamec said he did not know whether the demonstration would be
permitted, but added, ``I doubt we would have reasons to approve
it.''
   Last year, 5,000 people who took part in a peaceful rally on the
Oct. 28 anniversary were dispersed by riot police using batons,
dogs, water cannon and tear gas.
   The Communist party daily Rude Pravo in Prague has already
warned that any protesters this year could face prosecution.
   Czechoslovakia's relations with Austria, fraught with tension
from the past centuries of Hapsburg domination of Bohemia, are
complicated today by Austrian criticism of Czechoslovakia's human
rights record.
   Austrian Chancellor Franz Vranitzky indicated after initial
talks with Adamec that Vienna hoped to focus on improving economic
and cultural ties during the current visit. The two men are also to
sign an agreement designed to address Austrian concern over the
safety of Czechoslovak nuclear reactors.
</TEXT>
