<HEAD>Newport Mansion Has Record Asking Price: $5.9 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A real estate firm that set a city record
last year by selling a mansion for $4.1 million is trying to beat
its own mark with an asking price of $5.9 million for a villa along
Millionaires' Row.
   ``Right now, the market is pretty good at the high end,'' said
Spencer Potter, a broker for the Boston-based firm LandVest.
   ``Outside of Boston we just sold a place for $2.5 million the
afternoon it went on the market. Of course, that's not typical. But
it only takes one buyer to make a market at this level,'' he said.
   The firm is trying to sell Fairholme, a Tudor-style villa next
to railroad magnate Cornelius Vanderbilt's former summer
``cottage,'' The Breakers.
   Fairholme was once owned by the sister of artist Georgia
O'Keeffe, and former President Kennedy visited occasionally to swim
in the heated pool when his back gave him trouble, Potter said. The
mansion is now owned by John and Chandler Maschek Jr. of Palm
Beach, Fla.
   ``The buyer will probably be someone self-made, with new money,
who wants to make a statement,'' Potter said.
   Last year, LandVest set a city record by selling Clarendon
Court, which is where socialite Martha ``Sunny'' von Bulow slipped
into a coma that her husband, Claus, was later acquitted of causing.
   The two mansions are within a few blocks of each other, along a
mile-long stretch of Newport known as Millionaires' Row.
