<FIRST>r a PM-PlantExplosion-MutualAid     10-24 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plant Explosion-Mutual Aid,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical Industries Mutual Aid Team Followed Similar Plant Explosions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Plant Explosion, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A large part of the emergency response to
an explosion at the Phillips Petroleum Co. plastics plant came from
the petrochemical industry.
   In addition to fire departments from Houston, Deer Park, LaPorte
and Pasadena, emergency crews rushed to the Phillips complex Monday
from other nearby chemical plants.
   They all are members of Channel Industries Mutual Aid, a group
of 96 chemical manufacturers and six communities formed in 1955
following a series of accidents and fires along the Houston Ship
Channel.
   In Texas City in April 1947, a freighter loaded with fertilizer
exploded at a dock, killing 512 people and injuring 4,000.
   The mutual aid group had been planning to use the Phillips plant
as a practice site for an emergency drill scheduled Nov. 8, said
Elizabeth Gonzalez, a deputy coordinator of the Pasadena Emergency
Management Office.
   ``It's an annual drill, and we were working on some of the areas
we identified as deficiencies in our 1988 drill ... elements of
triage and communications,'' she said. ``Needless to say, they're
working very well on all that now.''
