<FIRST>r i PM-Zambia     10-24 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zambia,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Little to Celebrate on 25th Independence Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA GOLDING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zambians glumly marked their 25th
independence anniversary today with little of the jubilation that
hailed the birth of what was black Africa's wealthiest nation.
   While it was a public holiday and bunting draped some streets of
Lusaka, the capital, there were no signs of open celebrations.
   President Kenneth Kaunda, who led the white-ruled British colony
of Northern Rhodesia to independence as black-governed Zambia on
Oct. 24, 1964, four months ago called for a low-key Silver Jubilee
to save his impoverished nation money.
   Instead, Kaunda watched sporting events, tribal drummers and
dancers and gymnastics at Independence Stadium here.
   Kaunda canceled lavish celebrations in June as part of a package
of International Monetary Fund-proposed economic reforms to salvage
his country's crippled economy.
   Kaunda at the time was forced to abandon a moderate home-grown
program and adopt more radical and unpopular measures including a
devaluation of the Kwacha currency, lifting of state-fixed price
controls and sharp increases in the cost of staple corn.
   All this meant severe belt-tightening for the nation's 7 million
people, whose living standards have plunged since they were
regarded the most prosperous black Africans at independence.
   Since the mid-1970s world prices of copper, which account for 90
percent of all export income, have plunged, spending on social
services has been axed, unemployment and inflation are at record
levels and urban crime is rampant.
   But on Monday night, in a nationwide television address, Kaunda
spoke optimistically about the future of his nation.
   ``I see a bright future for Zambia,'' he said. ``We have taken
very tough economic decisions. But there is no doubt in my mind
that these measures will yield results sooner rather than later.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
