<DOCNO> AP891024-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1113EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-NATO     10-24 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NATO,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Chiefs Meet to Discuss Nuclear Matters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VILAMOURA, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO defense chiefs today discussed
the Western alliance's nuclear needs in an era of reduced East-West
tensions.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and other ministers of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization began a two-day strategy session at
the Quinta do Lago resort on Portugal's southern coast.
   A Dutch official said Cheney and his aides described the U.S.
nuclear modernization effort as ``more in reaction to what the
Soviet Union is doing at this moment'' _ that despite an easing of
tensions the Soviets were building up some long-range nuclear
systems.
   The Dutch official, speaking on condition of anonymity, quoted
the Americans as saying Soviet reform has shown up in the field of
non-nuclear weapons but not on the strategic nuclear side.
   NATO's secretary-general, Manfred Woerner, opened the meeting by
talking about the ``good perspective'' on East-West arms controls
talks in Geneva and Vienna, according to this account. But he
cautioned that NATO governments should not reduce their military
budgets without any concrete results.
   The defense chiefs did not discuss a candid speech given a day
earlier by Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze, in which
he said a disputed Soviet radar station violated the U.S.-Soviet
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty and would be dismantled.
   He also told the Soviet legislature the Kremlin was willing to
negotiate the disbanding of the NATO and Soviet-led military
alliances in Europe.
   There was no immediate reaction to Shevardnadze's remarks. But
his speech was certain to be analyzed, at least informally, by
officials attending the meeting here.
   In advance of the talks, NATO officials said the ministers would
not make any key decisions on their nuclear forces.
   ``The nuclear affairs of the alliance are running along very
smoothly at this time,'' said a senior NATO official who demanded
anonymity.
   Even so, the ministers were considered likely to give their
aides the go-ahead for a detailed examination of the alliance's
nuclear role at a time of enormous changes in the Soviet Union and
Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
