<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-IRA     10-24 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-IRA,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bonn Seeks Extradition of Suspects in British Military Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has asked France to
extradite three suspected IRA terrorists accused of murder in
attacks on British military facilities in West Germany, a spokesman
for the Justice Ministry said today.
   Federal officials also are considering an extradition request
for two other jailed suspects in the bombings this past spring in
the northern cities of Hanover and Osnabrueck that left a British
officer dead, said ministry spokesman Stephan Wanner.
   Alexander Prechtel, spokesman for the federal prosecutor's
office in Karlsruhe, said in an interview that his office filed
charges in absentia against the five on Sept. 13 and asked Bonn to
seek extradition.
   The five are accused of murder and attempted murder, Prechtel
said.
   West Germany is party to a European accord on extradition that
binds nations to turn over criminal suspects to states seeking to
prosecute them.
   Wanner said the Bonn government had issued a formal request on
Oct. 12 for extradition from France of the three suspects jailed
there. Prechtel identified those three as: Pauline Drumm, 22;
Donagh Mary O'Kane, 29; and Patrick James Murrey, 46, all of
Ireland.
   Two other suspects in the bombings last June and July were
identified by Prechtel as Leonard Hardy, 28, and Donna Maguire, 23,
both jailed in Ireland.
   They are suspected in the bombing of a British Army barracks in
Osnabrueck on June 19 and a car-bombing in Hanover on July 2 that
killed British Army Sgt. Steven Smith.
   The IRA claimed responsibility for those attacks, as well as
several others against British military facilities in West Germany
over the past few months.
</TEXT>
