<FIRST>r a PM-PlantExplosion-Industry     10-24 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plant Explosion-Industry,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plastics Industry Might Feel Shock Wave From Fatal Explosion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Plant Explosion, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Phillips Petroleum Co. plant hit by
an enormous explosion and fire is the largest of its kind in the
nation and a lengthy shutdown could affect prices in the world
plastics industry, analysts say.
   Phillips' 800-acre Pasadena plant complex turns out more than 2
billion pounds of plastics per year, three-quarters of it
polyethylene. Phillips supplies up to 19 percent of the world's raw
polyethylene, and if its unit making that plastic is destroyed or
shut down for a while after Monday's explosion, manufacturers could
be affected.
   ``If the whole thing goes down, there are going to be shortages
all over the place,'' analyst Bill Kuhlke of DeWitt &amp; Co., a
Houston-based chemical consulting firm, told the Houston Chronicle.
   But, Dave Dryden, a spokesman at Phillips' Bartlesville, Okla.,
headquarters, said today: ``It's hard to say what the effect might
be on the industry. ... We're very early in the assessment (of
damages).
   ``There are thousands of different plastics,'' Dryden said.
``About a third of the world's plastics are made by Phillips or its
contractors.''
   Polyethylene is made from ethylene, a gas derived from natural
gas. Ethylene for the Pasadena plant comes by pipeline from a
Phillips plant in Sweeny. Phillips is spending $300 million to add
1.5 billion pounds per year of ethylene production at Sweeney.
   The polyethylene plant was to have increased production 15
percent in 1990.
   The high-density polyethylene comes out as milky, BB-sized
pellets that manufacturers shape into anything from motor oil
bottles, milk jugs, plastic bottle caps to industrial pipe and
shopping bags.
   Phillips also makes 500 million pounds annually of polypropylene
at the plant, using propylene gas as the base. That plastic's uses
include carpet fiber and films.
   Some industry observers said the effect of the plant's shutdown
will be tempered by a recent loosening of the plastics markets.
   ``Neither (polyethylene nor polypropylene) is nearly as tight as
it was a year ago,'' said Greg Derrick, Phillips' coordinator for
financial communications in Bartlesville.
   Consultant Earl Simpson with Bonner &amp; Moore Associates said the
Phillips explosion should allow a polyethylene price increase of
about 3 cents per pound. Stock on hand will only last about five
weeks, he said.
</TEXT>
