<HEAD>Pregnant Woman Killed, Husband Shot, Baby Saved</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to ADD couple's occupations, baby's gestation,
detective saying gunman may have mistaken couple for police, background
on couple. No pickup. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors performed an emergency Caesarean section
on a dying woman after police located her and her wounded husband
from the sound of sirens coming through the couple's open car
telephone.
   Carol Stuart, 33, a lawyer from Reading, died early today.
Hospital officials said she was 32 weeks pregnant and delivered a
live baby boy. They refused to release information this morning on
his condition, which earlier was listed as critical.
   Her 29-year-old husband, Charles, was in fair condition at
Boston City Hospital with a gunshot wound in the abdomen.
   Mrs. Stuart died at 3 a.m., about seven hours after she and her
husband were robbed and shot in their car by a man who accosted
them outside Brigham and Women's Hospital, police said.
   Police said they were able to locate the couple from the sound
of their sirens coming through the open cellular telephone Stuart
had used to call for help before he blacked out.
   Arthur Jones, a spokesman for Mayor Raymond L. Flynn, said the
Stuarts were leaving Brigham and Women's, where Mrs. Stuart had
just undergone a prenatal examination, when a man climbed into
their car and forced them to drive a short distance.
   Jones said the assailant robbed the couple of their watches and
other belongings, then shot them.
   At 10:40 p.m., Stuart contacted state police with his cellular
telephone.
   State Police dispatcher Gary McLaughlin managed to get a few
details from Stuart on the couple's location before Stuart blacked
out, Trooper Barbara Bennett said.
   Boston Police Deputy Superintendent Joseph Dunford said police
conducted a search by repeatedly turning their car sirens on and
off.
   The dispatcher was able to tell police when they neared the
Stuarts' car from the sound of the sirens coming through the
telephone.
   At 10:50 p.m., police and medical personnel found the Stuarts.
   Stuart was able to provide a ``sketchy'' description of the
attacker, Dunford said. No arrests were made.
   The gunman apparently thought Stuart was a police officer,
possibly because of the cellular phone in the car, Dunford said.
Before shooting the Stuarts, the gunman said, ``I think you're
Five-0,'' slang for police, Dunford said.
   Ted Kakas, owner of the fur store Stuart managed, said it was
the couple's first child and they had been attending a birthing
class before the shooting. The couple had just celebrated their
fourth wedding anniversary, he said.
</TEXT>
