<FIRST>u a PM-CocaineTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0487 10-24 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0487,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial of Americans Accused of Aiding Colombian Drug Lord to Go to
Jury</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with defense finishing closing
arguments. Picks up 7th graf pvs, ```There was ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense attorneys for five Americans
accused of conspiring with Carlos Lehder today called the Colombian
drug lord a ``bad dude'' but denied he had anything to do with the
defendants.
   Attorneys ended their final arguments and rebuttal this morning
in the so-called ``Son of Lehder'' trial after Raymond David, who
represents Donald Lady, 41, of Pomona, Calif., charged the
prosecution was grasping at straws.
   ``Carlos Lehder is a drug baron and bad dude, but I don't know
what he has to do with the people sitting over there at the
(defense) table,'' David said.
   Defense attorneys presented arguments Monday and today on behalf
of their clients: The accused were not part of the conspiracy that
the government alleges ran from 1974 to 1989, had withdrawn from
the conspiracy, committed crimes outside the statute of limitations
or were innocent.
   After the defense finished presenting its closing arguments
today, the judge was expected to instruct the jury so it could
begin deliberations.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Ernst Mueller told the jury, ``The
evidence shows only one thing _ that they are guilty as charged.''
   Frederick Mycock, who represents lawyer Barry Kane, 52, of
Hyannis, Mass., told the jury Monday that the government had failed
to prove with any credible witnesses that Kane was guilty.
   If Kane had flown cocaine as alleged in 1977, he withdrew from
the conspiracy, making the government unable to prosecute him
because of the 5-year statute of limitations. And, Mycock said,
there was not one all-encompassing conspiracy as alleged by the
government, but several conspiracies.
   Mueller tied each defendant to Lehder and his organization in
their roles as pilots of cocaine flights and distributors of the
drug.
   ``There was a common thread of importation and distribution,''
Mueller said.
   Lehder, 40, was convicted last year and sentenced to life in
prison without possibility of parole for running a massive
smuggling operation. The case grew out of an investigation that
followed Lehder's trial.
   Defense attorney Patrick Hallinan, who represents Thomas
Herington, 35, of Mill Valley, Calif., claimed the government
``reached down into the slime'' for witnesses.
   ``We don't have one solid piece of evidence except out of the
mouths of felons, liars and perjurers,'' said Hallinan.
   Kevin Sanders, who represents Sam Stewart of Anaheim, Calif.,
called his client a hero, a family man and a law-abiding citizen,
who was the victim of a government ``witch hunt.''
   Herington faces one count of conspiracy to distribute five
kilograms or more of cocaine. Kane, Stewart and Donald Lady, 41, of
Pomona, Calif., are accused of the conspiracy distribution count
and an additional charge of conspiracy to import cocaine.
   Jack Carlton Reed, 59, is charged with operating a continuing
criminal enterprise and conspiracy to distribute.
   If convicted, the men face possible sentences of 10 years to
life.
</TEXT>
