<HEAD>U.N. Rethinking Decision to Distribute Machetes in Tense Namibia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations, which is
distributing farm tools to thousands of recently returned refugees,
is rethinking a plan to hand out machetes because of the tense
political climate in Namibia.
   ``The decision to distribute machetes at this time, which could
be used as weapons, is under review,'' said U.N. spokesman Fred
Eckhard.
   The United Nations, which is monitoring Namibia's transition to
independence, repatriated more than 40,000 Namibians who fled
during the territory's 23-year bush war.
   The United Nations provides monthly food packets to the refugees
and has begun supplying them with the hoes and seed.
   Eckhard said the United Nations believed it would be unwise to
pass out the machetes prior to the pre-independence elections set
for Nov. 7-11.
   There has been sporadic election-related violence since
campaigning began in July.
   South Africa, which has ruled Namibia for 74 years, has not set
the date for independence, but it is expected to be early next year.
