<FIRST>r a PM-PrisonDisturbance     10-24 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prison Disturbance,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guards, Inmates Injured in Disturbance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGDON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inmates went on a rampage in one
cellblock of the State Correctional Institution and at least 29
staff members and 19 prisoners were injured.
   Inmates broke windows, destroyed furniture, set several small
fires and threw things Monday night in Cellblock A, which houses
280 of the Huntingdon facility's 2,000 inmates, said prison
spokesman Ed Mason.
   The incident began when an undetermined number of prisoners
refused to return to their cells after dinner, Mason said.
   Then, about 25 to 35 inmates began ``throwing just about
anything they could get their hands on'' as all guards left the
cellblock, he said.
   ``We don't think it was planned. We think it was a
spur-of-the-moment type thing,'' prison spokesman Steryl Grove said
today.
   Guards regained control of the cellblock by 9:25 p.m., Mason
said. The rest of the prison remained secure.
   Four inmates and 17 correctional officers were treated for minor
injuries at J.C. Blair Memorial Hospital and released, Grove said
today. One officer suffering a head injury and one inmate were
admitted in satisfactory condition, according to a nursing
supervisor who refused to give her name.
   Eleven other staff members and 12 inmates were treated inside
the prison, Grove said.
   Grove said he did not believe Monday's disturbance stemmed from
incidents that began Thursday, when an inmate broke a guard's jaw.
The inmate was placed in restrictive housing.
   Four others were placed in restrictive housing Friday after as
many as six inmates punched and kicked a guard, causing minor
injuries, Grove said.
   Friday afternoon, about 75 inmates gathered in the prison
control center and demanded to see two of the inmates in
restrictive housing, but prison officials refused.
</TEXT>
