<FIRST>r a PM-RiotTrial     10-24 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riot Trial,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Opens in Police Shooting That Touched Off Riot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection and legal wrangling resumed today
for the trial of a white Hispanic policeman who killed a black
motorcyclist, touching off three days of racial protests and
rioting.
   Colombian-born Miami officer William Lozano faces two
manslaughter counts in the Jan. 16 shooting of Clement Lloyd, 23,
who was being chased by police, and the death of his passenger,
Allan Blanchard, 24, who died of injuries suffered when the
motorcycle crashed.
   The slaying led to burning and looting in predominantly black
poor neighborhoods. One person was killed and 11 were wounded, and
13 structures burned down only days before the area was host of the
Super Bowl.
   Potential jurors passed two small groups of demonstrators on the
courthouse steps Monday. Black protesters carried signs with such
slogans as ``Stop Killing Black Men,'' while Hispanic
demonstrators, some of them relatives of Lozano, waved Colombia's
flag. One man was arrested when he tried to force his way past
police guarding the courthouse door.
   Inside, attorneys and spectators passed through two sets of
metal detectors and bags and briefcases were searched.
   Defense attorney Roy Black, seeking to have the trial moved,
listed for Dade Circuit Judge Joseph Farina the extraordinary
measures adopted by police worried about a violent reaction to the
trial. Police have bought 700 gas masks and made arrangements for
use of two armored personnel carriers.
   ``I can't remember any trial in which it was necessary to buy
armored personnnel carriers to prepare for it,'' Black said. ``We
can't prevent a riot, but we can ensure jurors are not worried
about it.''
   Four times in the 1980s, police slayings of black men or the
officers' subsequent acquittals have sparked racial violence in
Miami.
   Black said jurors in Miami might be afraid to acquit Lozano and
touch off new rioting.
   Prosecutor John Hogan said he was not concerned about the jurors.
   ``The test is not whether they have heard of the case, the test
is whether or not they can base a decision on the evidence in
court,'' he said. ``We've been able to get juries in other high
publicity cases here in Dade County.''
   Attorneys estimated it could take weeks before trial testimony
begins.
</TEXT>
