<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--OilSpill     10-24 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Oil Spill,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil From Wrecked Freighter Smears Fjord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fuel oil spilled by a wrecked Brazilian
freighter has fouled 12{ miles of coastline in western Norway's
Sognefjord, officials said Tuesday.
   About 40 volunteers and government workers began cleaning up the
mess with buckets and shovels Monday, said Odd Arne Follum, of the
National Pollution Control Board.
   Sticky sludge coated parts of the remote, sparsely populated
coast when the Mercantil Marica leaked up to 35,000 gallons of
heavy fuel oil on Monday. The ship ran aground and broke in two
during a storm near the fjord Saturday. All 35 aboard the ship were
rescued.
   Residents and a national association of bird watchers criticized
the government Tuesday for tardiness in dealing with the spill.
   Stormy weather hampered efforts to contain the slick, Follum
said.
   ``Most of it will be easy to clean, but it will take weeks,'' he
said. There has been little environmental damage, Follum said.
   A dozen salmon farms were protected from the slick by floating
barriers.
