<FIRST>u w PM-PrenatalCare 2ndLd-Writethru a0545 10-24 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prenatal Care, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0545,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Official Says Science Could Reduce Infant Deaths</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: CORRECTS ranking to 22nd in grafs 3, `There must,'' and 22,
Each year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Medical science has the means to reduce the
annual number of infant deaths by 10,000 in this country, a top
government health official said today.
   ``We must remove the barriers'' to early prenatal care, Dr.
James Mason, acting surgeon general and assistant secretary for
health in the Department of Health and Human Services, told the
House Select Committee on Children, Youth and Families.
   ``There must be an outreach for those people who are unlikely to
come in by themselves,'' Mason told the committee, which is
examining this country's ranking of 22nd among industrialized
nations in infant mortality.
   The Bush administration has proposed an expansion of Medicaid
eligibility for expectant mothers, he said, and a White House
commission on infant mortality is planning to introduce other
proposals in about two months.
   Lawmakers are looking at such solutions for the problem as more
efforts to consolidate social programs that deal with pregnant
women, a streamlined application system for various social
programs, and an aggressive outreach program though schools,
clinics and welfare agencies to get to women earlier.
   Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., chairman of the panel, questioned
the administration's sense of urgency if it knows that 10,000
infants could be saved yearly. He said there is an identifiable
population of high-risk pregnant women on the rolls of the Women
Infants and Children nutrition program.
   Mason said nearly 40,000 of the 4 million Americans born this
year will not live past their first birthday. An additional 400,000
will live but will be born with or develop chronic problems due to
inadequate care before birth.
   Expectant mothers who must rely on government-funded health
centers rarely get the uniform care private patients receive,
according to a report by the committee's minority staff released on
the eve of today's hearing.
   It said only 18 percent of the government-funded agencies offer
necessary prenatal services in the same facility. Of the 91 sites
surveyed in 10 states, only 38 percent reported offering prenatal
care.
   As a result, the care that a private patient may receive from
one clinic or physician _ pregnancy testing, family planning
consultation, nutrition counseling, delivery and post-partum care _
is scattered for poor women, the study said.
   The study is part of an effort by the committee to explore the
rise during the 1980s in infant mortality and infants with low
birth weight. The figures had fallen in the two previous decades.
   ``We are needlessly wasting hundreds of thousands of lives and
millions of dollars a year because of our failure to provide
adequate prenatal care to pregnant women,'' said Miller, D-Calif.,
chairman of the select committee.
   Miller said that in 1987, the low birth weight rate in the
United States rose to 6.9 percent, the highest level since 1979.
   Each year, 300,000 babies die or are born with low birth weight,
and the U.S. Public Health Service ranks the United States last
among 22 developed nations in infant mortality rates, Miller said.
   He said the committee wants to learn about barriers to adequate
care and ``social problems that have compounded the crisis.'' Among
those are AIDS, drug abuse and the transmission of syphilis to
children because of increased trading of sex for drugs.
   A key issue is the growing number of teen-age mothers who,
according to government figures, have a disproportionate share of
babies with low birth weight and infant deaths. Only 53 percent of
teen-agers receive care in the first three months of pregnancy, the
government reported.
   The centers surveyed were in Alabama, Arkansas, California,
Colorado, Iowa, Maine, New York, Ohio, Virginia and Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
