<FIRST>r a AM-CrashSurvivors     10-24 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash Survivors,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flight 232 Survivors Form Support Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several Denver-area residents who survived the
crash of United Airlines Flight 232 in Sioux City, Iowa, in July
are organizing a support group to help one another cope with
lingering emotional trauma.
   ``For me, talking to other survivors is probably the most
valuable thing as far as therapy,'' said Jerry Schemmel.
   ``You can talk to counselors, your wife, your family, but when
you sit down in front of another person who went through the same
thing you did, you know that person relates exactly to what you're
talking about.''
   Schemmel, 29, is one of 184 people who survived the crash of
Flight 232 on July 19. The airplane cartwheeled and crashed just
short of an airport landing strip en route from Denver to Chicago,
killing 112 people.
   The victims included Schemmel's colleague and friend Jay
Ramsdell, 25, commissioner of the Denver-based Continental
Basketball Association. Ramsdell was seated about 10 rows behind
Schemmel.
   ``I had one week that was particularly tough for me,'' said
Schemmel, who now serves as acting CBA commissioner. ``It was
described by a therapist as post-traumatic depression. Then I got a
call from another survivor, Garry Priest, and the discussion just
completely picked me up.
   ``Being able to relate to the others opens things up for me. You
tell the survivors things you wouldn't even tell a therapist.''
   Kate Wolfe Bressieux, 35, another survivor, said she hopes the
support group will help ``normalize what we're going through.''
   ``There are very few people who have survived a plane crash, and
nobody can really understand it unless they've shared that
experience. I hope the support group will facilitate the healing
process,'' she said.
</TEXT>
