<SECOND>PM-Sex Case, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0497,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor, Wife Plead Guilty in Sex `Research' Prostitution Scheme</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to include judge's first name; picks up 4th graf
pvs, `The Woods... Note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES E. BEGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EUGENE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doctor and his wife pleaded guilty to
prostitution and were fined $2,500 each for paying college students
to have sex with the woman.
   Under terms of an agreement between the prosecution and the
defense, neither Rodney Thorp Wood nor Nancy Steffen Wood will
serve time in prison, perform community service or be placed on
probation.
   The couple sat together Monday holding hands and exchanging
smiles as they waited in court. When Lane County Circuit Judge Jack
Mattison asked if they had anything to say, both said, ``No, your
honor.''
   The Woods, saying they were conducting research into the
``sexual potential of the mature female,'' paid male students at
the University of Oregon $10 for each orgasm they or the
44-year-old woman experienced. Police said Wood, 60, recorded the
encounters and took photographs.
   The Southampton, N.Y., couple were cited by police Sept. 16 at a
Eugene hotel.
   Police said they had evidence the couple intended to carry on
their ``research'' at other West Coast campuses.
   Wood was suspended as director of anesthesiology at Southampton
Hospital on Long Island, N.Y., after the incident became public.
   The Woods were charged with prostitution after four students who
were asked to have sex with ``Nancy S.'' testified before a grand
jury. Among them was a 19-year-old man cited for prostitution after
he received money from the couple.
   Prosecutor Sean Hoar said the 19-year-old cooperated with
authorities and never was charged.
   Defense attorney Richard Urrutia blamed his clients' plight on
the media.
   ``All their actions were undertaken innocently and in good
faith, and it is a tragedy that they now come under a cloud of
suspicion and have been subject to sensational reporting in the
press,'' he said. ``We can only hope that this sorry episode does
not have a chilling effect on future research into areas such as
human sexuality.''
   Urrutia said the Woods never received any money in the
encounters, and that paying a token fee to scientific research
subjects is customary.
   Urrutia declined to discuss the origin of the research project,
and said he didn't know why the Woods traveled across the country
to conduct it.
   He said the couple pleaded guilty because they wanted to get on
with their lives.
</TEXT>
