<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Veto     10-24 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Veto,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Looking for Legislation to Exercise Line-Item Veto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House is looking for legislation on
which President Bush can seek to exercise a line-item veto as a
test case, presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said today.
   Such a move _ vetoing just one part of a bill while leaving the
rest intact _ would produce a major constitutional confrontation
with the Democratic majority in both the House and the Senate.
   Some legal scholars contend that such powers are implicit in a
president's power to veto legislation; others argue against such an
interpretation.
   Now, Fitzwater said, the administration is willing to force the
issue and prompt a court case, believing the president has such
powers and should be able to exercise them.
   ``We are looking for a vehicle that might be a suitable test
case. We haven't found one yet,'' Fitzwater said.
   The theory is to ``try to do it and see if it works....You claim
you have the authority and you just do it,'' Fitzwater said.
   He said forcing such a test had been considered for some time,
beginning in the Reagan administration.
   Both former President Reagan and Bush called for a
constitutional amendment to ensure the president line-item veto
powers, and it has long been an item on conservative agendas.
However, the proposals never made it very far in either
congressional chamber.
   Vice President Dan Quayle told an audience in Chicago on Monday
that the president was ``inclined to do so'' if he can find an
appropriate bill in which to veto individual provisions while
signing the rest into law.
   Quayle said line-item veto power would allow the president to
reduce federal spending.
   Meanwhile, Fitzwater said the president will continue to press
for a cut in the tax on capital gains and plans to meet with groups
of mostly Democratic senators this week to lobby for the plan,
which has already passed the House.
   Fitzwater said the administration has the votes to pass a cut _
if it can have a straight majority-rule vote on the measure in the
Senate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
