<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1345EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UNBirthday     10-24 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN Birthday,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Celebrates 44th Birthday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of children sang ``Happy
Birthday'' to the United Nations on Tuesday, then grabbed forks and
plates and dug into a mammoth birthday cake topped with 44 candles.
   The party commemorated United Nations Day, marking 44 years
since the U.N. Charter came into force on Oct. 24, 1945.
   The organization has even been accused of suffering from
middle-aged spread. The United States, Japan, Soviet Union, and
European governments have put the organization on a stringent
fiscal diet, with a zero-growth budget.
   But the world organization can look back on the last two years
as having been one of its most productive phases in years.
   U.N.-mediated accords led to the Soviet withdrawal from
Afghanistan, completed this year. The war front between Iran and
Iraq is still quiet since both nations agreed to a truce last year.
   ``There are growing signs that international relations may be
entering a new and more positive era,'' said Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar. ``There is, however, no reason for
complacency.
   ``Conflicts still persist in many parts of the globe. The
buildup of arms has not ceased,'' he said. ``Far too many people
still live in absolute poverty without adequate food or shelter and
face discrimination.''
   In 1988, the nearly half-million men and women who have worn the
blue beret in U.N. peacekeeping operations were honored with the
Nobel Peace Prize.
   On Nov. 7, Namibia will begin the first free elections in its
history under U.N. supervision, which are expected to end in the
territory becoming the world's newest nation next year, after being
held by South Africa since 1915.
   Central American nations have asked the United Nations to
oversee their regional peace agreement. This week, the Security
Council is expected to approve a U.N. border patrol force to cut
off Contra rebel infiltration into leftist Nicaragua, and shipments
of weapons to leftist rebels in El Salvador.
   Diplomats were moved from the General Assembly Hall to a large
basement conference room this week so it could be prepared for a
Tuesday evening concert by the Montreal Symphony Orchestra,
conducted by Charles Dutoit and with Yo Yo Ma as cello soloist.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
