<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Soviets     10-24 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Soviets,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Calls Soviet Admissions on Afghanistan ``Extraordinary''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration today called
``extraordinary'' admissions by the Soviet foreign minister that
its invasion of Afghanistan was illegal and that a radar
installation violated the anti-ballistic missile treaty.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater praised Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze's candor, calling it ``a step in the
right direction'' for arms control.
   Shevardnadze, in a speech Monday to the Supreme Soviet
legislature, said the decision under the late Soviet leader Leonid
Brezhnev to send troops into Afghanistan was a ``gross violation''
of Soviet law and ethics.
   He said the Krasnoyarsk radar station in Siberia was a violation
of the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty and would be dismantled.
The United States had argued for years that the massive
installation violated the 1972 ABM treaty.
   Fitzwater said of Shevardnadze's admissions: ``They're
extraordinary.''
   ``It's difficult to say what grand meaning they have, but it
certainly seems like a step in the right direction in terms of
glasnost ... and an environment for improved progress on arms
control and any other number of issues,'' he said.
   Fitzwater, who was also former President Reagan's White House
press secretary, said that, ``As the spokesman who stood here for
any number of years talking about the ABM treaty violation of the
Krasnoyarsk radar and talking about the occupation of Afghanistan,
the acknowledgements yesterday by the foreign minister are fairly
extraordinary.''
</TEXT>
