<FIRST>r a PM-DogStaples     10-24 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dog Staples,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Accuse Connecticut Company of Animal Abuse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen thousand doctors have signed a petition
asking a medical supply company to stop using surgical staplers on
dogs when training its salespeople, organizers said today.
   The company, U.S. Surgical Corp. of Norwalk, Conn., has been a
subject of protests by animal rights groups. The staplers can be
used in some cases in place of stitches.
   Eight participants _ along with Rusty, a mixed golden retriever
they said was rescued on its way to U.S. Surgical _ appeared at a
Manhattan news conference before leaving for Norwalk, where they
hoped to present the petition to company officials.
   ``We will turn them away,'' said Leon Hirsch, president of U.S.
Surgical. ``They are not welcome in our facility. ... There's been
too much animal rights terrorism.''
   ``This organization is a sham front,'' said Hirsch. ``They're a
pseudo-medical group of animal rights activists.''
   Dr. Neal D. Barnard, a Washington, D.C., psychiatrist and
president of the Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine,
contended U.S. Surgical laboratories kill about 1,000 dogs a year
after practicing stapling techniques on them.
   ``Former participants have reported that the strength of the
staples was tested by attempting to lift the dogs by their staples
and by attempting to tear the stapled organs apart,'' said Barnard.
   Barnard and other doctors and veterinarians said U.S. Surgical
trains its salespeople with dogs in order to get a jump on
competitors like the 3M company, which does not use dogs.
   U.S. Surgical says the dogs are anesthetized.
   Physicians Committee members said most medical students learn to
use instruments by observing other physicians and by practicing on
cadavers or fake, foam rubber organs, making the use of dogs
unnecessary.
</TEXT>
