<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1358EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Peru     10-24 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peru,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Puts Lima Under State of Emergency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government placed the capital and the port
of Callao under a 30-day state of emergency today, restricting
civil rights and giving the military broad powers to fight leftist
insurgents, an official newspaper reported.
   The move came less than three weeks before municipal elections
scheduled for Nov. 12, which Maoist Shining Path guerrillas are
trying to sabotage through a campaign of terror and assassinations.
   Police said rebels set fire to 10 public and private buses
Monday night in different areas in Lima Callao, five miles west of
here, after forcing passengers to get off. No one was injured in
the attacks, police said.
   The government also extended state of emergency restrictions in
the Andean province of Yauyos in the department of Lima, the
official government newspaper El Peruano reported. The government
on Monday announced new emergency restrictions in four other
provinces in Lima department, giving the military control over most
of the country's most populous department.
   State of emergency decrees now cover more than one-third the
area of Peru, including eight departments and several provinces.
More than half the country's 21 million people, including 7 million
in Lima and Callao, are affected.
   A department is the largest political subdivision in Peru and is
divided into provinces.
   The government has used state of emergency decrees to combat
terrorism since 1982. Among the restrictions implied in the decree
are suspension of habeas corpus rights, rights of free movement and
guarantees against search and seizure.
   The decrees remain in effect for 30 to 60 days and are routinely
extended.
   The Maoist Shining Path began its armed insurgency in 1980 near
the highland city of Ayacucho, 235 miles southeast of Lima. It
operates throughout the Andean highlands, in some coastal areas and
in the coca-producing jungles of the northeast.
</TEXT>
