<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1408EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HorseNeglect     10-24 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Horse Neglect,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Horses Suffer Malnutrition, Neglect on California Ranch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NUEVO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In one of Southern California's worst cases
of animal neglect in years, horses on a ranch have been so underfed
that they chew on wooden fence posts and eat their own manure.
   At least a dozen horses on the Allmond family ranch walk
painfully on unclipped hooves, sleep in their own urine in unkempt
stables and have swelled stomachs, a symptom of worms.
   Nearby ranchers have been complaining about the ranch to animal
control officials for months, but said nothing was done until
recently. They said it must have taken about a year for the horses'
conditions to deteriorate.
   ``This whole thing makes me sick,'' said Brigitte Richardson, a
horse breeder and one of several residents pressing Riverside
County animal control officers for action. ``Here we are sending
aid to foreign countries and this is happening in the heart of our
country.''
   For as long as anyone can remember, the ranch has been operated
almost single-handedly by Gil Allmond, who said he is 79 years old
but is believed by friends to be in his mid-80s.
   The ranch, about 65 miles southeast of Los Angeles, is owned by
Allmond's son, Ed Allmond, a certified horse show judge who animal
control officials said is now working with the county to set up a
feeding and veterinary schedule for the horses.
   Pressure on the county peaked Oct. 11, when one of the ranch's
horses _ a former champion show mare _ had to be destroyed after it
apparently was improperly fed.
   When a reporter visited the Allmond ranch last week, about 20 of
the ranch's 30 horses were so skinny their ribs, hip bones and
spines protruded. Wooden fence posts and the top of a gate had been
chewed away by the horses. Many of the animals were eating their
own feces.
   Some horses had matted hair and skin sores from lying in their
urine. Some walked awkwardly on hooves that hadn't been trimmed in
months.
   ``I've been working with horses for years, and I've never seen
anything this bad,'' said horse breeder Brian Seaman.
   The matter may be referred to the district attorney for legal
action.
   The elder Allmond denied that he has mistreated the animals and
said they are properly fed daily.
   ``Some of the horses are OK and some are not,'' he said. ``Some
are real old and are going to have to be destroyed. That mare (that
was destroyed) was 30 years old and just couldn't go on any more.''
   Ed Allmond, who lives in nearby San Jacinto, did not return a
reporter's telephone message Tuesday.
   Emmett Gibson, the county's chief animal control officer, said
action against the Allmonds won't be taken until a veterinarian
called in finishes a report on his inspection of the ranch earlier
this month.
   The ranch has emerged as one of southern California's worst
cases of animal neglect since humane officers in 1975 discovered
100 horses starving on breeder Rex C. Ellsworth's ranch in Chino.
</TEXT>
