<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--China-Soviet     10-24 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--China-Soviet,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese, Soviets Hold Border Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's foreign minister urged Tuesday that a
speedy solution be found to border disputes between China and the
Soviet Union.
   Foreign Minister Qian Qichen spoke at a meeting with Soviet Vice
Foreign Minister Igor Rogachev, who is in Beijing for the fourth
round of talks on the border in 2{ years, the official Xinhua News
Agency said.
   The last round, held in Moscow in 1988, ended with the two sides
saying they had settled most differences over the eastern part of
the border, the scene of bloody clashes in 1969.
   A working group was set up to discuss the western border.
   The Soviet news agency Tass had said the fourth round was to
finish Sunday. Xinhua, however, has carried no reports on its work
and its brief dispatch Tuesday did not make it clear if the round
was still going on.
   The Soviet Embassy has refused to answer questions about the
talks.
   According to Xinhua, Qian said both sides should strive to
settle outstanding issues in a just and reasonable way and at an
early date. He said progress was made at past rounds but did not
comment on the fourth round.
