<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1413EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Lawyers     10-24 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Lawyers,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bar: Lawyers Look To Help, Not Exploit Quake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's become a cliche that every disaster is
followed by a lawyer looking to turn tragedy into a quick buck. But
the State Bar says that doesn't seem to be the case with the
Northern California earthquake.
   So far, say officials of state and local legal organizations,
the response of lawyers to the Oct. 17 quake has been to offer free
or low-cost help to victims. Still, some lawyers stand to make
substantial sums down the road if they can provide liability for
damage, injury or death.
   ``We have not received by phone any complaints of unethical
solicitation (of clients), maybe in part due to the fact that we
got out there early and acted as a deterrent,'' Clayton Anderson,
director of investigations for the 117,000-member State Bar, said
Monday.
   ``On a national basis, historically there as been solicitation
in disasters. The legal profession is trying to put a stop to
that.''
   He said the bar distributed 6,000 leaflets to legal groups and
shelters for earthquake victims, spelling out rules on
solicitation: A lawyer can advertise services but can't go to an
accident scene or hospital to recruit clients, for example. A
toll-free number is listed for complaints.
   The California Trial Lawyers Association, whose members often
represent victims in injury lawsuits, has promised to guard against
ambulance-chasing. The office of famed injury lawyer Melvin Belli,
which says it will sue the state over the collapse of a freeway
overpass in the quake, says its attorneys are being careful not to
solicit clients.
   Meanwhile, lawyers are being mobilized to help those injured or
displaced by the earthquake.
   Volunteer lawyers will be stationed at clinics run by the
Federal Emergency Management Agency, helping people apply for
benefits, said Nancy Clinch of the bar's Board of Governors.
   ``Within three hours of the earthquake, the State Bar was
organizing those clinics,'' said Ms. Clinch, who organized legal
clinics after a September 1988 fire that destroyed more than 200
homes in Nevada County. ``It's a wonderful opportunity for lawyers
to become involved.''
   ``We called people Saturday morning for a 2 o'clock clinic, many
still digging out of their own rubble, and people just dropped
everything and came down here,'' said Drucilla Ramey, executive
director of the Bar Association of San Francisco.
   Plans for clinics include presentations by federal disaster
officials, insurance representatives, landlord-tenant experts and
others. Then participants could speak with volunteer lawyers.
   More information is to be provided through toll-free telephone
numbers, already set up by several counties and the State Bar.
   Ms. Ramey said common concerns of tenants of damaged buildings
include rent obligations, getting security deposits back and rights
when buildings are demolished.
   Inquiries are also numerous about whether homeowner's insurance
covers earthquakes _ the advice is to file a claim in every case _
and about federal aid and the rights of employees, said lawyers.
   Most county bar associations have ongoing lawyer referral
programs. Although free service is normally provided only after a
financial screening, ``I imagine substantially all of it will be
pro bono (free) in the next few weeks,'' said Stephen Schadlich,
president of the Alameda County Bar Association.
   At some point, however, some lawyers will be talking about
lawsuits involving large sums of money.
   Richard E. Brown of Belli's office said it has been contacted by
relatives of people who may have died in the collapse of Interstate
880 in Oakland and are interested in suing the state.
   But Brown said Belli has not contacted any victims or relatives
_ ``he'd lose his license if he'd done that'' _ and instead has two
lawyers working full-time to offer free legal consultations on
earthquake-related matters. Fees would be charged only if a lawsuit
were filed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
