<DOCNO> AP891024-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 2108EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--PoodleSprings     10-24 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Poodle Springs,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Raymond Chandler's Final Detective Novel To Be Made Into Movie</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Poodle Springs,'' the mystery novel that
was started by Raymond Chandler and finished by Robert B. Parker,
will be made into a movie, Universal Pictures has announced.
   Chandler, who had completed only four chapters of ``Poodle
Springs'' before his death in 1959, wrote six other Philip Marlowe
mysteries including, ``The Big Sleep'' and ``The Long Goodbye.''
   The Chandler estate selected Parker to finish ``Poodle
Springs.'' Parker has published 17 novels featuring a Boston
private eye named Spenser _ the same detective on which the
``Spenser: For Hire'' TV series was based.
   Universal announced Monday that Academy Award winning
producer-director Sydney Pollack and producer Jon Avnet will tackle
the ``Poodle Springs'' project with Michael Blake adapting the
novel for the big screen.
   ``We have the opportunity to make one of the classic movie
mysteries of all time,'' said Tom Pollock, chairman of MCA Motion
Picture Group.
   Pollack won an Oscar in 1985 for ``Out of Africa.'' Avnet has
produced movies including ``Risky Business.'' Blake wrote the
screenplay for the still-unreleased movie, ``Dances With Wolves,''
starring Kevin Costner.
</TEXT>
