<FIRST>r a AM-Nielsens     10-24 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Knocks Out ABC's World Series Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC climbed back on top of the Nielsen
ratings and ABC slipped to the bottom in an unusual week in which
the San Francisco earthquake rocked television schedules.
   ABC seemed certain to repeat its victory of the week before,
when it ended NBC's 68-week winning schedule. But the earthquake
last Tuesday forced postponement of the World Series just as the
third game was getting underway in San Francisco's Candlestick Park.
   NBC's ``Cheers'' was first for the week ended Oct. 22, closely
followed by ``The Cosby Show.'' ABC's highest-ranked show was its
Monday Night Football game between the Los Angeles Rams and the
Buffalo Bills.
   NBC was first in the A.C. Nielsen Co. survey with an average of
14.1. CBS was second with 12.6 and ABC third with 12.1. The ratings
represent the percentage of the nation's 92.1 million household
tuned into a program.
   ABC's coverage of the games, and counterprogramming by NBC and
CBS, fell by the wayside. ABC, unprepared with alternative
programming, dropped to third place. None of its entertainment
programs made the Top 10 because its strong Tuesday comedy lineup
was pre-empted, first by the planned World Series and then by
special coverage of the earthquake.
   The Tuesday night pre-game show tied for 44th place.
   The networks' special coverage of the earthquake was not ranked
by Nielsen because it was unscheduled and not sponsored. The
network evening news shows, however, had nearly five million extra
viewers who tuned in because of the quake. ABC was first, followed
by CBS and NBC.
   The San Francisco Giants and the Oakland Athletics are not due
to resume World Series play until Friday. The resumption depends on
the weather and repairs to the ballpark.
   Here are the Top 10: NBC's ``Cheers,'' NBC's ``The Cosby Show,''
NBC's ``A Different World,'' NBC's ``Golden Girls,'' NBC's ``Dear
John'' and CBS' ``60 Minutes'' tied, NBC's ``Empty Nest,'' NBC's
``Unsolved Mysteries'' and CBS movie ``Do You Know the Muffin
Man?'' tied, and ABC's Monday Night NFL Football.
   The networks all had follow-up coverage of the earthquake with
special reports and in regularly scheduled news magazine show.
Here's how they did: ABC's ``20-20'' in a tie for 20th place, CBS'
``48 Hours'' 29th, ABC News special report 34th, ABC's ``PrimeTime
Live'' in a tie for 37th place, and NBC's special report 43rd.
   Fox Broadcasting's ``Married...With Children'' was its
highest-rated show. It tied for 46th place. Its next highest show
was ``Open House'' in a tie for 69th place.
   ABC's ``World News Tonight'' led the news shows with a rating of
11.5. CBS was second with 11.2 and NBC third with 10.7. CBS was
rated for only four nights because the night of the earthquake it
pre-empted its West Coast news feed for special coverage.
   The lowest-rated show of the week was CBS' ``Saturday Night with
Connie Chung.'' Here are the five bottom shows: NBC movie ``Stuck
With Each Other,'' ABC's ``Mr. Belvedere,'' ABC Mystery Movie
``B.L. Stryker,'' ABC's ``Living Dolls'' and CBS' ``Saturday Night
with Connie Chung.''
</TEXT>
