<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1607EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     10-24 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarians Have a Democracy, With the Same Old Worries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarians proclaimed a democracy and
honored the long-maligned 1956 revolt, but on Tuesday they had the
same leaders and the same problems: how to tell truth from lies and
live on $100 a month or less.
   A day after the heady celebration, a pensioner said he hoped for
``a price freeze, so we can live better.'' With annual inflation
above 20 percent and the government lifting food subsidies under
market reforms, his wife said, they can afford meat only on Sundays.
   An estimated 100,000 Hungarians cheered the new democratic
republic Monday when acting President Matyas Szueroes proclaimed it
from the Parliament balcony.
   That evening, even more filled the same square to honor the
anti-Stalinist revolt of 1956, which was crushed by Soviet troops.
   They applauded proclamations by former revolutionaries that real
democracy will be achieved only when Hungarians can elect leaders
of their choice.
   Although the Communist Party has changed its name, one-party
rule remains in force, at least until planned multiparty elections
planned for next year.
   Hungary has committed itself on the path to democracy.
Parliament adopted legislation last week creating the legal
framework for the first free elections in more than 40 years and,
before that, the Communist Party disbanded in favor of a new
Socialist Party committed to democracy.
   Economic survival was a common topic on the street Tuesday. Many
Hungarians place their hopes in Premier Miklos Nemeth, a
41-year-old economist who is introducing market forces and private
ownership.
   ``For the past 40 years, we have heard nothing but lies,'' the
retired couple said in unison. They and others interviewed would
not give their names.
   The husband said lies continued, but at least ``the leadership
has finally expressed the truth about what happened here 33 years
ago.''
   He and his wife live on a small pension and constantly face
poverty, which official statistics say threatens 25 percent of
Hungary's 10.6 million people.
   Even for working people, the average wage barely exceeds the
equivalent of $100 a month.
   As the retired couple spoke, a woman nearby counted bottles she
had collected to redeem for the deposits. Westerners notice an
increasing number of pensioners stopping them on the street to ask
for change.
   An 18-year-old cook said Hungary had experienced ``tremendous
changes'' in the past year, but ``I will be optimistic when I don't
see any Communists anywhere.'' He expressed faith in Nemeth's
ability to run the government.
   A store clerk said, ``I trust Nemeth because he's relatively
young and a technocrat.''
   The premier, who studied at Karl Marx University in Budapest and
at Harvard, is committed to a market-oriented economy as part of
any reform program.
   A pensioner from a village nea Lake Balaton said economic reform
would allow ``ordinary Hungarians to have a better future once a
market economy is created.''
   He said he had to supplement a monthly pension of 5,000 forints
(less than $100) with part-time work at the post office and selling
produce from his garden.
   A young book vendor said the changes this month indicated
``something has begun to move, and we just have to hope concrete
changes will come.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1616EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SegregationistSpeeches     10-24 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Segregationist Speeches,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Segregationist Commission Supplied Speeches For Mississippi Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mississippi's segregationist watchdog
agency supplied state lawmakers, officials and educators a standard
speech promoting segregation to deliver before Northern audiences
in 1963.
   The speech claimed separate drinking fountains and bathrooms
were necessary because many blacks lacked morals, education and
proper hygiene, according to a copy obtained by The Clarion-Ledger.
   ``There are many Negroes, of course, who have reached plateaus
of citizenship,'' the speech says. ``They are personally clean,
have high morals and are educated. However, they are still in the
minority.''
   The now-defunct, state-sponsored Sovereignty Commission spied
on, infiltrated and harassed civil rights groups during the 1960s.
It also funded the White Citizens' Council, an organization
established to promote segregation.
   Erle Johnston Jr. of Forest, who plans to describe the
commission and the events of the 1960s in a book, said he wrote the
speech and its accompanying answers to questions expected from the
Northern news media.
   Johnston, who usually accompanied the speakers, handled public
relations for the commission in the 1960s before serving as its
director from 1963 through 1967.
   Johnston defended the speech as appropriate for its time. ``We
were trying to let people know how things worked in Mississippi. We
didn't try to convert a soul. We just tried to tell them how things
worked,'' he said.
   Segregation in the 1960s was in its death throes and its
defenders ``resorted to any means of survival,'' said David
Sansing, a professor of history at the University of Mississippi.
   ``A society that discriminates and exploits will not mind lying.
It would just do whatever it had to do to justify a system that had
no defense,'' Sansing said.
   The commission paid air fare, meals and other expenses for the
volunteer speakers, who included a reporter from The
Clarion-Ledger, well-known in the 1960s for its hard line against
integration.
   Titled ``The Message From Mississippi,'' the speech claims
Mississippi blacks preferred segregationist ways.
   ``Many of our colored leaders, ministers, educators and
newspaper editors openly endorse the separate school system and
repudiate the outsiders who come into Mississippi to violate our
laws,'' the speech says.
   The questions and answers discuss two of Mississippi's most
infamous civil rights slayings, referring to both as ``unsolved
murders:''
   _Seven days after 14-year-old Chicago native Emmett Till
whistled at a white store owner's wife, his body was pulled from
the Tallahatchie River in Tallahatchie County on Aug. 31, 1955. He
had been beaten and shot once in the head.
   An all-white jury acquitted two white men of the killing.
   While Till's slaying ``was a crime of violence we deplore,'' the
speech says, what Till did was ``a very serious offense, although
it was not deserving of capital punishment.''
   _On April 24, 1959, in Poplarville, a mob of at least 23 white
men dragged Mack Parker, a black 23-year-old truck driver accused
of raping a white woman, from his jail cell, shot him, weighted him
with chains and threw his body in the Pearl River.
   The speech claims the killing took place because
``Mississippians had watched as court decrees stayed the execution
of a St. Louis Negro, Robert Goldsby, who shot down a white woman
as she was trying to protect her husband.''
   The speech also claims that the federal government was
responsible for the riot that resulted in two deaths following the
1962 admission of James Meredith into the University of Mississippi
as its first black student.
   ``There was no disturbance, no injury, no death, so long as the
state of Mississippi was permitted to be responsible for law and
order in Mississippi,'' the speech says. ``It was only when the
federal authorities acted hastily in firing tear gas into a group
of students and others that violence, injury, death and destruction
of property resulted.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1531EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Gangs Bjt   10-24 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Gangs, Bjt,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Gangs Blamed For Murders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAITHAM HAMAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABLUS, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO-allied gangs with fanciful
names like ``Black Panther Brigades'' and ``Red Eagles'' are blamed
for most of the 20 murders here of Arabs accused of collaborating
with Israel.
   Israeli officials claim some gangs operate under direct order of
the PLO. But Palestinians maintain that at least some of the
murders have been carried out in defiance of PLO Chairman Yasser
Arafat.
   With 132 Palestinians killed for alleged collaboration in the
22-month-old Palestinian uprising, there are fears that the
executions are getting out of hand. Palestinians complain that
ordinary citizens are being intimidated by the frequent murders.
   In Nablus last week, the Red Eagles killed a 24-year-old
upholstery worker and wheeled his body through the streets of the
West Bank's largest city in a pushcart, presumably as a warning to
others.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, a school guard was found burned to
death in his car Oct. 5 and graffiti signed by the ``Palestinian
Revolutionary Eagles'' took responsibility the slaying.
   A senior Israeli defense official on Tuesday confirmed a report
in The New York Times that security forces had discovered documents
linking the Revolutionary Eagles in Gaza to Yasser Arafat's
mainstream PLO faction Fatah.
   One letter quoted by the Times says slayings should be blamed on
the little-known Eagles group in order to deflect blame from the
PLO.
   The Times said, however, that the documents could be forgeries.
If genuine, the papers could give credence to Israel's repeated
arguments that Arafat is sponsoring murder despite his claim to
have renounced terrorism in December.
   Israeli officials have frequently cited the slayings of
Palestinians by fellow Arabs as reason for the United States to
halt its dialogue with the PLO, begun after Arafat's statement on
terrorism.
   The pace of the killings has quickened as the uprising has
dragged on without political gains. Of the 132 slayings by
Palestinians since the revolt erupted in December 1987, 110
occurred this year alone.
   At least 601 Palestinians have been killed by Israeli soldiers
or civilians during the revolt, and 40 Israelis also have died.
   Palestinian sources say the murders of some supposed
collaborators claimed by such groups as the Abu Jihad Phalangists
are ordered by opponents of Arafat's policies.
   The Red Eagles in Nablus are believed backed by the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a radical Syrian-based PLO
faction that opposes Arafat's efforts to negotiate an agreement
with Israel.
   In Nablus, residents of the Yasmina quarter where the Black
Panthers operate say the gang is murdering people despite appeals
from PLO-backed uprising leaders and Arafat himself.
   They say the gang's members, believed to be 10 men ages 19 to
25, wander freely through the dark, twisting alleys of Yasmina,
often armed with knives, hatchets or pistols.
   ``People are scared to death,'' a 32-year-old Yasmina shopkeeper
said. ``They are afraid to leave their houses.''
   The shopkeeper, like others who agreed to discuss the Black
Panther slayings, would not allow his name to be used out of fear.
   Nablus residents and local journalists said the Black Panthers
have carried out 15 or 16 of the 20 slayings in the city, most of
alleged collaborators but also including prostitutes and drug
dealers who some activists consider enemies of the uprising.
   The Black Panthers are allied with Arafat's Fatah PLO faction,
but local Fatah officials say the gang's members are running out of
control, ignoring orders in uprising leaflets that any killings
must have the approval of the revolt's leaders.
   ``They are not educated enough to be judges. They are working
against the intefadeh,'' said one Fatah leader in Nablus.
   Two weeks ago, residents listened carefully to an appeal from
Arafat on the PLO's radio station in Iraq urging more control in
slayings of collaborators. They say the statement was clearly aimed
at the Black Panthers.
   Neither Arafat nor uprising leaders have condemned collaborator
killings outright, however, and there is widespread support for
killing Palestinians who endanger the lives of activists by
informing on them.
   Arafat, in an interview early this month with a London-based
Arabic-language newspaper, said he gave authority to uprising
leaders to order murders of those proven to be collaborators.
   ``The unified command has the right to kill all those who
cooperate with the enemy,'' he told the Al-Quds Al-Arabia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
