<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1702EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-EastGermany-Change     10-24 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany-Change,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Watch First No Votes Cast Against Communist Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germans on Tuesday watched on live television
what would have been unthinkable just weeks ago: members of the
Communist-controlled parliament voting against the sole candidate
for president.
   In all, 26 lawmakers voted against Egon Krenz while another 26
abstained _ making up more than 10 percent of the 500-seat People's
Chamber.
   It was the first time in the nation's 40-year history that the
Communist Party-selected candidate for president got anything less
than a unanimous vote, and the first time such proceedings were
broadcast live.
   ``I always count badly,'' joked parliament speaker Horst
Sindermann as he fumbled while tallying the show of hands. ``I
don't want any falsified results.''
   While the 74-year-old Sindermann spoke in jest, the issue is
extremely serious for the nation's growing opposition groups. They
have accused the government of rigging regional elections last
spring.
   Sindermann, a lifelong Communist and survivor of the Nazis'
notorious Mauthausen concentration camp, said parliament should
``ban formalism'' in future meetings, suggesting more critical
debate could be allowed in the chamber.
   While some ``no'' votes may have been encouraged to give the
impression the party represents a variety of opinions, thereby
diluting opposition complaints the parliament is a rubber-stamp
body, Tuesday's vote was a radical departure from the unanimous
endorsements given all previous proposals by the ruling Politburo.
   ``Today's voting results speak for the necessary and new
self-confidence of this high chamber,'' Krenz said in his speech to
the parliament, in an apparent reference to the signs of dissent
among the ranks.
   Krenz reaffirmed the need for East Germany to stick closely to
its ``socialist foundation,'' but also spoke of the need for
renewal in the troubled nation.
   The 52-year-old East German leader also promised an
investigation into charges of police brutality during
demonstrations earlier this month. Authorities later acknowledged
for the first time there had been police attacks against peaceful
pro-democracy protesters.
   While only time will tell whether any substantive reforms are
undertaken, there already have been plenty of changes of style
since Krenz took over the more important job as Communist Party
chief a week ago.
   The broadcast of the voting for president displays the
government's attempts to show it is interested in more openness
after decades of repression of free speech.
   East German TV viewers watched pictures of a pro-democracy
demonstration of 300,000 in Leipzig on Monday, just hours after it
occurred. The same night, they were able to view the party's
ideology chief, Kurt Hager, accuse former leader Erich Honecker of
having encouraged ``elements of a personality cult'' during his 18
years of authoritarian rule.
   On Saturday, two senior party officials engaged in a heated
debate with demonstrators on an East Berlin street, and portions of
that exchange were broadcast on the main evening news.
   The change is enormous for TV viewers accustomed to being
flooded with government attacks on the West and official attempts
to contradict the West German TV shows that reach most of the
communist nation.
   State-run newspapers also have been filled with growing numbers
of critical voices, ranging from workers to artists.
   But while more people are being encouraged to talk openly, Krenz
and his colleagues have made clear that the Communist Party will
keep the ``leading role'' in the nation of 16.5 million people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
