<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     10-24 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Toll in Ethnic Violence Reaches 300</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethnic conflicts have killed 300 civilians and
injured 5,260 since they erupted 20 months ago, an Interior
Ministry official said Tuesday.
   The conflicts have prompted 360,000 people to flee their homes
in fear, including Armenians, Azerbaijanis and Meskhetian Turks,
said Col. Gen. Yuri V. Shatalin. Thousands of those homes have been
set on fire, he said.
   The Interior Ministry's troops and police have suffered 890
casualties, including 12 deaths, he said.
   Nagorno-Karabakh, the disputed territory at the focus of the
Armenia-Azerbaijan conflict, remains virtually blockaded, Shatalin
said.
   Only troop escorts permit the transport of food to the
ethnically torn territory, he said.
   Nagorno-Karabakh is a primarily Armenian enclave within
Azerbaijan. Armenians want it transferred to Armenian control and
Azerbaijanis are resisting fiercely.
   Azerbaijanis blockaded the republic of Armenia as well this
month, but troops were able to restore train traffic on the main
line to Yerevan, which runs through Azerbaijan.
   Shatalin said the Supreme Soviet legislature is due to decide
the fate of Nagorno-Karabakh soon, but he fears that any decision
will infuriate one side or the other.
   In the long-running Armenia-Azerbaijan conflict, Shatalin said,
the death toll is almost equally divided between the two
nationalities.
</TEXT>
