<FIRST>r w AM-PrenatalCare     10-24 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prenatal Care,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prenatal Care Problem: Getting It to People in Need</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. medicine has the means to prevent 10,000
infant deaths each year, a Bush administration official told a
House panel Tuesday, but witnesses said obstacles keep many needy
women from proper care.
   The women who need early care the most can rarely fit that care
into their lives because poverty forces them to be preoccupied with
the struggle for personal survival, witnesses told the House Select
Committee on Children Youth and Families.
   Women who do seek care must travel long distances, changing
buses several times, for just a brief appointment, witnesses said.
   ``When one stops to consider the many problems they face,
including lack of basic necessities of life, long waits in a busy
clinic, to spend a few minutes with a doctor they have never seen
before, who uses technical terms they do not understand, and who
has to hurry to see the next patient perhaps the question should
not be `why don't they?' but `why do they?''' said Marilyn L.
Poland, a nurse and anthropologist on the faculty of the Wayne
State University Medical School.
   ``When they are faced with a choice between waiting for a
welfare check to buy basic necessities before the money is stolen
or to keep a prenatal appointment _ prenatal care becomes less
important,'' she said.
   Doctors, on the other hand, complain that they are hamstrung by
the rise in malpractice lawsuits and insurance premiums, especially
severe among obstetricians. Doctors also complain that Medicaid _
the state-administered health care system for the poor _ is
underfunded and caught up in red tape.
   Dr. James O. Mason, the acting surgeon general and assistant
secretary for health in the Department of Health and Human
Services, said the administration is trying to tackle the worst
problems.
   ``We estimate that we could save 10,000 of the 40,000 babies who
die each year, just by applying what we already know about things
like case management, outreach and home visiting,'' Mason said.
   There are 4 million babies born in the United States each year,
and the infant mortality rate _ the rate of infants who die within
a year of birth _ ranks this country 22nd among industrialized
nations.
   For the short term, Mason said, President Bush had submitted a
budget proposal that would expand the number of low-income women
eligible for Medicaid.
   Mason said that an interdepartmental commission he chairs will
give the White House recommendations in the next two months ``to
achieve better coordination among the extensive array of existing
programs.''
   Among the solutions being advanced is ``one-stop shopping'' in
which health and various social services are located under one roof.
   ``One-stop shopping is based on the premise that by allowing
eligibility for AFDC (welfare), Medicaid and other social services
to be determined at the same time and at the same site that health
care is delivered, there will be an increased likelihood that the
poor pregnant woman will receive the full range of services which
she needs and to which she is entitled,'' Mason said.
   Other witnesses said the issue is deeper rooted and must be
tackled in part with sex education beginning in grade school.
   Witnesses complained that the loss of neighborhoods and
neighborhood-oriented medical practices along with the growth in
government medical programs has also created a bureaucratic,
impersonal medical system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0126 </DOCNO>
