<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Lebanon     10-24 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Lebanon,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Troops Kill Two Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed two guerrillas
in Israel's self-declared security zone in south Lebanon on
Tuesday, the military command said.
   The clash north of Majayoun, four miles north of the Israeli
border, came hours after the army said Israeli-backed militiamen
shot and killed two other armed guerrillas in the security zone.
   An army spokesman said an Israeli force on a routine patrol of
the zone's central sector spotted a guerrilla squad and opened
fire, attacking it from a short distance and killing two guerrillas.
   The Israeli unit suffered no casualties, the spokesman said. No
further details were released.
   Military officials said Soviet-designed AK-47 assault rifles,
hand grenades and explosives were found near the guerrillas' bodies.
   The officials were unable to say if the victims in the clashes
Monday and Tuesday were Palestinian or Lebanese guerrillas. Both
Palestinian and Lebanese militias have attacked Israeli soldiers
and their militia allies in the Israeli-controlled zone in south
Lebanon.
   No organization has claimed responsibility for the attacks on
the Israeli unit or the South Lebanon Army, which is trained, armed
and financed by Israel.
   Foreign reports have said about 500 Israeli soldiers patrol the
security zone, which covers 328 square miles, along with the
militia force made up mostly of Lebanese Christians.
   Israel carved out the buffer zone to protect its northern border
against guerrilla attacks in June 1985 when it withdrew the bulk of
its troops from Lebanon after a three-year occupation.
</TEXT>
