<FIRST>r w AM-Yellowstone-Timber     10-24 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yellowstone-Timber,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Park Service Won't Allow Timber Convoys Through Yellowstone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Park Service says it will not
allow commercial timber hauling through Yellowstone Park, despite a
request by the U.S. Forest Service.
   Parks Director James Ridenour denied the request this week on
the advice on lawyers who said it was against federal law,
spokesman George Berklacy said Tuesday.
   ``There is a park regulation that prohibits commercial transport
across park roadways,'' said Berklacy.
   Ridenour also was concerned that a lumber company's plan to
transport about 20,000 truckloads of logs through the park would
have adverse impacts on important grizzly bear, elk and bison
habitats as well as roadways, said the spokesman.
   He said the Forest Service, which sold the timber, indicated to
the Park Service that there was an emergency need to go through
Yellowstone. But Berklacy said Park Service lawyers disagreed,
saying that the need did not meet the standards required to
constitute an emergency.
   Environmentalists were waiting for Ridenour's decision as the
first big test of his willingness to protect the parks from
commercial assault.
   ``I think the Park Service is to be commended,'' Michael Scott
of the Wilderness Society said Tuesday. ``It did the right thing.''
   Scott said he was glad Ridenour did not accept the Forest
Service's argument that an ``economic emergency'' existed to
justify the hauling.
   ``It would have set a very serious precedent,'' said Scott. He
said that if the Forest Service had prevailed, private owners who
were watching the action would have come forth with similar
requests.
   ``People expect when they enter the boundaries of Yellowstone
Park that things will be different, a world dominated more by
nature than the works of civilization,'' Scott said.
   The timber to be hauled is from national forests bordering
Yellowstone and amounts to about 40 million board feet from trees
that were partially burned by fires that blazed through the park
last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 2031EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Stalin     10-24 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stalin,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stalin Biographer: Return to the Dictator's Methods a Possibility</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The general who wrote the first Soviet biography
of Josef Stalin said Tuesday there could be a return to the brutal
dictator's methods if Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms don't show
tangible results.
   ``Literally speaking, I rule out a repetition (of Stalin),''
Col. Gen. Dmitri Volkogonov said. ``But a certain return to
conservatism is not excluded, of course.''
   Volkogonov, 61, appeared at a government-sponsored news
conference to present his four-volume ``political portrait'' of
Stalin titled ``Triumph and Tragedy.''
   The book, said by the official Tass news agency to be the first
Soviet biography of Stalin, has been printed in an initial
Russian-language edition of 300,000 copies.
   Volkogonov's work was 10 years in the making and he was given
unprecedented access to previously secret archives, said the
author, chief of the Military History Institute of the Soviet
Defense Ministry.
   His remarks to reporters indicate his 1,344-page work, published
by the Novosti Press Agency, conforms to the new official view of
Stalin as a bloody tyrant, instead of the former version of Stalin
as the architect of the Soviet Union's wartime victory over the
Nazis and the country's industrializer.
   ``The main thing for him was power; his credo was violence,
physical and ideological,'' Volkogonov said.
   In response to a reporter's question, he estimated that from 21
million to 22 million Soviets were unlawfully imprisoned, sent into
internal exile or wrongfully convicted during Stalin's 29-year
reign as Soviet leader.
   Of that number, ``more than two-thirds perished,'' Volkognov
said.
   He said his calculations were based on the capacity of
Stalin-era prisons, labor camps and ``shooting chambers'' where the
Soviet secret police carried out executions.
   In preparation for his book, Volkogonov said he met with
hundreds of people who had known or worked with Stalin, among them
former members of the ruling Communist Party Politburo, secretaries
of the party's policy-making Central Committee, marshals of the
armed forces, people's commissars and members of the dictator's
entourage.
   Asked if another Stalin could arise in the Soviet Union,
Volkogonov said history excludes ``a total repetition.'' But he
said the apparent failure of Gorbachev's reforms could trigger a
conservative reaction.
   ``Attempts to preserve this Stalinist system, attempts to return
to some of his methods, are not excluded in principle,'' Volkogonov
said. ``To exclude them altogether, we need to do a lot. First of
all, our society needs like air at least some success to be felt in
any sphere _ social, agricultural, anywhere _ in order to infuse
new hope in the future success of the changes.''
   The Soviet Union also needs political mechanisms ``that would
guarantee against a return to the past,'' he said without
elaborating.
   For almost two decades, Volkogonov served in the Main Political
Department of the Soviet Army and Navy, but he said he gave that
job up to work on the book.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
