<FIRST>u a PM-ZsaZsaSentencing 7thLd-Writethru a0675 10-24 0971</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zsa Zsa Sentencing, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0675,0997</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Judge Sentences Zsa Zsa Gabor to Three Days in Jail for Slapping
Policeman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to ADD $10,000 restitution order, no possibility
of early release; picks up 6th graf, `Earlier, Rubin ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today sentenced actress Zsa
Zsa Gabor to three days in jail and ordered her to pay more than
$12,000 in fines and restitution for slapping a police officer.
   ``If you strike a cop, you go to jail,'' Municipal Judge Charles
Rubin told Miss Gabor in sentencing her for battery on a police
officer, driving without a valid driver's license and having an
open container of alcohol in her car.
   Rubin also fined the Hungarian actress $2,350, ordered her to
pay $10,000 in restitution to the city of Beverly Hills and its
police department and directed her to perform 120 hours of
community service in a shelter for homeless women.
   He gave Miss Gabor a 24-month jail sentence, but suspended that
to four days and gave her credit for the day she served after being
arrested June 14.
   ``The law applies equally to everybody, whether they're rich or
poor and whether they're famous or not,'' the judge said, ordering
her to serve the three-day sentence before Dec. 29 and allowing no
possibility of early release.
   Earlier, Rubin denied a motion by Miss Gabor's new attorney,
Harrison Bull.
   In setting the conditions for her community service, the judge
ordered Miss Gabor not to say anything to anyone about the case or
give interviews while performing her community service, and asked
reporters to stay away from her.
   As Rubin lectured Miss Gabor about having an open bottle of
whiskey in her Rolls-Royce Corniche, she laughed, earning her a
rebuke from the judge.
   The judge said Miss Gabor's action ``verbally slapped the faces
of every cop.''
   ``She was not satisfied with that. She turned around and slapped
the face of every American by comparing justice in the United
States to Communist Russia and Nazi Germany,'' the judge said.
   Before sentencing, Deputy District Attorney Elden Fox argued for
a tough sentence.
   ``How dare the defendant suggest that she waws not tried by a
jury of her peers? ... ``How dare she suggest they do not
understand the class of people that she comes from?'' Fox argued.
   He said Miss Gabor's antics during trial ``Suggested that this
is a joke... she had no respect for the process.''
   In his motion for a mistrial, Bull argued that Miss Gabor wasn't
properly defended during trial by previous counsel William Graysen.
But Rubin ruled that Graysen's defense was competent, and refused
to declare a mistrial.
   Bull then began calling character witnesses for Miss Gabor,
including charity fundraiser and entertainment industry publicist
Gloria Luchenbill.
   Miss Gabor listened to witnesses with her chin thrust up, and at
one point sprayed herself with a new dose of perfume.
   Bull earlier called on R.G. Markle, who identified himself as an
expert in legal ethics, to back up a contention that Graysen sought
out Miss Gabor in order to gain favorable publicity for his law
practice.
   Bull then called Graysen, who testified under questioning by
Bull that ``I took the case for several reasons, and one of them
was for the publicity.'' Graysen also said he thought the case
would be interesting, that he admired Miss Gabor, and he believed
there may have been some wrongdoing by police in the matter.
   Miss Gabor arrived at court this morning in a black dress,
stepping from a black Mercedes Benz with her husband and telling
about 100 reporters and camera crew members, ``Of course, I'm
nervous.''
   She explained the dress by saying ``My stepfather just died,''
referring to her mother's third husband, Edmond de Szigethy, who
died Sept. 30.
   A jury on Sept. 29 convicted Miss Gabor of battery on a police
officer, driving without a valid driver's license and having an
open container of alcohol in her car. She was acquitted of failing
to obey an officer.
   The maximum possible sentence for the misdemeanor conviction was
18 months in prison and a $3,500 fine.
   District Attorney Ira Reiner urged a 30-day jail sentence, a
fine of more than $3,000 plus $14,000 to compensate the Beverly
Hills Police Department for its costs. But Fox had dismissed the
idea of a jail term after her conviction, saying she was too old to
serve time.
   ``I can't believe this is happening to me,'' Miss Gabor, who is
secretive about her age but according to court documents is 66,
said in a telephone interview Monday night. ``I'm 100 percent
innocent.''
   She said she spent the evening at home, ``feeding my five dogs
and my German husband,'' Frederick von Anhalt.
   ``We were invited to a dinner party but I can't go out. I've got
to get up early in the morning,'' she said.
   During the trial, Miss Gabor told reporters she was afraid to go
to jail because jails are filled with lesbians.
   She later apologized, saying, ``I got letter from the lesbian
and gay association. They are going to boycott me because I say
there are lesbians in jail. Imagine a women's jail, there must be
lesbians ... maybe I should become a lesbian. What do I know? I
like men.''
   The three-week trial cost $30,000. Fox, unhappy with what he
called a courthouse ``media circus,'' had been eager to recoup
trial expenses instead. But Reiner spokeswoman Sandy Gibbons said
court costs could not be recouped constitutionally.
   The tempestuous Miss Gabor slapped Officer Paul Kramer on June
14 after he stopped her Rolls-Royce convertible on a busy street.
The actress testified she instinctively struck out after Kramer
roughed her up.
   Kramer overreacted, she said, and used undue force in arresting
her.
</TEXT>
