<FIRST>r i AM-Belgium-Abortion     10-24 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgium-Abortion,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Opens Abortion Debate; Issue Referred For Constitutional Test</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIPPE NEURAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament on Tuesday began debating a
bill that would end a 122-year-old ban on abortions in this
overwhelmingly Roman Catholic nation of 10 million people.
   ``The issue is painful and divides us by its conflict of values,
the right to life and the distress of women,'' said Jacqueline
Mayence, a conservative but pro-abortion senator who opened the
debate.
   ``Nobody wants to promote abortion,'' she said, but added, ``the
ban is inapplicable, particularly because of public opinion ... and
new legislation in neighboring countries which leads to `abortion
tourism.'''
   Public opinion polls show most Belgians favor abortions.
   The bill before the 184-member senate was preceded by 30 similar
measures in the past 15 years that all failed to win legislative
approval. The latest would let a woman have an abortion before her
12th week of pregnancy if she is in a ``state of distress.''
   Under Belgian law, women who have abortions, and doctors who
perform them, risk jail terms of up to 10 years. Yet enforcement of
the law has been spotty and the courts have issued very lenient
penalties to offenders in recent years.
   An estimated 15,000 abortions are performed in Belgium each year
with hospitals reporting these as womb surgery to allow women to be
reimbursed by the social security system.
   As debate opened, Senate President Frank Swaelen, a Christian
Democrat, sent the bill to the Council of State for a ruling on
whether it conforms with the constitution.
   The Council of State, a legal panel that acts as a
constitutional court, was asked to issue its ruling by week's end.
   Swaelen's move did not suspend the debate. But it will delay a
final senate vote until next month and reflected abortion
opposition within Prime Minister Wilfried Martens' Christian
Democratic Party.
   The latest bill was adopted by two Senate committees but has
opened opened up a rift within Martens' coalition of Christian
Democrats, Socialists and a Flemish nationalist party. No
government minister attended Tuesday's debate.
   Christian Democrats, especially in Belgium's Dutch-speaking
northern half, are almost unanimously opposed to legalizing
abortions. The Socialists are in favor as are the opposition
Conservatives.
   After the senate has voted on the abortion bill, the issue must
still win approval of the dominant 212-member Chamber of
Representatives where Martens' government occupies 150 seats.
   The abortion debate really began 16 years ago when Dr. Willy
Peers, head of a maternity ward at a Namur hospital, announced he
regularly performed abortions.
   He was jailed briefly but never tried. His action set off a
pro-abortion campaign that led prosecutors to suspend some cases
and judges to acquit or give light sentences to offenders who were
prosecuted.
   ``The Parliament must thus put law in conformity with social and
legal reality,'' said Ms. Mayence.
   She added that the bill would not establish abortion on demand,
but permit it in certain circumstances. Abortions could only take
place after the 12th week of pregnancy if the foetus suffered from
serious, incurable diseases or the life of the mother was in danger.
   The bill also stipulates that abortions must only be carried out
in approved hospitals or medical centers.
</TEXT>
