<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1645EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Stalin     10-24 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Stalin,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priest Plans Service for Poles Slain by Secret Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Warsaw priest plans to hold religious
ceremonies for up to 3,000 people who were murdered by secret
police during the Stalinist era and buried near his church.
   ``These people were deprived of a Christian burial, therefore
the Warsaw church has a totally special obligation to fulfill this
(funeral) ritual,'' the Rev. Jozef R. Maj, parish priest at St.
Catherine's Church, told state television Monday.
   He said lectures and ceremonies would be held Thursday through
Saturday, with a funeral service Saturday night.
   He also appealed to people to provide any information they have
that could ``broaden our knowledge'' about the Poles killed as
communism was imposed throughout the country.
   A cleaning last fall of the archives of the Roman Catholic
church revealed that 500 to 3,000 people slain by Polish secret
police from 1946 to 1956 were buried in the parish cemetery, the
television report said.
   The examination of the church archives was reported in the
Polish press last year, but at that time the Stalinist repression
in Poland after World War II was a taboo subject for the official
media.
   The existence of a mass grave in the Sluzewiec cemetery had been
known for years even though the victims were buried secretly. Names
of the victims have not been released by the Interior Ministry and
many have not been identified.
   Thousands of Poles who were accused of resisting communist rule
were arrested, held without trial, tortured and killed as Soviet
dictator Josef Stalin enforced his domination over East-bloc
countries controlled by the Soviet army.
   Among those slain were members of the underground Home Army that
had fought the Nazis and was under the command of the Polish
government-in-exile in London. Stalin broke relations with the
government-in-exile in 1943.
   The television news commentator said it is probable that among
the victims buried in the cemetery are a Home Army general and a
group of teen-age Boy Scouts who fought in the Warsaw Uprising
against the Nazis in the closing days of World War II.
   The commentator said it had been determined that the youngest
person buried in the parish cemetery was 17 years old.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
