<FIRST>r a AM-PekinRacism     10-24 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pekin Racism,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>High School Reinstates Lyrics of Fight Song After Racist Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEKIN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at a high school here reinstated a
25-year-old fight chant one month after it was shelved when a
student complained that it contained a subliminal salute to the Ku
Klux Klan.
   ``To say that an innocent cadence, which happens to have a
`K-K-K' in it, is racist is stretching things a little bit,'' said
Chic Renner, school board president, on Tuesday.
   A student complained on Sept. 18 about the traditional chant at
Pekin High School. Superintendant Jack Wilt agreed and ordered
changes in the final line of the chant: ``P-P-P-E-K, K-K-K-I-N.
P-E-K, K-I-N. Pekin, Pekin, Pekin.''
   The new lyrics spelled out ``Dragon,'' the school mascot. But
officials said fans found the chant awkward.
   Wilt said he and principal Bill Rees reconsidered the issue last
Thursday and decided they had gone too far in ordering it
re-written.
   ``I thought the original decision was correct, but it seemed
Rees and I were the only ones who thought so,'' Wilt said. ``Some
people felt that maybe we had over-reacted.''
   Wilt said Tuesday he still believes the ``Pekin'' chant, with
its repetition of ``K-K-K,'' contains a racist overtone ``if viewed
in a narrow context.''
   ``But we decided that no racism was intended and that maybe we
over-reacted, so we changed it back,'' Wilt said. ``I hope this is
the end of it.''
   Pekin is sensitive to the racism issue after allegations that
black students from Peoria and Champaign were harassed by students
from the predominantly white Pekin High School twice in the 1988-89
school year.
</TEXT>
