<FIRST>r w AM-Mitterrand-Kurds     10-24 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mitterrand-Kurds,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>French First Lady Appeals To Congress, Democracies, To Save Kurds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France's first lady, Danielle Mitterrand, on
Tuesday brought an impassioned appeal to Congress to help save the
Kurdish people from annihilation.
   ``Do not forget them. Silence is killing them,'' she told the
gongressional Human Rights Caucus.
   ``They are all individuals in distress and their people is in
danger of extinction,'' Mrs. Mitterrand said. Several Kurdish women
in the packed hearing room wept during her speech.
   There are an estimated 20 million Kurds scattered among Turkey,
Iraq, Iran, Syria, Lebanon and the Soviet Union. They have been
subjected to persecution in all these countries, especially in Iraq
which is strongly believed to have bombarded them with poison gas
last year.
   Iraq has denied the accusation, but one of three American
physicians who visited Kurdish refugees from Iraq in Turkish camps
told the caucus his team found conclusive evidence of poison gas
symptoms. Robert Mullen Cook-Deegan said refugees described eye,
lung and gastro-intestinal irritation, consistent with the known
effects of poison gas.
   Mrs. Mitterrand, a noted human rights activist who co-sponsored
the first international forum on the plight of the Kurds last week
in Paris, described her visit last May to the same Turkish camps
the physicians visited.
   Without directly criticizing Iraq, which is one of France's
biggest weapons clients, Mrs. Mitterrand said the Kurdish refugees
clearly do not believe assurances by the Iraqi government that they
can return home without fear of persecution.
   ``The result is that the Iraqi Kurds in Turkey are in a
desperate situation: They can neither go home _ which is their
deepest wish _ nor become integrated into the Kurdish population in
Turkey,'' she said.
   Mrs. Mitterrand said she visited the camps, despite attempts by
Turkish authorities to dissuade her, and encountered ``dreadful''
living conditions at the barbed-wire enclosures where more than
30,000 Kurdish refugees are incarcerated.
   The only help can come from the world's democratic governments,
she said.
   Members of the caucus said Congress had ignored the Kurdish
tragedy for too long. ``This is one of the most flagrant examples
of man's inhumanity to man,'' said Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
   ``The brutal Iraqi campaign to eradicate the Kurds must be
condemned,'' he said. More than 60,000 Kurds fled the Iraqi attacks
``and we must act now to ensure it never, never happens again.''
</TEXT>
