<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 2044EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NYCPolitics     10-24 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYC Politics,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polls Show Dinkins Support Slipping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic mayoral candidate David Dinkins'
commanding lead in the polls over Republican Rudolph Giuliani has
shrunk in the aftermath of questions about his financial dealings,
a new poll indicates.
   Dinkins, who led Giuliani less than two weeks ago by about 20
percent, was picked by 45 percent compared with 41 percent for
Giuliani in the poll conducted for the New York Daily News and
WABC-TV.
   The poll of 500 voters, conducted Sunday, had a margin of error
of 5 percentage points.
   The poll was the first since the Sept. 12 Democratic primary to
show Dinkins' support at less than 50 percent.
   The Daily News-WABC poll indicated the biggest shift in support
occurred among Jewish voters, who last week favored Dinkins by 10
points.
   Now, 44 percent of Jewish voters support Giuliani and 26 percent
support Dinkins, according to the poll. Twenty-six percent were
undecided, and 69 percent were not strongly committed to either
candidate.
   Dinkins on Monday compared the new poll results to those done
shortly before the Democratic primary ``that suggested that (Mayor
Edward) Koch and I were neck and neck. We of course were not and
the outcome was not what they predicted.
   ``I suspect that's the case here,'' he said.
   However, Dinkins said he had ``anticipated there would be some
fall-off'' in support among all voters due to the recent
controversy over his finances.
   Political analysts have said Dinkins' loss of support may be due
to questions about his finances, including his failure to pay taxes
from 1969 to 1973 and discrepancies in the stated value of stock he
transferred to his son.
   Dinkins has denied any wrongdoing.
   Giuliani said the poll results confirm ``what I've been seeing
in the streets in the last three or four weeks.''
   He said voters ``want fundamental change. They want honest,
reformed government. I think they realize ... that David Dinkins
isn't up to the task of being mayor.''
</TEXT>
