<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1729EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-WeaponsPlants     10-24 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weapons Plants,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Admits Questionable Payments to Atomic Weapons Producers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department acknowledged Tuesday it
may have erred in rewarding the private operators of several of its
nuclear weapons plants with millions of dollars in bonuses despite
serious failings to protect the health and safety of workers and
nearby residents.
   The admission came from Henson Moore, the deputy energy
secretary, and other department officials during a grilling by a
House Government Operations subcommittee, which documented the
bonus payments to operators of the Rocky Flats plutonium processing
plant and the Savannah River nuclear production center.
   Savannah River, the nation's only source of tritium used to make
nuclear warheads, has been closed for more than a year because of
safety and technical problems that prompted the department to
switch management companies there last April.
   The Rocky Flats plant, situated about 16 miles from Denver, is
in disarray and is under FBI investigation for possible criminal
violation of environmental laws.
   ``There is room for real question'' about whether the Energy
Department should have paid $912,000 in bonuses last year to the
top 25 E.I. du Pont de Nemours &amp; Co. managers of the Savannah River
plant near Aiken, S.C., Moore said in sworn testimony.
   He acknowledged that the three highest-paid Du Pont executives,
with collective government salaries of $561,000 and bonuses of
$306,000 in 1988, were not based at the plant site. They worked at
Du Pont headquarters at Wilmington, Del.
   Separately, government auditors disclosed Tuesday that Du Pont
on Sept. 27, 1988, told the Energy Department that some of the
reactor fuel and ``targets'' used to produce tritium at Savannah
River were defective and that others might be defective as well.
The department immediately ordered Du Pont to stop making the fuel
and targets and to investigate whether the problem might
jeoparidize safety.
   Several months later it was decided there was no safety problem,
but the Energy Department did not approve a plan for improving
manufacturing of the fuel and targets until earlier this month, the
General Accounting Office said in a report to Congress.
   Replacing the defective and suspect materials will cost at least
$731,000 and possibly an additional $8 million, depending on how
the problem is resolved, the GAO said.
   Over the objections of the Energy Department's legal staff, Rep.
Mike Synar, D-Okla., chairman of the House subcommittee, released
figures on salaries and bonuses paid to Du Pont executives in each
of the past five years. In what Synar called a compromise with the
department, the subcommittee withheld the names and job titles of
the Du Pont managers.
   Moore said that to release the managers' names would unfairly
subject them to ``public abuse.''
   From 1984 through 1988, the top 25 Du Pont executives in charge
of running Savannah River got $12.7 million in salaries plus $3.5
million in performance bonuses from the Energy Department, the
figures showed.
   Westinghouse Savannah River Co. took over as operator at the
plant last April 1. Moore told the committee that the top
Westinghouse executives are paid less than the Du Pont managers
were, and that all top Westinghouse managers are stationed at the
plant. Moore did not provide exact figures for Westhinghouse
salaries or bonuses.
   Synar also questioned why the department paid Rockwell
International Corp. $26.8 million in bonus money in the 1986-88
fiscal years for running Rocky Flats in a period when the plant was
cited for numerous flaws in safety and health protection.
   The GAO, in a separate report released at the subcommitee
hearing, said the department, in its ratings used to set Rockwell's
semi-annual bonus awards, deliberately played down or ignored
negative information about the company's performance.
   Bruce Twining, who headed the Energy Department regional office
in Albuquerque, N.M., that approved the bonus payments to Rockwell,
admitted under questioning from Synar that the department probably
went too easy on Rockwell.
   ``Looking back from today, those ratings could clearly be
questioned,'' Twining said.
   Rockwell announced last month that it was withdrawing from its
Rocky Flats contract next January because of a disagreement with
the Energy Department over the company's potential liability for
environmental violations at the plant.
   Moore disclosed that EG&amp;G Inc., which will take over as operator
of Rocky Flats when Rockwell leaves, will be paid $15 million in
advance for one year's work. After the first year, its earnings
will be pegged to performance ratings by the department, he said.
</TEXT>
