<FIRST>u a AM-RockHall     10-24 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rock Hall,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rock Hall Class of 1990 Selected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Who, Bobby Darin, the Four Tops and Simon
and Garfunkel were among eight recording artists selected Tuesday
to the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame.
   They will be inducted in January in New York City along with The
Four Seasons, The Kinks, The Platters and Hank Ballard in the class
of 1990.
   Their selections bring to 43 the number of recording acts chosen
for the hall of fame.
   In addition to the recording artists, three ``early
influencers'' were selected to be honored at the as-yet unbuilt
hall of fame and museum _ jazz singer-trumpeter Louis Armstrong,
jazz guitarist Charlie Christian and blues pioneer Ma Rainey.
   This year's selection of inductees was announced at a news
conference by Paul Shaffer, band leader on NBC's ``Late Night with
David Letterman'' and musical director of the rock hall induction
ceremony the past three years.
   ``This is a big year for me, personally. It's starting to move
into my era,'' Shaffer quipped. ``The first album I ever bought was
a Four Seasons Golden Hits. I still have that record I bought.''
   ``Bobby Darin was an idol of mine. I love the Four Tops. Simon
and Garfunkel. Hank Ballard. ... I'm thrilled with this year's
inductees,'' he said.
   Rock music historian Norm N. Nite, who has two syndicated radio
rock 'n' roll oldies shows, called the latest group of selections
``a good cross section'' of musical style. Nite, a member of the
rock hall board, said the class represents an effort to honor
entertainers who are long overdue for recognition.
   ``We're trying to get caught up on a lot of people owed getting
in. As years go by, it will get tighter and tighter,'' Nite said.
   Two songwriting teams will be inducted in the non-performing
music industry category, although some have been important
performers as well. The writers include the teams of Brian Holland,
Lamont Dozier and Eddie Holland, and Gerry Goffin and Carole King.
   Groundbreaking for the $48 million hall of fame and museum is
set for next year in downtown Cleveland next to the Cuyahoga River.
Larry Thompson, who is heading a fund-raising effort in Cleveland,
said he hopes to reach an interim goal of $40 million by Nov. 15.
   The hall of fame and museum is to open in 1992.
   More than 200 performers, producers, writers, record executives
and broadcasters cast ballots this year.
   Inducted earlier this year were Dion, Otis Redding, The Rolling
Stones, The Temptations and Stevie Wonder.
   The 1988 artists class included The Beach Boys, The Beatles, The
Drifters, Bob Dylan and The Supremes.
   The 1987 group was made up of The Coasters, Eddie Cochran, Bo
Diddley, Aretha Franklin, Marvin Gaye, Bill Haley, B.B. King, Clyde
McPhatter, Ricky Nelson, Roy Orbison, Carl Perkins, Smokey
Robinson, Joe Turner, Muddy Waters and Jackie Wilson.
   The original 1986 group was Chuck Berry, James Brown, Ray
Charles, Sam Cooke, Fats Domino, Everly Brothers, Buddy Holly,
Jerry Lee Lewis, Elvis Presley and Little Richard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
