<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 2112EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HealthCare     10-24 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Health Care,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Urged To Open Up Access To Health Care System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private insurance and health care should be
opened up to more people through a system of legal requirements and
increased taxes, state and congressional officials said Tuesday.
   ``Although we may not be able to provide universal health care
in our country at this time, we ought to provide universal access
to health insurance in the private sector,'' said Rep Doug Walgren,
D-Pa.
   Rep. Edward Roybal, D-Calif., chairman of the House Select
Committee on Aging proposed a ``rearrangement of present plans ...
to place the burdens on all Americans'' in his testimony at a
hearing of the U.S. Bipartisan Commission on Comprehensive Health
Care.
   ``We must be able to expand the cigarette tax,'' Walgren said,
explaining that surveys show Americans are willing to pay increased
taxes to solve pressing national and ethical problems such as
health care.
   Walgren, a member of the House Energey and Commerce subcommittee
on health and environment complained that health insurers want to
provide coverage only to the healthy leaving 20 percent of all
applicants for private insurance without adequate coverage because
of exclusions or above-average premiums for pre-existing medical
conditions.
   He has introduced legislation to prohibit private insurers from
denying coverage in such situations.
   Expansion of the payroll tax, increased estate and gift taxes
and universal mandatory health insurance are solutions to the
nation's health care crisis, said Barbara Matula, North Carolina's
Medicaid director.
   ``We are mandated to have car insurance and fire insurance. We
can be mandated to pay health insurance,'' said Matula, who
represented the American Public Welfare Association at Tuesday's
hearing.
   Business representatives argued mandated benefits would increase
costs and threaten the viability of small businesses that employ
most new American workers.
   But Matula insisted workers and employers not be allowed to opt
out of paying health insurance premiums because they would provide
funding for coverage for themselves, their families and the
unemployed.
   While not offering specific strategies or solutions, Melvin
Glasser, director of the Committee for National Health Insurance, a
20-year-old coalition of about 40 individuals and labor leaders
pleaded with the commission not to ``try again to resort to
piecemeal, patchwork methods'' like the catastrophic health care
program.
   The House repealed the program outright and the Senate
drastically cut its funding. The differences among lawmakers are
being worked out by a budget conference committee.
   The 15-member panel, known as the Pepper Commission for the late
Florida congressman who was its first chairman and creator, was
born in the catastrophic care law. It is to submit to Congress a
proposal for health care reforms entailing what benefits to provide
to whom and how to pay for them.
   There are an estimated 31 million people who have no health
insurance, more than 9 million Americans who need long-term care
and 13.5 million underinsured who can not get adequate health care
because of financial constraints.
   The commission is scheduled to hold at least one additional
hearing before making its final report to Congress by March 1, 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
