<FIRST>u i AM-NATO 1stLd-Writethru a0617 10-24 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0617,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ministers Discuss Space, Nuclear Capabilities</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with comment after Tuesday meeting,
details. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VILAMOURA, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's defense minister said
Tuesday the Kremlin admission that one of its radars violates the
1972 ABM treaty was a ``remarkable'' example of the change taking
place in the Soviet Union.
   Gerhard Stoltenberg said the speech Monday by Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze containing the statement was ``a
true sign of glasnost,'' the policy of openness promoted by
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Stoltenberg and the other NATO defense ministers are in this
resort for a semiannual meeting of the Western alliance's Nuclear
Planning Group.
   ``The fact that he stands up and says straight out that
Krasnoyarsk was a violation of the anti-ballistic missile treaty is
a whole new language,'' Stoltenberg told reporters after the
Tuesday afternoon session.
   He said there had been no time for a full analysis of the
changes under way in the Soviet bloc.
   Frits Bolkestein, the Dutch defense minister, said the final
statement Wednesday was expected to welcome Shevardnadze's pledge
that the Krasnoyarsk radar in Siberia would be dismantled.
   ``It was an acknowledgement of what the United States has
maintained for a long time ... and we obviously applaud this
recognition,'' said a senior U.S. official, who demanded anonymity.
   Shevardnadze, speaking to the Soviet legislature, said the
Krasnoyarsk radar had been a stumbling block to agreement with the
West on other arms issues.
   ``We are saving the ABM treaty and opening the way to the
conclusion of a treaty on strategic weapons,'' Shevardnadze said.
   He also said the Soviet Union was prepared to withdraw all
military forces to its own territory by the year 2000 and negotiate
elimination of the opposing NATO and Warsaw Pact alliances.
   The NATO defense ministers, meeting for two days at the Quinta
do Lago vacation complex on Portugal's southern Algarve coast,
rejected the latter idea.
   ``I can assure you, we're not thinking of disbanding NATO,''
Stoltenberg said, and called Shevardnadze's offer ``an old formula
... more vague and abstract'' than before.
   Bolkestein said: ``There's not much left of the Warsaw Pact in
terms of true cohesion. The same thing cannot be said of NATO.''
   Hungary and Poland have are moving away from one-party Communist
rule and Moscow has made no move to stop them, but they have sworn
continued allegiance to the Eastern defense alliance.
   Stoltenberg said ministers agreed Tuesday that the future role
of NATO nuclear forces would be studied after the signing of a
conventional arms reduction treaty, expected at the end of talks
now being conducted in Vienna, Austria.
   He said he expected preliminary drafts of six papers for the
study to be ready next year and anticipated ``concrete proposals''
by 1991.
   During the morning session, U.S. Defense Secretary Dick Cheney
said Soviet spending on strategic and space weapons had not slowed
under Gorbachev's program of reform, officials reported.
   U.S. aides estimated the Kremlin spends $20 billion to $40
billion a year on its space program, Dutch officials said.
   All 16 NATO nations attend the nuclear strategy sessions except
France, which is not a member of NATO's integrated military
structure. Iceland, which has no armed forces, attends as an
observer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
