<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-24 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rainy, Windy, Snow In Pacific States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stormy weather spread wind and rain across the Pacific Coast
with snow inland over the mountains Tuesday, while the extreme
north-central part of the nation basked in record warmth.
   A cold front pushing in from the Gulf of Alaska was followed by
showers and thunderstorms Tuesday over northern California and
western Oregon.
   Snow fell at some higher elevations of California and
west-central Nevada.
   Upper elevations of the Sierra Nevada above Lake Tahoe received
1 to 2 feet of snow late Monday and into early Tuesday, the
National Weather Service said. An additional 4 to 6 inches of was
expected on the eastern slopes of the central Sierra Nevada.
   The storm that arrived Monday, the first real snow storm of the
season, forced closure of a state highway into Yosemite National
Park and prompted the California Highway Patrol to require chains
on roads through the mountains.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were scattered along the
east coast of Florida during the afternoon, and a few showers were
scattered along the coast of Texas.
   Heaviest rainfall during the six-hour period up to 2 p.m. EDT
was 1.09 inches at West Palm Beach, Fla.
   Early morning dense fog was reported in Lower Michigan,
northeastern Illinois, southwestern Ohio and east-central Louisiana.
   Record temperatures were 76 at Fargo, N.D., and 73 at
International Falls, Minn., the town in extreme northern Minnesota
that usually calls itself the nation's icebox.
   Temperatures dipped into the 20s and 30s overnight in the
Rockies, the northern Atlantic Coast, the northern Plains, the
upper Mississippi Valley, the upper Great Lakes and the middle
Atlantic Coast region.
   Tuesday morning's low for the Lower 48 states was 12 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
</TEXT>
