<FIRST>r w AM-HUDProbe-Cushing     10-24 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe-Cushing,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Talking With Cushing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional investigators have held talks
with an attorney for a main figure in the probe of scandals at the
Department of Housing and Urban Development, but a spokesman for
the panel chairman said Tuesday they have not offered immunity to
obtain testimony.
   Bob King, administrative assistant to Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif.,
chairman of a subcommittee investigating the department, said talks
have taken place between the panel's staff and a lawyer for R.
Hunter Cushing, former deputy assistant secretary at HUD.
   King said Cushing has begun to cooperate and provide information
to the panel.
   Cushing is one of four former HUD officials who has cited
constitutional rights against self-incrimination in refusing to
testify before Congress in its investigation of alleged influence
peddling, fraud and mismanagement in the department.
   Citing sources it did not identify, The New York Times reported
Tuesday that the House panel has begun immunity discussions with
Cushing's attorney.
   King said immunity has not been discussed or considered,
although he did not rule it out. ``At this point, Mr. Lantos isn't
thinking about doing that,'' King said.
   Jamie Gorelick, Cushing's attorney, said she has met with staff
of Lantos' subcommittee but she declined to comment on the subject
of the talks. Stuart Weisberg, staff director of the panel, also
declined to comment on the content of the talks.
   Cushing had been scheduled to appear before the subcommittee of
the House Government Operations Committee last week, but Lantos
cancelled the meeting, saying he needed to return to his Northern
California district because of the earthquake.
   Gorelick said ``it was unclear what was going to happen on that
date,'' had the meeting been held. She said, ``It might be a little
strong to say he's cooperating'' with the panel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
