<DOCNO> AP891024-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1854EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SF-Quake-880Theories     10-24 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF-Quake-880 Theories,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Theories Abound on Why Killer Highway Failed. ^With AM-SF Quake,
Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a governor's panel prepares to
probe the deadly earthquake-collapse of Interstate 880, outsiders
are hurling their theories at state officials inundated by ``Monday
morning quarterbacks.''
   California Transportation Department officials have declined to
speculate on the collapse and are refusing to share information
they might have about why a 1\-mile section of freeway in Oakland
fell down in the massive quake.
   Thirty-nine bodies have been recovered from the rubble of I-880
_ making up more than half the 63 quake casualties. More are
expected from the collapse as rescuers carefully search the
unstable rubble.
   Outside engineers and structural experts, whose views are being
sought largely by the news media, are blaming everything from a
lack of steel in the vertical columns to unstable soil beneath the
structure and the peculiar way the structure may have synchronized
with earthquake waves.
   Few have visited the wreckage and must draw their conclusions
from news accounts and pictures. Caltrans ``is still not letting
anybody in but their own people to take a look,'' complained
scientist Glenn Borchardt, an expert on soil stability with the
state Division of Mines and Geology.
   ``We're not going to get into that,'' said Caltrans structural
chief Jim Roberts when asked again if the department has ideas
about the cause of the collapse. The department maintains that it
was as surprised as Gov. George Deukmejian that the structure fell
down, and spokesman Jim Drago said the agency is tired of all the
``Monday morning quarterbacks.''
   ``I've been assured there were no experts, no studies, no data
that suggested in any way that it would fall,'' said Caltrans
Director Robert Best.
   But in the quake's wake, experts are offering their theories,
and old studies and documents are beginning to surface.
   Generally, experts and Caltrans agree on a general observation:
the structure, opened in July 1957, was built with out-of-date
earthquake safety codes, and the materials used, such as concrete,
are not as strong as material available today.
   Beyond that, the theories are varied.
   Among them:
   _An engineer hired by The New York Times, Dr. Piotr D. Moncarz
of Palo Alto, who was able to visit the site, suggested that the
freeway was brought down partly because seismic waves coincided
with the swinging of the structure, amplifying the quake's power.
   _Soils expert Borchardt, who first raised the soil instability
issue in a 1982 report on earthquake dangers, said the ground
beneath the structure, made up largely of clay, may have
``liquefied'' or at least ``amplified'' the quake's effect.
   _Former state highway engineer Jim See said the freeway fell
because reinforcing bar in the concrete pillars was not braced or
wrapped with more steel.
   _Dr. Nigel Priestly, a structural expert at the University of
California at San Diego, said lack of steel in the columns
contributed to their collapse, but added that steel connections
holding the roadway to the columns also were suspect.
   _John Kariotis, a South Pasadena structural engineer, said the
columns could have been strengthened with steel jackets to avoid
collapse, an argument rejected by Roberts, who said their own
experiments showed that wouldn't have worked.
   In the end, Drago said, all the theories might turn out to be
correct, but they're little help now because ``You never get two
engineers to agree on anything.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
