<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 2200EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Arctic-DemilitarizedZone     10-24 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arctic-Demilitarized Zone,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Proposes Creating Arctic Demilitarized Zone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada should help create a demilitarized zone in
the Arctic, a panel recommended Tuesday at a conference on
cooperation with the Soviet Union.
   The proposal came as part of arms-control discussions for the
region by the 13-member panel that included disarmament experts,
retired Canadian military officers and native Indian
representatives.
   The recommendations, including an end to simulated bombings over
the region, came on the second day of a four-day conference on
Canadian-Soviet Arctic cooperation.
   In its recommendations, the panel said the Arctic should be made
into a demilitarized zone that prohibits military aircraft carrying
nuclear weapons from flying in or out of the region.
   However, it said under its proposal that members of NATO and the
Warsaw Pact would be allowed to fly over the region to verify
arms-control agreements.
   The panel also said the superpowers should agree to strict
limits or a total ban on sea-launched cruise missiles from Arctic
waters.
   The group further called for the Soviet Union to agree to keep
its submarines out of Canada's Arctic waters and halt weapons tests
at Novaya Zemlya in the Soviet Arctic.
   At a conference dinner Monday, Canada's junior minister for
Indian and northern affairs said negotiating Arctic security issues
outside of East-West arms talks now under way could prove
destabilizing.
   The minister, Kim Campbell, said the best way to ensure peace
and security in the Arctic ``is to lend full support to the
East-West negotiations on arms control.''
   Andrei Granowsky, a Soviet Foreign Ministry official, said he
couldn't comment officially because the conference proposals didn't
come from the Canadian government. However, he said Soviets
attending the conference had welcomed the ideas.
   ``We appreciate the fact that Canadian scholars are expressing
new ideas to strengthen security in the region,'' he said. ``We
need a stockpile of ideas for future dialogue. We ourselves are
searching for new concepts.''
   The conference was sponsored by the Arms Control Center, an
independent Ottawa think-tank, and the Union of the Soviet
Friendship Societies, a group that promotes multinational
cooperation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
