<FIRST>r w AM-SF-Quake-CalDelegation     10-24 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF-Quake-Cal Delegation,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>California State Lawmakers Encouraged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California state lawmakers who spent Tuesday
in Washington said they were encouraged by meetings with
administration officials and a House vote for an earthquake relief
package, but the praise was less than unanimous.
   ``We think we have been very successful here as it relates to
the administration,'' said State Senator Bill Campbell, discussing
meetings held with a variety of federal officials. ``Our
congressional delegation has been successful.''
   ``We're very happy with our input here,'' said Campbell, a
Republican.
   Campbell said the group of six assembly members and four
senators met with Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner, Housing
Secretary Jack Kemp, acting Federal Emergency Management Agency
chief Grant Peterson; the deputy director of the Office of
Management and Budget and a member of the White House staff.
   He said that among the progress made was a ``commitment (by
FEMA) to look at the idea'' of sending in trailers to house the
8,000 to 10,000 people left homeless in Santa Cruz and Watsonville
areas south of San Francisco; a commitment from FEMA to extend
emergency housing grants to three months for renters and more than
four months for homeowners if needed; a promise to expand the
number of disaster application centers if necessary; and a move by
Kemp to free $500 million for earthquake aid.
   Campbell also said that the Small Business Administration will
get together with the Office of Management and Budget to talk about
raising the current cap on home repair loans by the Small Business
Administration from $100,000 to $500,000.
   Lawmakers say raising the cap is necessary given the high cost
of real estate in the area and it could be done with an
administrative order if budget director Richard Darman would agree.
   The aid package passed by the House includes a requirement that
the cap be raised. Californians have argued that the action would
be too slow.
   State Assemblyman Richard Katz, a Democrat who heads the
Assembly's Transportation Committee, said he was generally
satisfied with the response from Washington but was concerned about
the source of the $1 billion in bridge and road repair funds from
Tuesday's House-passed legislation.
   ``The billion dollars that you heard talked about for
transportation to some extent right now is a fiction,'' he said.
``It's a billion dollars that would have come to California anyhow
over the next several years, and under the current proposal we're
getting it earlier.''
   ``We will go back to the state today with better feelings than
we came, more work that needs to be done,'' he said. ``We will go
into special session next week and we will probably either generate
some sales tax revenue or some additional revenue on our side to do
part of the job from our standpoint. But again, we're going to need
additional help from the White House.''
</TEXT>
