<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0646 10-24 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0646,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab League Vows to Help Rid Lebanon of Syrian Troops</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-9 pvs with 9 grafs to ADD Fahd quotes. Picks up
graf 10 pvs, `But as ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arab League on Tuesday promised
an accord for a complete Syrian troop withdrawal from Lebanon,
where Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun rejected a peace plan that
lacks a timetable.
   Thousands of Aoun supporters demonstrated in Beirut on Tuesday
and burned tires in the streets after Moslem and Christian members
of Lebanon's Parliament approved the plan in Taif, Saudi Arabia, on
Sunday.
   The peace plan, which is aimed at ending 14 years of
Christian-Moslem fighting, gives more political power to the Moslem
majority. It also says Syria, which backs Moslem leaders, must pull
its troops out of the Lebanese capital within two years.
   But the forces, estimated at 40,000, could remain in the eastern
Bekaa valley near the Syrian border, and the plan had no timetable
for a total withdrawal.
   The Arab League said the duration of the Syrian forces' stay in
the Bekaa ``will be defined by an accord between the Syrian and
Lebanese governments.'' The 22-member Arab League, it said, ``will
be charged with concluding and implementing that accord.''
   The commitment came in a document read by Saudi Foreign Minister
Prince Saud al-Faisal at the closing session of the Lebanese
Parliament that was called by the Arab League.
   The document called on the Lebanese Parliament to meet in
Lebanon no later than Nov. 7 to ratify political reforms that were
agreed upon in the peace plan and to elect a president for their
fractured nation.
   The five-page document was signed by the Arab League committee,
comprising King Fahd of Saudi Arabia, Morocco's King Hassan II and
Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid. The three leaders were asked
by an Arab League summit meeting in May to try to help find a
settlement to the sectarian turmoil in Lebanon.
   King Fahd, chairing the closing session in the Red Sea port of
Jiddah, told the 63 Parliamentarians present that the peace plan
reached in the resort of Taif was a ``great achievement.''
   He thanked Syrian President Hafez Assad and President Saddam
Hussein of Iraq for their cooperation, indicating he had won
approval from the two enemies to stop arming rival factions in
Lebanon. Saddam backs the Christians, and Assad is the Moslems'
main supporter.
   Fahd promised unspecified financial support to ``restore Lebanon
better than it was'' once the peace plan is carried out.
   But as the final meeting got under way, 10,000 young followers
of Aoun marched through the Christian enclave north of Beirut to
protest the accord.
   Addressing the demonstrators, Aoun said the reference in the
peace accord to the timing of a Syrian withdrawal ``is very vague,
from now until eternity.''
   ``We don't want to give away our beloved land,'' he said.
   The peace accord also would eventually lead to the disbanding of
militias, and the main Shiite groups, the Syrian-backed Amal and
the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, have rejected the accord. Druse warlord
Walid Jumblatt also has criticized it.
   Samir Geagea, who commands the main Christian militia, the
Lebanese Forces, still has not committed himself either way.
   Syrian forces came to Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
Peacekeeping mandate and now control 70 percent of Lebanese
territory. Aoun claims the Syrians have violated their mandate by
siding with Moslems in the civil war, and his 20,000 troops fought
the Syrians for six months until the Arab League-brokered
cease-fire Sept. 22.
   Aoun, a Maronite Catholic, has not openly criticized any of the
political reforms suggested in the peace charter that are mainly
designed to give Moslems an equal share of power with the
Christians.
   These include increasing Parliament seats from 99 to 108, to
give Moslems equal representation in the legislature.
   The reforms also redistribute the powers of the president,
traditionally a Maronite Catholic, the prime minister, a Sunni
Moslem, and the Parliament speaker, a Shiite Moslem, to ensure
wider Moslem participation in the decision-making process.
   Christians have dominated power since independence from France
in 1943, when they were considered the majority. Moslems now make
up 55 percent of the population of 4 million.
   Lebanon has been without a head of state since Amin Gemayel's
term expired Sept. 22, 1988, with Parliament unable to meet to
elect a successor. The vacuum produced two rival Cabinets, one
Christian headed by Aoun, and a Syrian-backed government headed by
Salim Hoss, a Sunni.
</TEXT>
