<FIRST>r a AM-Jaycees-SovietUnion     10-24 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jaycees-Soviet Union,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaycees President Hopes To Start Soviet Chapter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDNEY, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national Jaycees president said Tuesday
he plans to go to the Soviet Union in December to help three
Estonian groups become chapters of the service organization.
   ``If we can get them going in the Soviet Union, we can get in
the other Eastern bloc nations as well,'' said Robby Dawkins, U.S.
Jaycees president.
   Dawkins was in Nebraska to recognize the state's high national
ranking in the organization.
   He said in a telephone interview he would go to the Soviet Union
Dec. 1-15 ``to try to start Jaycees chapters behind the Iron
Curtain.''
   ``If we can get the Jaycees started over there, and if they
don't get oppressed and they are free to learn and grow as
individuals, then we might possibly be changing the course of
history in the next 25 years when those people who were in Jaycees
become the leaders,'' he said.
   The U.S. Jaycees began 70 years ago with 29 chapters and has
grown to 240,000 members in 5,000 communities, he said. There are
Jaycees chapters in 93 countries, including Poland where one began
about two years ago, Dawkins said.
</TEXT>
