<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 2207EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev-Economy     10-24 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Economy,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Predicts Better Times Within 18 Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev sees rosier
prospects in 12-18 months for his campaign to improve the economy
and put more consumer goods on the shelves, Tass reported Tuesday.
   The official news agency said the Gorbachev, who has pressed for
reform since gaining power in March 1985, spoke to journalists from
the Communist Party daily Pravda on Monday. Ivan T. Frolov, a
Gorbachev confidant, was named editor-in-chief of Pravda last week.
   Concern is widespread that people may go hungry this winter
because of food shortages, which have caused rationing of meat, tea
and other staples. Ethnic violence has contributed to shortages in
some areas and has raised fears of mass unrest.
   Such problems have created disenchantment with Gorbachev's
``perestroika'' reform program and some people even blame it for
the nation's woes.
   Gorbachev told Pravda reporters ``the acuteness of the problems
encountered by the country should be alleviated ... within 12-18
months,'' Tass said, paraphrasing his remarks and not giving
reasons for such a precise forecast.
   It said Gorbachev expressed confidence that, ``rallying all
scientists and creative people in society, the country will be able
to improve the financial situation and the situation in the
consumer market, continue and deepen economic reform, arrest
negative processes and set the beginning to the improvement of the
situation.''
   He said ``unpopular measures'' might be needed, Tass reported
without giving details.
   The agency's dispatch said Gorbachev felt the most important
contribution the press could make at this stage was to ``promote
the values and ideas of perestroika.''
</TEXT>
