<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1927EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Watsonville     10-24 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Watsonville,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Meets with Watsonville Officials on Quake Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATSONVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. George Deukmejian said Tuesday
that tax increases to pay for last week's devastating earthquake
would be a last resort he would turn to only if federal aid and the
state surplus prove insufficient.
   ``I certainly have not ruled out the possibility of a tax
increase,'' the governor said after a briefing with disaster
officials in Watsonville, California's ``salad bowl,'' where much
of the state's lettuce, artichokes and berries are harvested.
   ``We are going to have to see whether or not there is going to
be a need for additional revenues,'' said Deukmejian, speaking to
reporters over the din of power saws, hammers and tractors in the
central city.
   ``We are waiting to see what the federal government is going to
do. They are moving very quickly,'' the governor said.
   The U.S. House on Tuesday passed a $2.85 billion aid package and
sent the measure to the Senate. The state surplus stands at $1
billion.
   Deukmejian on Monday said a special session of the state
Legislature would be called in the next two weeks to evaluate
earthquake damage and arrange for relief that could include a
temporary increase in sales or gasoline taxes.
   The Legislature completed its 1989 session Sept. 16 and is not
due to return until January.
   The governor also said Monday that he and legislative leaders
discussed the possibility of holding an earlier, special election
to consider a ballot measure currently slated for June 1990. That
proposal would liberalize the state's spending limit and pave the
way for a gradual 9-cent gasoline tax increase.
   The governor flew to Watsonville on Tuesday for a briefing on
damages by city Fire Chief Gary Smith, who said, ``Hopefully within
the year we will be back on our feet and you won't even notice.''
   As of Tuesday, the damage total was near a half-billion dollars
in Watsonville, a community of 27,000 people. Regionwide, estimates
topped $7 billion from the Oct. 17 quake.
   The city's Main Street was still cordoned off and thousands of
people either displaced from their homes or too frightened to
return indoors, congregated in makeshift tent cities.
   Outside Salvation Army headquarters, about 50 people lined up
for tents, sleeping bags, clothing, food and household items. But
outside the Main Street area, businesses were open.
   Spokeswoman Colleen McQuillan said the Red Cross fed breakfast
to 5,357 people Tuesday. The city estimates 1,200 residents are out
of their homes because of the quake, while Red Crross and Salvation
Army say up to 5,000 people are sleeping in tents.
   Deukmejian met privately with officials in City Hall, and later
with Smith in an open session. Spokesman Kevin Brett said it was
unnecessary for the governor to get out of his car to see the
damage or suffering.
   ``As you are driving into town, the damage is very evident,''
Brett said.
</TEXT>
