<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1929EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Intelligence     10-24 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Intelligence,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sen. Boren Says No Difference With Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE P. HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate intelligence
committee said Tuesday that he and President Bush have ``no
philosophical difference'' about easing guidelines for involvement
by CIA operatives in coups in which a foreign leader might be
killed.
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla, said he wanted to clear up ambiguities
in the guidelines within ``a matter of days or a few weeks as
opposed to months.''
   Saying that reports of disagreement with Bush were greatly
exaggerated, Boren said, ``We're working in perfect harmony. We
have not had a quarrelsome word about it. We have no philosophical
difference.''
   Bush had similar remarks about Boren the day before.
   The unsuccessful coup attempt against Panamanian Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega brought to light a series of classified guidelines
that restrict the actions of CIA officials under a longstanding
prohibition against assassinations.
   Bush reportedly complained last week in a private meeting that
an understanding reached between the Reagan administration and the
Senate intelligence panel could, if narrowly interpreted, require
the United States to warn Noriega of any coup that might endanger
his life.
   Boren confirmed that his committee and the Reagan administration
reached an understanding last year to restrict covert activities
against Noriega because of the presidential elections in the United
States.
   ``The committee said, `Let's wait _ we've got an election season
_ to let the new president-elect have some input into it,''' Boren
said.
   Boren, speaking with reporters at the White House, endorsed the
administation's call for a freer hand.
   ``I for one don't believe that the prohibition against
assassinations should keep you from working with someone that might
want to overthrow a government,'' Boren said.
   ``Those people wouldn't be aimed at hurting anyone or
assassinating anyone,'' the senator said. ``They want to overthrow
a government. You can't guarantee that someone might not get hurt
in overthrowing a government.
   ``I certainly don't believe there should be any affirmative
obligation to inform someone like Gen. Noriega of any plan that we
might learn about that might harm him in any way,'' he said. ``I
think that goes far beyond what the executive order ever intended.''
   Boren was among a group of senators that met with Bush on his
campaign for a cut in the capital gains tax rate. However, he was
questioned by reporters later about the restrictions on CIA agents.
   ``The president and I have not had a feud about this,'' Boren
said. ``In fact we were just joking about it a minute ago. We don't
know where the feud came from.''
</TEXT>
