<FIRST>u i AM-Peru     10-24 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Places Lima, Callao Under State of Emergency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government, in an effort to quell violence
by leftist guerrillas before municipal elections, on Tuesday placed
Lima and the nearby port of Callao under state-of-emergency rule
for 30 days.
   Rebels of the Maoist Shining Path movement have vowed to
sabotage the elections set for Nov. 12.
   Guerrillas late Monday seized 10 buses in Lima and Callao, five
miles west of the capital, and after ordering the occupants out
burned the vehicles, according to police. No one was injured in the
attacks.
   The state of emergency restricts civil rights, including the
right of free movement and guarantees against search and seizure,
and gives the military broad powers.
   Lima and Callao have been under a state of emergency almost
constantly since February 1986. The last decree affecting the two
cities expired in July.
   The government on Tuesday also extended state-of-emergency
restrictions in the Andean province of Yauyos in Lima department,
the official newspaper El Peruano reported.
   On Monday the government imposed emergency rule in four other
provinces in Lima department, giving the military control over most
of the state.
   A department is the largest political subdivision in Peru and is
divided into provinces.
   More than one third of Peru and about half of the country's 21
million people are now under emergency rule.
   The government has used state-of-emergency decrees to combat
terrorism since 1982. The decrees are normally for periods ranging
from 30 to 60 days and are routinely extended.
   Shining Path guerrillas began their compaign to gain power in
1980. The government has said more than 15,000 people have been
killed in violence related to the insurgency.
</TEXT>
