<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Apartheid     10-24 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Apartheid,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>300 Athletes Dropped from Anti-apartheid List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 athletes are being dropped
from a U.N. list aimed at isolating South Africa by drawing
attention to athletes who competed in its racially segregated
system, an official said Tuesday.
   Over 3,000 athletes are listed in the ``Register of Sports
Contacts with South Africa,'' which is put together by the U.N.
Special Committee Against Apartheid.
   By publishing the list of athletes and a similar list for
cultural events, the United Nations hopes to isolate South Africa
until it abolishes the apartheid system of racial discrimination.
   U.N. Ambassador James Gbeho of Ghana announced Tuesday that 328
cricket players and motorcyclists who competed in South Africa
before April 1 would be deleted from the list.
   The agreement to pare down the list was reached at the urging of
the International Cricket Conference and the International
Motorcycling Federation, both of which are shunning the apartheid
state, said Gbeho.
   However, the removal of names is on a one-time basis, and
cricketers and motorcyclists will still be added to the list if
they compete in South Africa in the future, he said.
   The deletions include motorcyclists from the United States,
Britain and 14 other countries.
</TEXT>
