<HEAD>Man Gets 5-25 Years in Burning of Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of dousing his pregnant
daughter with a flammable liquid and setting her on fire was
sentenced Tuesday to five to 25 years in prison, despite that the
girl had asked the judge to be lenient.
   Kimberly Richmond, 17, gave birth to a healthy girl by Caesarian
section just hours after she suffered second- and third-degree
burns on more than two-thirds of her body in July.
   Summit County Common Pleas Judge Glen B. Morgan sentenced Joseph
Richmond, 41, to five to 25 years for aggravated arson, three to 15
years for felonious assault and one year for child endangering.
   The sentences will run concurrently, but Richmond must serve at
least five years, said Dave Lombardi, law clerk for the judge.
   Ms. Richmond, who spent two months in a hospital burn unit
before her release Sept. 21, appeared in court Tuesday and asked
the judge to sentence her father to probation instead of a prison
term.
   ``I think it was an accident,'' she told the judge. ``I don't
want him to go to prison.''
   Ms. Richmond wore a neck brace and gauze gloves, but said she
felt all right. She also said her baby was doing fine.
   She declined to talk to reporters after the sentencing.
   On Sept. 26, Richmond pleaded guilty to the charges in
connection with the July 24 incident, which police said occurred
during a family argument.
   Authorities said Richmond told them he only wanted to scare his
daughter and didn't want to hurt her.
   Police said they thought the flammable liquid was brake fluid.
   Richmond initially pleaded innocent by reason of insanity to the
felony charges, but Morgan reviewed a psychiatric report and ruled
he was mentally competent to stand trial.
