<HEAD>Government Sues Better Homes Over Employee Relocations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department claimed Tuesday in a $7
million lawsuit that the government was defrauded by a company that
had a contract to relocate federal employees in 24 states.
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Des Moines, charges
that Better Homes and Gardens Family Relocation Service, a
subsidiary of Meredith Relocation Corp., defrauded the General
Services Administration on performance of the one-year contract.
   The company, required to purchase employees' homes at an
appraised value, was accused of intimidating independent appraisers
so it could buy houses at a reduced price.
   The suit also charges that the company deliberately placed
federal employees in a ``distress-sale situation'' and destroyed
records to cover up improper practices.
   The lawsuit charges violations of the False Claims Act, breach
of contract, unjust enrichment and common-law fraud, the department
said.
   The lawsuit was the result of joint investigation by the
inspectors general of GSA and the Interior and Agriculture
departments.
</TEXT>
