<FIRST>r i AM-CostaRica-Summit     10-24 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Costa Rica-Summit,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tight Security for Summit Meeting Because of Drug War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tight security will be in effect for
an 18-nation summit meeting because ``drug barons have put a price
on the heads of some presidents,'' presidential spokesman Jorge
Urbina said Tuesday.
   Urbina did not say if the government knew which presidents had
been threatened. Among the heads of state expected to attend the
conference Friday and Saturday are President Bush and Colombian
President Virgilio Barco, who are at the center of campaigns
against drug traffickers in their countries.
   Urbina said 4,000 policemen and security agents will be on duty
for the summit.
   Police were seen Tuesday stationed along the road from the
airport to San Jose and at strategic points in this city of 1
million.
   President Oscar Arias said Monday, ``We want to talk of
fraternity, dialogue, understanding'' at the meeting, which will
celebrate the 100th anniversary of Costa Rican democracy.
   He said he hoped the meeting would ``serve to eliminate fears
and encourage common undertakings that cannot wait any longer.''
   Arias won the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for his drafting of a
Central American peace accord.
   Also expected for the summit are the heads of state of Canada,
Brazil, Argentina, Venezuela, Uruguay, Paraguay, Bolivia, Ecuador,
Nicaragua, El Salvador, Honduras, Suriname, Bahamas, Belize and
Jamaica and the governor of Puerto Rico.
   Leaders of Cuba, Chile, Haiti and Panama were not invited.
   Panamanian Foreign Minister Leonardo Kam issued a protest last
week saying ``the invitations were selective ... almost
discriminatory, which does not contribute to the ideals of
integration of Latin America and the Caribbean.''
</TEXT>
