<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 2105EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CrimeTreaties     10-24 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crime Treaties,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Crime-Fighting Treaties With Six Nations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Tuesday approved treaties with
six other nations providing for mutual investigative assistance in
criminal cases.
   ``These new treaties are really the central tools in the fight
against drug trafficking and other serious transnational crimes,''
Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass., told the Senate before it ratified the
treaties, 99-0.
   He said the conviction in New York's ``pizza connection'' case
of 17 members of a drug ring stretching from Italy and the United
States was made possible by already existing ``mutual legal
assistance treaties.''
   The latest batch of treaties is the product of four years of
talks between the United States and the Cayman Islands, the
Bahamas, Belgium, Canada, Thailand and Mexico.
   Provisions call for cooperation in taking testimony or
statements of witnesses, producing documents, records and evidence,
executing searches and seizures, serving documents, assistance with
forfeiture of assets.
   Under the treaties, the attorney general could refuse to provide
such assistance and an ``understanding'' attached by the Senate
provided that no information about U.S. citizens would be furnished
to a foreign government if if would be seen by an official of that
country involved in drug trafficking.
</TEXT>
