<FIRST>r w AM-Abortion 1stLd-Writethru   10-24 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0709,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>House to Vote Wednesday on Abortion Veto</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 12-13: ``But another,'' with anti-abortion N.J.
member swtiching to oppose Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of legislation that would ease
restrictions on federally financed abortions for poor women
scheduled a House vote on Wednesday in an attempt to override
President Bush's veto, hoping a changing political climate could
give them a second surprise victory.
   Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., who sponsored the successful
amendment, said, ``It's going to be very tough, but we're working
to win.''
   But opponents of the change, which would relax the prohibition
on Medicaid abortions for victims of rape and incest, said they
were confident they had the votes to upphold Bush's veto.
   A two-thirds vote of House members present is needed to override
the veto. If all 434 current members were present, 290 votes would
be needed to override the veto.
   The liberalized abortion language passed on a 216-206 vote two
weeks ago, and supporters acknowledged they had a long way to go to
override the president.
   ``We don't know how many votes we'll get tomorrow; we don't know
whether we'll get 217 or 270,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.,
a supporter of expanded abortion availability. ``But ... we know
the pendulum is swinging in our direction.''
   The measure is part of a $156.7 billion appropriations bill for
education, labor and health programs.
   Bush said he was seeking ``room for flexibility'' on the issue
immediately after the House vote, but under pressure from
anti-abortion supporters he hardened his stand and vetoed the bill
on Saturday.
   ``The times are not changing,'' said Rep. Robert Dornan,
R-Calif., a leading abortion opponent. ``We will sustain his veto
tomorrow on the floor.''
   House Speaker Tom Foley, D-Wash., called Bush's veto
``mistaken'' and said the Democratic House leadership was seeking
votes to override the veto. But he said the vote ``is not a party
issue in the sense that we don't recognize that other members of
the party have a different position.''
   The newest House Democrat is Rep. Gene Taylor of Mississippi,
sworn in Tuesday after being elected in a special election last
week. Standing with Foley at a swearing-in ceremony, Taylor told
reporters he opposes ``any federal funding for abortion'' and would
vote to sustain Bush's veto.
   But another freshman Democrat reversed a lifelong anti-abortion
stance to announce he would vote to override the president.
   In what he described as ``the most difficult and agonizing
decision'' of his political career, Rep. Frank Pallone Jr. of New
Jersey said he remains opposed to abortion. but has come to believe
``sound public policy and the needs of American women are best
served if access to legal and medically safe abortion is
maintained.''
   Supporters of the liberalized abortion language said they were
urging colleagues to change their minds on the issue and were
urging constituents to contact their representative.
   A conservative Repubican, Rep. Arthur Ravenel Jr., R-S.C., said
he supported the broader abortion language and believed some
Republicans would shift to override the veto.
   ``I'm finding some movement in my Republican colleagues,''
Ravenel said. ``I think it's possible we just may override the
president's veto.''
   The abortion provision would reverse a law in effect since 1981
that bans all federally financed abortions for poor women under the
Medicaid program, except in cases where the life of the mother is
endangered by her pregnancy.
   Although the Senate had endorsed more relaxed abortion curbs,
the House had insisted on that language until its vote two weeks
ago to accept the more liberal Senate-passed version. That vote
came at a time when abortion-rights supporters said they were
enjoying new political success since a Supreme Court ruling last
summer gave the states more room to regulate abortions and brought
new attention to the issue.
   The National Right to Life Committee, the leading anti-abortion
organization, distributed copies of a letter sent to Bush in June
pleding to uphold any veto of more liberalized federal abortion
laws. It said 152 House members signed that letter.
   That number, if all voted, would be more than enough to sustain
a veto. On the group's list, however, were some members such as
Ravenel who have since voted the other way or who did not vote two
weeks ago.
</TEXT>
