<FIRST>r i AM-NewZealand-Nuclear     10-24 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Zealand-Nuclear,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>France Explodes Nuclear Device in South Pacific</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government reported that
France exploded a 25-kiloton nuclear device Wednesday at its test
site on Mururoa Atoll. New Zealand condemned the action as an
affront to residents of the South Pacific.
   Government scientists said the blast was detected by New
Zealand's seismological station in Rarotonga, Cook Islands, at 5:30
a.m. local time.
   ``The countries of the South Pacific have made it abundantly
clear on innumerable occasions that they have had enough of nuclear
testing in the region,'' said Disarmament and Arms Control Minister
Fran Wilde.
   ``The continued testing of these devices in the Pacific is an
affront to all of us who live here,'' she said.
   Warwick Smith, head of the Seismological Observatory at the
Department of Scientific and Industrial Research, said it was 108th
test at Mururoa since France abandoned atmospheric testing there in
1975.
   It followed tests this year on May 11, May 20, June 3 and June
10 when the largest device, estimated to amount to 70 kilotons or
the equivalent of 70,000 tons of TNT, was exploded.
   Smith said Wednesday's blast probably meant that France was
beginning a new round of four tests for the remainder of this year.
   ``There was a series of four in May and June this year, and the
pattern over the past five years has been two series of four each
year,'' he said.
   Earlier this year the French government said it would reduce the
number of annual tests from eight to six.
</TEXT>
