<FIRST>u a AM-MobWitness 1stLd-Writethru a0687 10-24 0849</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mob Witness, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0687,0872</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probe Murderer's Kid Glove Treatment as Protected Witness</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-10, `Gilbert responded ...,' with 7 grafs to UPDATE
with broadcast of videotape, Mrs. Gilbert's comment that she gave husband
gun; picks up 11th graf, `Police Chief ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor announced an internal
investigation Tuesday into how the Police Department let a
confessed murderer and mob informant buy drugs, carry guns and
collect welfare while in its custody as a protected witness.
   It will be at least the third investigation into the custody and
death of admitted three-time murderer Peter Gilbert, who died of a
heart attack in June 1988 while on his way to an unsupervised
skydiving trip in Connecticut.
   Packages containing 9 grams of cocaine were found in Gilbert's
parachute bag. Later investigations showed that while in police
custody, Gilbert was paid at least $98,000, took trips, charged
meals and liquor to the state and bought bullets and jewelry at
taxpayers' expense.
   Mayor Joseph R. Paolino Jr., who maintains he didn't know
Gilbert was in department custody, said his action was prompted by
``outrageous revelations'' of recent weeks, including reports that
a police officer was videotaped joking with Gilbert about the free
ride they were getting.
   Paolino appointed Family Court Judge Susan McGuirl to conduct
the review.
   U.S. Attorney Lincoln C. Almond, who has turned down repeated
requests for grand jury inquiry, saying the matter lacks federal
jurisdiction, recused his office from further involvement last week
after learning a woman who is now a secretary in his office had
traveled to Florida with a police officer who was supervising
Gilbert on one of his seven trips there.
   The Providence Journal-Bulletin reported Saturday that Gilbert's
wife had a videotape of a police officer joking with her husband
about the free ride they were getting.
   Gilbert's wife, Debra, told the newspaper the tape shows
Detective Steven Cross with his arm around her husband's shoulders
saying, ``The criminal justice system has been good to us, Peter,
huh?''
   Gilbert responded by hoisting a soda in a toast and thanking
former Attorney General Arlene Violet.
   WPRI-TV on Tuesday night broadcast videotapes of Gilbert and
police officers cavorting at a Florida motel swimming pool. The
station said the officers were supposed to have been guarding him.
   The tape showed the encounter with Cross. Gilbert also
videotaped a police officer sleeping in a poolside lounge chair
while he was supposed to be guarding the witness, the station said.
   ``Hard time, tough duty,'' Gilbert said on the tape as he
laughed, WPRI-TV said. The station said Cross claimed he was ``play
acting'' to make Gilbert feel at ease.
   Mrs. Gilbert told the station she gave her husband a gun while
he was in police custody and that she had one as well. As a
convicted felon, Gilbert could not legally carry a firearm.
   Cross was recently transferred from the detective division to
the auto squad, which investigates stolen cars, said Police Officer
Bob Lauro.
   Police Chief Walter Clark has previously declined comment on the
transfer or the tape and didn't return calls Tuesday. Violet was
not at her law office Tuesday and did not return phone calls.
   The U.S. attorney's office recommended an investigation last
week.
   Paolino denied any political motivation in requesting the city
review.
   Paolino, a Democrat, is expected next year to challenge
Repubican Gov. Edward D. DiPrete, who announced a state police
investigation of the Gilbert case last week.
   Paolino said McGuirl's review would be different from the state
police investigation because it would look into ``appropriate
disciplinary actions and administrative changes,'' while the state
police investigation is looking into possible criminal actions.
   ``I'm just looking internally as to what happened in the past
and, more fundamentally, at the department as a whole,'' said
McGuirl, who will not have subpoena power.
   An eight-month investigation by Attorney General James E. O'Neil
and Providence police said police failed to properly supervise
Gilbert but recommended no disciplinary action.
   Former police chief Col. Anthony J. Mancuso, in charge when
Gilbert's protective custody was arranged, resigned as head of the
attorney general's drug force Monday, saying he did not want to be
``a political pawn.''
   Paolino said he would await McGuirl's report before taking any
disciplinary action.
   ``Let the chips fall where they may,'' he said.
   Police Chief Walter Clark, and Cmdr. Richard Tamburini, who was
in charge of Gilbert's supervision, did not immediately return
phone calls Tuesday.
   Two of the officers in the security detail have committed
suicide.
   Gilbert, 43, was a key witness in two trials and was expected to
testify against alleged organized crime figures. In the 30 months
he was in police custody, Gilbert was kept at a police station
apartment, then transferred in January 1988 to a safe house, while
serving a 10-year sentence for murder.
   Paolino, who took office in April 1984, said that ``if the name
Peter Gilbert was ever mentioned in my presence it was made with a
host of other issues and the name would have been meaningless to
me.''
</TEXT>
