<FIRST>r i AM-Malaysia-Commonwealth     10-24 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malaysia-Commonwealth,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ammunition Found at Commonwealth Summit Site; Threat Reported</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Commonwealth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police reported Wednesday that two
rifle bullets were found in the Putra World Trade Center where the
49-nation Commonwealth held its annual summit.
   The bullets for a U.S.-made M-16 rifle were found by a constable
Oct. 12, days before the summit opened its first session on Oct.
18, according to Police Inspector General Haniff Omar. The summit
ended Tuesday.
   Haniff also said that on Oct. 11 a telephone call, purportedly
from the Irish Republican Army, was received at national police
headuarters and the caller threatened to kill British leaders
attending the summit.
   Haniff, Malaysia's highest ranking police officer, said
information about the ammunition and telephone call were withheld
to facilitate investigations.
   He said precautionary measures were taken but police found no
explosives or additional ammunition and no arrests have been made.
   Queen Elizabeth II arrived on the royal yacht Brittania for a
state visit to Malaysia Oct. 14-18 and British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher attended the summit, which ended without incident
Tuesday.
   Haniff said a note written in Malay was found with the two
bullets that read ``Chogm merbahaya, Hisbollah Malaysia,'' which
means ``Danger, Hisbollah Malaysia.''
   It was not known if the name Hisbollah was meant to be
Hezbollah, a pro-Iranian, Shiite Moslem organization in Lebanon
that is believed to be an umbrella group for extremist groups
holding 18 foreign hostages, including eight Americans, in Lebanon.
   Police said they did not know of any Hisbollah or Hezbollah
group in Malaysia.
   The IRA, outlawed in both Britain and Ireland, is a
predominantly Roman Catholic organization that is waging a violent
guerrilla campaign to unite Northern Ireland with the Catholic
Republic of Ireland. Protestants outnumber Catholics 3-2 in
Northern Ireland, a British province.
