<FIRST>r i AM-China-Loans     10-24 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Loans,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Bank Says It is Preparing Loans to China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Asian Development Bank was
quoted Tuesday as saying the fund is preparing new loans for China,
which lost its access to low-interest Western cash after its
crackdown on pro-democracy protesters.
   The official Xinhua News Agency quoted Bank President Masao
Fujioka as telling Premier Li Peng that the bank and China should
cooperate.
   ``The Asian Development Bank is making active preparations for
some loan projects with China, and these will soon be handed over
to the ... board of directors for discussion,'' Xinhua paraphrased
Fujioka as saying. No details of the loans were given.
   China has lost other sources of low-interest loans since June,
when the Chinese army cracked down on pro-democracy demonstrators.
Several Western governments froze new development loans to China in
protest, and the United States and other countries pressured the
World Bank to freeze its loans.
   Although World Bank President Barber Conable has said he expects
to see the bank resume new loans soon, bank members delayed voting
on the matter at a September meeting.
   Many private foreign bankers are hesitating to make new loans
because of China's economic problems and its decision to slow
industrial growth.
   However, there have several signs that the financial freeze is
ending.
   Japan has said it will begin gradually resuming aid projects
that it froze in June. In addition, West Germany recently decided
to go ahead with a $239 million low-interest loan to China that
will help build a subway in Shanghai.
   Fujioka and more than 30 foreign bankers were in Beijing to
attend a conference on policies for poor countries.
</TEXT>
