<FIRST>r a AM-PlantExplosion-Vigil     10-24 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plant Explosion-Vigil,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Families Keep Vigil at Rubble of Plastics Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plant Explosion, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends and relatives of workers who were
in a plastics plant when it blew up waited and clung to shreds of
hope Tuesday as the search for victims continued.
   ``My best friend is in there, I think,'' said Albert Gonzalez,
27. ``He hasn't called his mother and sister, and he didn't come
home last night.''
   The explosions Monday at Phillips Petroleum Co.'s No. 5 plant
left at least two people dead, 22 workers missing and presumed dead
and 124 people injured.
   On Tuesday, people gathered in small groups at Phillips
Employees Credit Union, which sits across Texas Highway 225 from
the blackened rubble of the plant. They talked quietly, trying to
learn who was still among the missing.
   Mary De La Vergne, 38, found the name of her husband, Cipriana
Rodriguez, 43, who had been working in the building that exploded.
   ``I had just taken him lunch,'' said Ms. De La Vergne. ``I heard
the explosion when I was going back home.''
   She recalled that a much smaller explosion several months ago
was followed by a call from Rodriguez to tell her he was OK.
   ``He called me right away then, so when I didn't hear from him
this time, I knew something was wrong,'' Ms. De La Vergne said.
   At 10:30 p.m. Monday, her husband's supervisor and another
Phillips official came to her house to tell her that her husband
was missing.
   ``I can only keep on hoping,'' she said Tuesday, collapsing in
tears onto the steering wheel of her pickup.
   Gonzalez, who works in the plant's distribution department,
leaned against a highway overpass buttress, his sunglasses masking
reddened eyes. He has been calling his friend's relatives
regularly, but hope has dwindled.
   ``They're sitting by the phone and it won't even go for a full
ring before they pick it up. They say, `Mark?' and I say, `No, it's
just me.'''
   Ray Rodriguez, 50, of La Porte, came so he could retrieve his
truck, which is still parked inside the plant. His ears were still
ringing from the blast, which knocked him to the ground from about
100 yards away.
   Rodriguez shook his head as he thought about how close he had
come to death.
   ``We ran for our lives,'' he said. ``Some people wanted to stop
and I just told them to keep on going, because you can't tell
what's going to happen next. And there were more explosions.''
</TEXT>
