<DOCNO> AP891024-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 2336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Suriname-Hijacking     10-24 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Suriname-Hijacking,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amerindians Hijack Ferry in Campaign Against Peace Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amerindian insurgents angry about a
government peace accord with rival Bush Negro rebels hijacked a
ferryboat Tuesday, witnesses said.
   No hostages were taken, but the hijacking on the Saramacca River
temporarily cut off this capital from the rice-producing Nickerie
district. Rice is a leading earner of hard currency in this country
on the eastern shoulder of South America.
   Witnesses said the hijackers were Tucayana Indians, who have
been agitating against the government since it signed a July peace
agreement with rebels of the Jungle Commando group, who are mostly
Bush Negroes.
   On Aug. 31, the Tucayana hijacked a ferry at the same place. The
boat seized Tuesday replaced the one captured in August.
   Like the army, the Tucayana oppose the peace accord because it
calls for the 200 to 400 Jungle Commando fighters to become a
special police unit in the interior, where most of the Amerindians
live.
   The Amerindians, allied to the army during the three-year
guerrilla war, fear retribution if they fall under the control of
the Bush Negroes.
   The 65,000 Bush Negroes, who are descendants of escaped African
slaves, and 10,000 Amerindians are traditional rivals. They compete
for land for farming, hunting and fishing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
