<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-BoatPeople     10-24 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Boat People,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>658 Chinese Found Among Vietnamese Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration authorities said Tuesday they found 658
more Chinese among Vietnamese boat people, bringing the number of
Chinese trying to enter Japan by posing as Vietnamese refugees this
year to 1,642.
   Japan plans to send the Chinese back home and is negotiating
with the Chinese government, a Justice Ministry official said.
   They were among 3,372 boat people supposedly from Vietnam who
arrived in Japan this year, compared with 219 for all of 1988, said
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The 658 Chinese, who have been in the International Refugee
Assistance Center since arrival, were sent to immigration
facilities Tuesday pending deportation to China, the official said.
   Immigration officials escorted some of the male Chinese in
handcuffs to prevent possible disorder, Kyodo News Service reported.
   In September, violence flared between Chinese and Vietnamese
refugees at the center when 19 Vietnamese living in Japan broke in
and reportedly beat Chinese with pieces of wood.
   On Sept. 13, Japan began a policy of screening boat people and
accepting only those deemed to be fleeing political persecution and
refusing those who come seeking economic betterment.
</TEXT>
