<HEAD>Rampage Suspect Pleads Innocent, Trial Set for January</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: Marteen in 3rd graf is cq.</UNK>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winery worker Ramon Salcido pleaded
innocent Tuesday to charges he killed his wife, two of his
daughters and four other people in a rampage last spring.
   Salcido appeared before Sonoma County Superior Judge J. Brian
Jamar, who accepted the plea and tentatively scheduled Salcido's
trial for Jan. 30.
   However, Public Defender Marteen Miller said he needed more time
to prepare and would probably request a delay in the start of the
trial.
   Miller said he was preparing motions to move the trial to
another county because of news coverage and to challenge Salcido's
reported confession in Mexico. Salcido, a native of Mexico, was
arrested there several days after the April 14 rampage in the wine
country north of San Francisco.
   If convicted, Salcido could be sentenced to death. Miller said
he would argue that the extradition treaty between the United
States and Mexico forbids such a sentence.
   Salcido is charged in the slayings of his wife, Angela; two of
their three daughters; his wife's mother; two of his wife's
sisters; and a co-worker at Grand Cru Vineyards.
   The victims were shot, stabbed and beaten. A third daughter,
3-year-old Carmina, had her throat slashed like the other two, but
survived. She was found alive in the garbage dump where the
youngsters' bodies had been dumped.
