<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-BayBridge 2ndLd-Writethru   10-24 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Bay Bridge, 2nd Ld-Writethru,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with new material on removal of lower span and recasts
throughout. Changes Richter scale reading to reflect official change in
last graf. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers removed an earthquake-damaged
section of the lower deck of the San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge
on Tuesday, leaving a hole in the structure nearly as glaring as
the hole in the region's transportation system.
   Fifty-foot sections, one atop the other, have now been yanked
out of both levels of the double-decked 53-year-old bridge.
   Officials for the California Department of Transportation will
build new sections, each five lanes wide, and lift them into place.
They estimate the work will take at least one month.
   Steve Saville, a spokesman for the department, said he believed
it was the first time such large pieces had been removed since the
major highway link between the cities opened in 1936.
   ``It's a big hole,'' he said.
   For Bay area residents who escaped injury or property damage,
the closure of the bridge may be the biggest inconvenience of the
earthquake, Saville said. The bridge is normally used by 260,000
cars each day. The state is losing an estimated $130,000 a day in
tolls.
   The 200-ton lower section had been declared a total loss shortly
after the Oct. 17 earthquake. It was chopped into four pieces and
lowered more than 200 feet by crane to a barge floating next to a
bridge tower in San Francisco Bay.
   Transportation Department officials had hoped to repair the
upper section, and undertook a delicate two-day effort to lower
that section last weekend. The upper section was cut into just two
pieces and lowered, but a close inspection showed the steel
framework could not be salvaged, Saville said.
   The repairs will cost $1 million, the agency has said.
   Department planners had accounted for the possibly the upper
section would be unusable, and had already drafted a design for new
construction so the repair time estimate did not have to be
extended, Saville said.
   The 8.5-mile-long bridge had become the symbol of the World
Series between Oakland and San Francisco.
   Nationally broadcast pictures of the broken bridge, with the
upper deck dangling, provided the first graphic illustration of the
magnitude of the 7.1 Richter scale quake. One woman died when she
drove her car into the gap.
</TEXT>
