<FIRST>u a AM-AbortionBill 2ndLd-Writethru a0697 10-24 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Bill, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0697,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania House Approves Abortion Controls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads nine grafs to UPDATE with passage of abortion control
bill. Picks up 9th graf, `Pennsylvania legislators...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pennsylvania House of Representatives
on Tuesday passed a tough abortion control bill intended to make
the state the first to take advantage of a U.S. Supreme Court
ruling allowing more restrictions.
   After nearly nine hours of debate, the House voted 143-58 for
the new controls and sent the bill to the Senate, which recessed
earlier Tuesday and will not return until Nov. 13. Most attempts to
weaken the bill were easily defeated during the long session.
   Gov. Robert P. Casey has said he backs abortion restrictions
proposed by Republican state Rep. Stephen Freind, the state's
leading anti-abortion lawmaker, who opened debate on the House
floor by calling abortion an ``inherently violent'' act.
   He asked his fellow lawmakers: ``Abortion is the most wrenching
social issue of our time, but since when do we solve our social
problems with violence?''
   Freind called the bill ``a moderate, common sense approach to
this issue.'' Earlier Tuesday, also by a 143-58 vote, the House
approved adding the abortion control language into a pending bill
toughening penalties for incest. A pro-choice leader, Democratic
state Rep. Karen Ritter, argued during debate that the government
has no right to intrude on a woman's decision whether to have an
abortion.
   She said restrictions proposed by Freind trivialize ``one of the
most important decisions a woman can make. ... Why can't we trust a
woman to make the decision when to have a child.''
   Pennsylvania legislators have repeatedly voted for abortion
controls since the U.S. Supreme Court's 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision
made most abortions legal. Efforts to impose new restrictions
started anew after July, when the Supreme Court cleared the way in
a Missouri case for states to impose new restrictions on abortion.
   The anti-abortion proposals under consideration in Pennsylvania
include a ban on abortions after the 24th week of pregnancy, except
in cases where the mother faces irreversible harm, and a
prohibition on abortions for sex selection. Others include a
requirement that women inform their husbands if they plan to get an
abortion, and a 24-hour waiting period.
   ``We've lost amendments in the past and we may lose some
amendments today, but I think we'll pass the bill,'' Freind said.
   The American Civil Liberties Union of Pennsylvania called
Freind's measure ``the most dangerous abortion bill in any state
Legislature in the nation.''
   Ms. Ritter said there was an outside chance of swinging enough
votes to defeat it.
   ``We're not giving up hope on it yet,'' she said.
   The Florida Legislature, called into special session by Gov. Bob
Martinez, recently rejected all of his proposed abortion
restrictions. Last week, a committee of the Illinois House blocked
a bill to restrict abortions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
