<DOCNO> AP891024-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0736EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Savalas Adv25   10-24 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Savalas, Adv 25,0815</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Wed Pms, Oct. 25 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Kojak' Star Plays Has-Been TV Detective in Cable Comedy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a case of cable spoofing art, the USA Network
tonight is airing ``The Hollywood Detective,'' a sly comedy about a
once-famous TV detective fallen on hard times. It stars Telly
Savalas.
   Savalas, of course, didn't fall on hard times when CBS axed his
``Kojak'' series in 1978. He's even returning to television Nov. 4
as the tough New York cop in a new ``Kojak,'' part of ABC's
``Saturday Mystery'' series.
   But USA's movie does make you think, particularly at one point
when a reporter asks Savalas' faded TV detective, middle-aged actor
Harry Bell, the name and network of his old TV series.
   The faded star beams. ``Oh, yes,'' he casually says. `` `John
Crowne, Private Investigator,' NBC. You know, there is talk
recently about renewing the series, and I...'' Two real police
detectives hustle him away.
   A funny moment. Savalas is wonderful in it and throughout the
film. He shows a previously unseen comic side, playing a ham who
made millions in eight years as a TV detective but hasn't worked in
12 years.
   Although our hero visibly inflates when someone recognizes him,
he now lives alone, unloved and unemployed in his personal Tap
City, an ancient Hollywood bungalow surrounded by dry weeds.
   ``Detective'' vaguely echoes a nifty Art Carney-Lily Tomlin
movie of 1977, ``The Late Show,'' complete with a flakey Hollywood
lady, sweetly portrayed here by Helen Udy. But it's gently funny in
its own way.
   The two-hour film concerns, give or take, a missing-persons case
that our hero reluctantly accepts, aware that he's no detective.
   But he also is aware he needs money. Bills are piling up, his
stove was repossessed, and he hasn't even a hot plate on which to
warm his dinner, a can of tamales. Still, he remains a ham, even
with cold tamales.
   Up for a small part as an Irish priest in a TV movie at
Universal Studios, he recalls in his gumshoe-movie narration that
``the studio had been good to me once, and I figured I owed them
one.''Nope, the network says.
   His sleazy agent (nicely played by George Coe), a fan of porn
movies, says he could land him the lead in a new ``personal
picture'' called ``Author of Lust.'' Throttling Coe, the enraged
actor shouts the worst insult he can muster: ``You agent, you!''
   But when all seems lost, there is a knock on his door. The
knocker (Udy) is a young woman, Lois Wednesday. Like some Hollywood
inmates, she is not what network executives would call
reality-based.
   This is not just because her hair has tints of purple and blue,
the number of her apartment is ``1412},'' and her phone is shaped
like a tennis shoe. No, it is because she thinks Harry Bell, the
actor, really can solve a case.
   The case is her missing boyfriend. They met, had a fling, ``and
then he kinda sorta moved in,'' she explains in her wistful, wispy
voice. But he has disappeared, leaving behind $10,000 in cash.
   Harry Bell, actor, explains that he is no detective. However,
with the chance of earning $100 a day, plus expenses, he thinks
that ``maybe, just maybe, being a real detective wasn't much
different than being one on TV.''
   He soon learns that there is a small difference as he goes
through plot twists involving medflies, blackmail, the Hollenbeck
Fruit Company, a car chase, his arrest as a murder suspect, and a
once-great TV story consultant he summons when the case gets too
baffling.
   There also are two stiffs.
   While the proceedings sag slightly near the gunfire-filled
finale, this ``Detective,'' well-written by Christopher Crowe and
deftly directed by Kevin Connor, is a fine and funny film. You'll
like it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere on television...
   ANOTHER REASON TO CONTINUE LIVING: NBC's cable operation, CNBC,
has hired Morton Downey Jr. You may recall him as the host of a
much-publized, now-defunct syndicated talk show. It featured a lot
of shouting and he would bellow ``Zip it!'' to those with whom he
disagreed.
   Starting Dec. 4, he will host ``Showdown,'' a half-hour
weeknight series in which he will debate great issues with another
regular, New York Daily News columnist Richard G. Carter. Guest
experts also will check in and, as was the case in his old series,
there will be a studio audience.
   However, says CNBC spokesman Jim Boyle, Downey has ``pledged to
be much different than what he was in his old show'' and that his
new show will be ``toned down.'' And that the audience will not get
to shout.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
