<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1424EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Washington Adv30   10-24 0833</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Washington, Adv 30,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Oct. 30, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Riffs and Dunks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Philadelphia 76ers play their first
home game this season, Grover Washington Jr. will be there,
performing the national anthem.
   It's a tradition, and a logical one _ not just because the
saxophonist lives in the suburb of Germantown or that former 76ers
star Julius Erving is a close friend.
   Musically, Washington says, it makes sense as well. That's
right, jazz and basketball. Riffs and dunks. Horn charts and game
plans. He can hear it now, ``Starting at guard, please welcome,
Grover Washington Jr.''
   ``We live really parallel lives,'' said Washington, who even
wrote a song about Erving called ``Let It Flow.''
   ``We are trying to create, whether it's on the court or on the
bandstand or the stage, the concept of team play _ whether you are
on a basketball team or whether you are in a band.
   ``There are role players on a basketball team and role players
in a band. Everybody shifts around, everybody gets to handle the
ball, so to speak. My role is like the point guard. I try to give
the ball to the people who can really do things with it. I'm also
like a player-coach.''
   Washington has provided valuable assists to collaborators Ralph
McDonald, Ronnie Foster, Donald Robinson and others. Singer Bill
Withers got a boost in 1980 when the saxophonist phoned and urged
him to add vocals to the track of ``Just the Two of Us,'' a No. 2
hit off the platinum ``Winelight'' album, winner of the ``Best Jazz
Fusion Performance'' Grammy.
   On ``Time Out of My Mind,'' his 21st album, he offers
encouragement to the 1990 Trans-Antarctic Expedition Explorers with
``Protect the Dream.'' Sports crept in again as Washington
explained why he was supporting those inspecting environmental
conditions around the Antarctic.
   ``When I think of those guys on foot and on skis, going across
Antartica, I realize all that is really for all of us,'' he said.
``They come back with information and the ball will be in our
court. There are a lot of concerned people around that will take
the advice and the facts they will be finding out.''
   Washington sees his own work as information. Short stories
without words. Impressions, often first impressions, turned into
sound. The titles are a clue: ``Gramercy Park,'' a melodic James
McBride-Damon DueWhite composition about the historic section of
Manhattan, or the romantic ``Unspoken Love,'' written by Gerald
Veasley.
   The title track, a hit for Steely Dan, is a gesture of thanks to
the jazz-rock group.
   ``Every time I get in my car and ride to New York, its either
`Gaucho,' or `Nightfly,''' Washington said of the Steely Dan record
and group member Donald Fagen's solo album.
   ``Plus with that group, they've been some of the guys on the
cutting edge of entertaining. ... They talk about religion, the
Third World. They talk about glamour, how living hard will take its
toll.''
   Washington likes a pace as relaxed as his own sweet saxophone.
That means time with his wife, Christine, and children, Shana Bly
and Grover III. Jam sessions are balanced by parents' night at
school. It makes for a richer life, and better records, he says.
   ``Through the things I do every day, I can relate in musical
terms to my fans, let them know we have more similarities than
differences. I am more than a one-dimensional person and the
audience is more than a one-dimensional audience.''
   He was born in 1943 in Buffalo, N.Y., and was playing sax by age
10. Washington's career took off in 1970 when he was featured on
Johnny ``Hammond'' Smith's ``Breakout'' and arranged the cover of
Carole King's ``It's too Late.'' His first solo record, the
acclaimed ``Inner City Blues,'' came by accident when he wound up
doing a solo intended for tenor saxophonist Hank Crawford who
couldn't make the studio date at the last minute.
   The title track is a cover of Marvin Gaye's haunting meditation
on urban life. Appropriate, since Gaye, and another personal
favorite of Washington's, Stevie Wonder, have often incorporated
jazz into their own work.
   Jazz greats Charlie Parker, Sonny Rollins, Cannonball Adderley
and John Coltrane are important influences. Washington also
incorporates classical music and sounds from South America, Europe,
Africa and Japan.
   But he thinks locally as well as globally. He doesn't need to
travel 5,000 miles for inspiration: Just walking down the street is
enough.
   ``There's a record player playing in here all the time,'' he
said, pointing to his head. ``I'm listening to everything. The
screech of brakes. Three or four people walking and you can hear
their heels clicking. Railroad tracks.
   ``Any kind of movement. Birds wings. There's a lot of things to
be learned just by picking up on the subtle things that really
present the whole musical picture.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Oct. 30</NOTE>
