<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     10-24 0848</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0885</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp. said it will continue exploring ways to
get the best deal for its shareholders and indicated it may not
accept anything less than the $6.75 billion offered by a
labor-management group that failed to get financing for a buyout.
   In a statement, the parent of United Airlines said Monday it
considered the failed bid's price of $300 a share to be ``an
attractive offer'' and ``in the best interests of shareholders.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. announced it would lay off
2,500 employees, or nearly 20 percent of its work force, as part of
a restructuring designed to put the company back on its feet
following a 10-month anti-takeover battle.
   The minicomputer maker also will divide its operations into four
departments, or ``profit centers,'' designed to focus on particular
customer services and to target resources to ``businesses that
generate an acceptable return on investment,'' spokesman Joe
Gavaghan said Monday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Six major oil companies reported mixed quarterly results, mostly
because of lower gasoline prices that hurt their refining and
marketing businesses.
   Earnings were down at Exxon Corp., Phillips Petroleum Co. and
Atlantic Richfield Co., while Ashland Oil Inc. reported a net loss.
Occidental Petroleum Corp. said earnings rose slightly. Amerada
Hess Corp., bucking the trend, said earnings more than doubled. The
reports were released Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The struggling investment firm Integrated
Resources Inc. said it would transfer its main broker-dealer
subsidiary to two executives and change the division's name in an
attempt to stanch a sales force exodus.
   Integrated, which has $1.75 billion in debt, said Monday that
Integrated Resources Equity Corp. would be renamed Royal Alliance
Associates Inc. and its stock transferred to Integrated executives
Gerard M. Lavin and Gary W. Krat.
   The change is directed at retaining credibility for Integrated's
3,900 registered broker-dealers who sell products ranging from
mutual funds to investment partnerships to stocks and bonds, Krat
said in an interview.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman and chief executive of The Ogilvy
Group, an advertising and marketing company recently acquired by
Britain's WPP Group PLC, has resigned to take a senior post with
American Express Co.
   Kenneth Roman, 59, said Monday he was ending a 26-year career at
Ogilvy because the job offered by American Express was ``simply too
exciting to turn down'' and because the post-buyout transition at
Ogilvy had been accomplished.
   Roman will become executive vice president corporate affairs and
communications at American Express, one of Ogilvy's clients.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resort-entertainment company Qintex
Australia Ltd., hurt by financial problems including the collapse
of its $1.5 billion deal to buy MGM-UA Communications Co.,
announced a broad restructuring aimed at generating hundreds of
millions of dollars in savings and asset sales.
   Qintex, an operator of resorts and television stations, plans to
sell its remaining 51 percent stake in Mirage resorts in Australia
and Hawaii, said Chairman Christopher Skase.
   The announcement Monday came after the Australian Stock Exchange
suspended trading in Qintex because the company hadn't answered an
exchange question about its loans, investments and deposits to
Qintex Entertainment Inc., a U.S. affiliate that filed for
protection from creditors late Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NAPLES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee A. Iacocca
criticized Japan for maintaining what he called a ``rigged market''
that owed much of its business success to restrictive national
trade policies.
   Iacocca, speaking Monday to more than 600 members of the
Magazine Publishers Association and the American Society of
Magazine Editors, specifically complained about critical remarks by
Akio Morita, chairman of Sony Corp., in the recently published
book, ``The Japan That Can Say No.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dealers are continuing to sell all-terrain
vehicles for use by children despite an agreement between the
government and manufacturers to curtail such sales, a consumer
group says.
   The U.S. Public Interest Research Group, a private organization
affiliated with consumer advocate Ralph Nader, said Monday that 54
percent of dealers surveyed told volunteers who called on the
telephone that an adult-sized vehicle would be appropriate for use
by children under age 16.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent broadcasters launched a formal
assault on a Rochester, N.Y., cable television system that is
operating a broadcast-style TV station on one of its 39 channels.
   The Association of Independent Television Stations, in a 47-page
petition to the Federal Communications Commission, said Monday the
establishment of WGRC-TV, channel 5, on the Greater Rochester
Cablevision system was a threat to fair competition and the
diversity of programming for viewers.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined broadly Monday in sluggish trading, as
the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 26.23 to 2,662.91.
   Bond prices rose in tandem with a decline in the stock market.
   The dollar drifted lower in lackluster trading.
   Copper futures prices fell to their lowest levels in more than
two months; heating oil plunged the 2-cents-a-gallon daily limit as
energy futures sagged; stock-index futures dropped along with stock
prices; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and grains and
soybeans were mixed.
</TEXT>
