<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 0102EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryBills     10-24 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rates on Short-Term Treasuries Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose at auction to their highest level in two weeks.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.8 billion in three-month bills
Monday at an average discount rate of 7.52 percent, up from 7.37
percent last week. Another $7.8 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.50 percent, up from 7.42 percent
last week.
   The rates were the highest since Oct. 10 when three-month bills
sold for 7.63 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.60 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.77 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,809.90 and 7.90 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,620.80.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for 1-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for
making changes in adjustable-rate mortgages, fell to 7.85 percent
last week, down from 8.00 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
