<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Decline In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell slightly against the Japanese yen
in slow trading today, while prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
declined moderately after a five-day gain.
   The dollar closed at 142.10 yen, down 0.30 yen from Monday's
close. It opened at 141.80 yen and ranged between 141.72 yen and
142.25 yen.
   Volume totaled $5.644 billion, compared with $4.534 billion
Monday.
   A dealer at the Bank of Tokyo said the dollar's decline
reflected a decline on the New York market, and trading was slow,
with no major market-affecting news.
   Other dealers said market participants were awaiting the release
of U.S. economic figures this week, including a report on orders
for durable goods, due later today in Washington, and estimates of
third-quarter growth in the gross national product.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
99.14 points Monday, dropped 58.97 points, or 0.17 percent, closing
at 35,526.55.
   Volume totaled 900 million shares, compared with 600 million
shares Monday.
   A dealer at Nomura Securities Co. said there was no major news
affecting trading, but investors apparently were wary after gains
in the index over the last five trading days.
