<HEAD>GM Considering Going Overseas to Produce GM-Sponsored Shows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp., in a cost-cutting move, may
look overseas to find companies to produce GM-sponsored television
shows that would air in the United States.
   The company plans to decide in four weeks whether to pursue the
plan, said Philip Guarascio, the company's executive director of
advertising.
   The move would allow GM to bargain with the three major
commercial networks for air time instead of simply buying
commercial time slots.
   GM, like other automakers, refuses to say how much it spends on
advertising. Industry estimates quoted in Monday's edition of The
Detroit News put the automaker's network television advertising
bill for last year at $443.4 million.
   Ford Motor Co. spokesman John Jelinek said the nation's No. 2
automaker has no such program in place or under consideration.
Chrysler Corp. spokesmen did not return a reporter's telephone call
seeking comment on whether it had such plans.
