<HEAD>UAL To Continue Exploring Options; No New Offer Surfaces</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede with one graf to include dropped word `of'. INSERTS
New 4th graf, UAL's opening ... a share, to UPDATE with today's market
activity. Picks up 4th graf pvs, The board's ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp.'s board of directors has decided to
keep the parent company of United Airlines independent for now as
it examines alternatives to a $6.75 billion buyout that collapsed
earlier this month.
   The $300-a-share bid from United's management, pilots and
British Airways PLC couldn't generate enough bank financing, and
its failure helped trigger a Friday the 13th plunge in the stock
market.
   Last week UAL's stock lost $111.25 a share. It closed up $10 a
share on Monday at $178.37{ on the New York Stock Exchange.
   UAL's opening was delayed today due to an order imbalance, with
indications that it could open anywhere from $143 to $153 a share.
   The board's announcement Monday was vaguely and carefully
worded, leaving UAL's precise plans unclear. It said it considered
the failed bid's price of $300 a share to be ``an attractive
offer'' and ``in the best interests of shareholders.''
   ``Consistent with the effort to maximize shareholder value, the
board will continue to explore all strategic and financial
alternatives available to the company,'' the UAL statement said.
   But it did not mention any specific alternatives, including an
informal proposal from UAL's management and pilots unit reportedly
valued at between $225 and $240 a share, or as much as $5.42
billion.
   United's pilots said they were disappointed with UAL's failure
to continue negotiating a possible takeover of the airline.
   Frederick C. Dubinsky, head of the pilots' group, said the union
``was prepared to work with the board to shape a transaction that
would provide UAL stockholders with value significantly in excess
of the current market price of UAL stock.''
   Analysts had linked the surge in UAL's stock Monday to a Wall
Street Journal report saying the labor-managment group was
considering a revised offer that would give employees a majority
stake in the company and leave some stock in public hands.
   But a separate statement from UAL Chairman Stephen Wolf on
Monday indicated an acquisition effort was over.
   Wolf said the cooperative buyout effort had helped management
and the pilots to forge a ``substantially improved working
relationship.'' He said he ``hopes that all 70,000 United employees
can now turn their full attention to operating the best airline in
the world.''
   Stephen Dexter, an analyst with Kemper Financial Services Inc.
in Chicago, said Wolf's statement indicates UAL's board wants
management to return its attention to running United Airlines.
   ``What this kind of does, it gives them a little breathing
room,'' Dexter said.
</TEXT>
