<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1035EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PrimeComputer     10-24 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime Computer,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Says It Will Lay Off 2,500</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLISON J. PUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. will lay off 2,500 employees,
nearly 20 percent of its work force, as part of a restructuring
after its billion-dollar buyout by J.H. Whitney &amp; Co., the company
said.
   The layoffs announced Monday will be spread over several months
and will mostly affect Prime's employees in the United States.
   The minicomputer company, which is based in Natick, will be
divided into four departments designed to focus on particular
customer services, said Prime spokesman Joe Gavaghan. More money
will be spent on those that do well.
   ``If there is a product for which there is not a strong market,
the spending on those products will be reduced or eliminated,''
Gavaghan said.
   The company's new strategy was part of a plan to reduce the $1
billion debt it took on after Whitney, a New York investment firm,
bought the company in August and ended Prime's 10-month battle
against hostile bidder MAI Basic Four Inc. of Tustin, Calif.
   Whitney paid $20 a share for 49.5 million Prime shares and
exchange notes with a face value of $22 per share for the remaining
21 percent of Prime's shares.
   Much of the deal, which analysts estimated was worth between
$1.06 billion and $1.16 billion, was financed by debt, said
Gavaghan.
   Gavaghan said the exact figure for Prime's debt would not be
available until a special board meeting, when the final details of
the Whitney merger were to be completed. The meeting has not yet
been scheduled, he said.
   Officials at Prime, which also announced Monday the introduction
of two new software products for computer-aided design, declined to
offer projections for Prime's revenue for the past year.
   The firm, whose revenue comes about equally from its ventures in
minicomputers, computer-aided design systems and customer service,
did not issue a third-quarter report.
   The company turned a profit of $19 million on sales of $1.6
billion in 1988. That year the firm posted a one-time loss of $58
million based on costs involved in a merger with Computervision
Corp., said Gavaghan.
   The cost of defending against MAI Basic Four and slow sales of
minicomputers led to losses of $14.4 million in the final quarter
of 1988, $5 million in the first quarter of 1989 and $19 million in
the second quarter.
   Prime said it has established a career counseling and training
center at its Natick headquarters to help those employees let go.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
