<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Bond-Debt     10-24 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bond-Debt,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Corp. Says Debt Totals 6.9 Billion Australian Dollars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond Corp. Holdings Ltd.'s debt
totals 6.9 billion Australian dollars, with rising Australian
interest rates and the Bell Group Ltd. acquisition the chief
causes, Chairman Alan Bond disclosed Tuesday.
   The disclosure followed Friday's news that Bond Corp. had
incurred the largest annual loss in Australian corporate history.
   In its fiscal year ended June 30, Bond Corp. lost 980.2 million
Australian dollars, the equivalent of about $762.4 million. Much of
the loss was due to one-time write-downs of the value of some of
Bond Corp.'s assets.
   Alan Bond, chairman and controlling shareholder of the
cash-strapped Australian media, brewing, natural resources and
property concern, provided the debt figures at a business gathering.
   He said the debt load would have been heavier if not for a
reduction of 5 billion Australian dollars over the past year from
asset sales. Bond indicated that detailed debt numbers, which would
include liabilities of units such as the Bell Group, would be
published soon in Bond Corp.'s annual report.
   Bond predicted that the debt would be lightened by an additional
3.8 billion Australian dollars this year, ending June 30, 1990, but
he didn't explain how the reduction would be achieved.
   Rising Australian interest rates and the acquisition of Bell
Group ``with its very high levels of short-term debt'' were blamed
by Bond for creating a condition ``that was no longer sustainable.''
   ``In order to restore confidence and ensure the support of our
principal lenders, we embarked on fundamental changes in the
structure and direction of the group,'' Bond said.
   That realignment resulted in continuing asset sales, as well as
write-offs exceeding 1.1 billon Australian dollars in the past
financial year. ``In essence we have made a decision to clear the
decks,'' Bond told the meeting.
   While some assets have been written down, others are undervalued
on Bond Corp.'s books, Bond maintained.
   Among the undervalued holdings are the company's Australian
brewing assets, which Bond said are actually worth 2.5 billion
Australian dollars while being on the books as being worth 950
million Australian dollars.
   An investment in Chile's telephone company is carried at $300
million, but really should be valued at $500 million, according to
Bond. Also, the company's property portfolio is undervalued by at
least 250 million Australian dollars, he said.
   Bond forecast that by next June, ``What will emerge will be a
company with a honed sense of purpose ... a stable balance sheet,
with good quality assets in brewing, telecommunications, media and
property.''
   He didn't mention energy resources on that list, possibly
signalling that all the company's coal and oil interests might be
for sale. Some oil holdings already have been sold.
   Bond Corp.'s annual loss compared with a profit of 273.5 million
Australian dollars a year earlier.
   Operating revenue in fiscal 1989 rose 69 percent to 8.48 billion
Australian dollars from 5.01 billion Australian dollars. But
after-tax interest costs jumped 85 percent to 686.7 million
Australian dollars from 371.1 million Australian dollars.
   In commenting last week on its results, Bond Corp. said the
financial performance of its U.S. brewing operations, G. Heileman
Brewing Co., was ``disappointing, and this has been reflected in
the results.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
