<FIRST>u f PM-Market-CircuitBreaker     10-24 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Market-Circuit Breaker,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Market Plunge Triggers Merc Circuit Breaker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plunge in stock prices this morning sent S&amp;P
500 stock-index futures down the 12-point limit permitted under
``circuit-breaker'' rules designed to slow a market collapse.
   Trading halted momentarily, then prices began climbing again,
said Merc spokeswoman Julie Jacobs.
   The contract for December delivery of stocks tracked by the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index fell to 335.95 on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange at about 9:30 a.m. CDT, Ms. Jacobs said. The
contract is valued at $500 a point.
   The 12-point drop tripped a circuit-breaker rule prohibiting
selling at prices below that level for 30 minutes.
   The decline occurred as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
on the New York Stock Exchange tumbled more than 80 points before
recovering some lost ground.
   The decline in part was a reaction to news that UAL Corp.'s
board of directors had decided Monday to keep the parent company of
United Airlines independent for now as it examines alternatives to
a $300-a-share buyout plan that collapsed earlier this month.
   The Merc circuit-breaker, implemented after the 1987 market
crash, also kicked in on Oct. 13, when the market sold off sharply
after financing for the UAL deal fell through.
</TEXT>
