<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1201EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Disney     10-24 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Disney,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Euro-Disney Shares Rocket in Official Gray Market Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shares in Europe's Disney theme park rocketed 18
percent higher on Tuesday when London's Stock Exchange allowed gray
market trading to begin officially because of heavy interest in the
new issue.
   The shares were quoted at the equivalent of $13.36, up $2.05
from the offer price of $11.31. They were up $2.88 at one point as
investors scrambled to take a stake in the theme park to be built
in France.
   Demand for the shares outstripped supply almost five times when
applications closed on Friday and a ballot was being held to divide
the allocation, the investment firm Warburg Securities said.
   Gray market trading, which takes place among investors before
full trading begins through the stock exchange, is the trading of
promises to buy and sell shares once full trading starts.
   The market is called gray because the activity is not illegal as
in a black market, yet it is not full trading, either.
   The sale of Euro Disneyland shares in Britain was part of a
public offering across Europe. Euro Disneyland SCA, the French
company building the park, is selling 85.9 million shares for about
$1 billion in the 12 Common Market countries to help finance the
$7.5 billion project.
   Euro Disneyland shares were scheduled to start trading
officially in London, Paris and Brussels from Nov. 6.
   A gray market in Euro Disneyland shares has existed in Paris
since the offer price was declared on Oct. 5.
   On Monday, London's Stock Exchange announced that instead of
allowing an unofficial gray market to develop in Britain it would
create its own, and gave several market making firms permission to
trade Euro Disneyland shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
