<SECOND>BC-Reebok,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shoe Company's President Steps Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOUGHTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   C. Joseph LaBonte has resigned as
president and chief operating officer of Reebok International Ltd.,
a company that designs and markets footwear and apparel.
   Paul Fireman, chairman and chief executive officer of the
company, said in a news release Monday he will take over LaBonte's
titles and corporate duties.
   LaBonte, 50, who had been with Reebok 2{ years, said he plans to
return to the presidency of The Vantage Group Inc., a venture
capital and mergers and acquisition firm in California, which he
founded in 1983.
   LaBonte was paid $1 million last year, according to Reebok
financial disclosure forms.
   Reebok had sales last year of $1.79 billion. It held a 23.5
percent share of the athletic footwear market in the United States,
compared with Nike Inc.'s 25.5 percent share, according to industry
estimates.
   In 1986, Reebok led the industry with a 31.3 percent share,
compared with Nike's 20.7 percent share.
