<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1202EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Airlines     10-24 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Airlines,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>USAir Posts Loss of $77.7 Million in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir Group Inc., the holding company for
the nation's seventh-largest airline, reported a net loss of $77.7
million for the third quarter, which it attributed to flat demand
and higher operating expenses.
   USAir said Tuesday it lost $77.7 million, or $1.86 a share, in
the three months ended Sept. 30, compared with a net profit of
$68.5 million, or $1.58 a share, in the third quarter of 1988.
   Third-quarter revenue was unchanged at $1.5 billion.
   ``Domestic airline industry traffic growth was flat during 1989
compared to 1988, and domestic industry revenue per passenger mile
for the third quarter of 1989 was only 1.4 percent above the
comparable period in 1988,'' said USAir Chairman and President
Edwin I. Colodny.
   Earnings also were affected by the airline's Kids Fly Free
program, lower fares in California and frequent flir awards,
Colodny said.
   The company, which absorbed Piedmont Aviation into its system in
early August, also reported higher labor and fuel costs as well as
one-time costs stemming from the merger.
   The effects of Hurricane Hugo, which disrupted USAir's major hub
at Charlotte, N.C., and other southeastern cities, cannot be
quantified, the company said.
   However, it said, the effects of Hugo and the recent California
earthquake, combined with recent trends ``are expected to cause
operating results for the fourth quarter and for 1989 to be
significantly lower than those of the comparable 1988 periods.''
   For the first nine months of 1989, USAir reported net income of
$38.5 million, or 76 cents a share, on revenue of $4.8 billion.
That compares with net income of $142.2 million, or $3.28 a share,
on revenue of $4.2 billion for the same period last year.
</TEXT>
