<FIRST>r f PM-Register-Ingersoll     10-24 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Register-Ingersoll,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ingersoll Publications to Buy Register for $250 million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ingersoll Publications Co. says it has
agreed to buy the New Haven (Conn.) Register from Goodson
Newspapers for $250 million and will terminate contracts to manage
the rest of Goodson's 66 newspapers.
   The sale of the Register, which Ingersoll announced Monday, was
expected to be finalized by Dec. 1.
   Ralph Ingersoll II, whose company owns more than 200 newspapers
and also managed Goodson's papers, acquired the Register on behalf
of Goodson from the Jackson family for $185 million in 1986.
   The Register has a daily circulation of 107,000 and a Sunday
circulation of 142,000.
   Thomas P. Geyer, the Register's chief executive officer, said
Monday that since the 1986 sale Ingersoll had been expected
eventually to acquire the Register from Goodson.
   ``Nothing at the Register will change as a result of this,''
Geyer said.
   Ingersoll also is terminating its management of Goodson
newspapers. Goodson's weekly and daily newspapers are in six states
and including the Register had total revenue of $225 million in
1988.
   Robert M. Jelenic, president of Princeton-based Ingersoll
Publications, said, ``We'll now be able to concentrate all the
energies of our extraordinary operating team on creating more value
for the communities served by our own newspapers.''
   Mark Goodson, chairman of New York-based Goodson Newspapers said
he had set up a management team that would be responsible solely
for operating the Goodson newspapers.
   The Ingersoll group includes the recently launched St. Louis
Sun; the Trentonian in Trenton; the Birmingham Post and Mail in
England; 28 other dailies; and more than 200 non-daily papers in
the United States and Europe. The newspapers have combined annual
revenue of more than $750 million.
</TEXT>
