<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Computer     10-24 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Computer,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Control Data Reports Third-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp. on Tuesday credited
extensive restructuring earlier in the year for a third-quarter
profit of $9.8 million, which contrasted with a $2.4 million loss
in the same period a year earlier.
   The computer company also reported earnings per share of 23
cents for the 1989 third quarter ended Sept. 30, compared with a
loss per share of 6 cents for the same quarter a year ago.
   Revenues of $763 million for the 1989 quarter were down 9
percent from $841.4 million a year ago.
   Control Data said the quarterly results were helped by the sale
of Imprimis, the disk drive subsidiary, to Seagate Technology.
Pre-tax earnings of $16.2 million include an $8.5 million gain from
restructuring, which was made up of a $33.7 million gain from asset
sales, including Imprimis, offset by charges of $25.2 million.
   For the first nine months of this year, the company reported a
loss of $484 million, or a per-share loss of $11.51, compared with
earnings of $14.5 million, or 34 cents a share, for the 1988
period. Revenues were $2.41 billion, compared with $2.7 billion a
year ago.
   The company lost $497.3 million in the second quarter, mainly as
a result of shutting down the ETA Systems supercomputer subsidiary
and cutting 3,100 jobs. Closing the St. Paul, Minn.-based ETA cost
Control Data around $335 million. The balance of the charges came
from shrinking the Cyber mainframe division, paying severance to
cover corporate staff layoffs and the company's departure from the
training and education business.
   ``The improved results the company achieved in the third quarter
are gratifying and stems from the actions taken during the past
several months,'' said Robert M. Price, chairman and chief
executive officer.
   ``While the results represent only a modest return to positive
momentum, the company can now build on that momentum.''
   Every business group except the semiconductor subsidiary was
profitable before interest and taxes in the third quarter, the
company said.
</TEXT>
