<HEAD>Goodyear's 3rd Quater Shows Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co. reported Tuesday
that its third-quarter profit rose 11 percent over a year ago due
to improved tire sales.
   Net income for the three months ended Sept. 30 totaled $70.5
million, or $1.22 a share, compared with earnings of $63.5 million,
$1.11 per share, in the 1988 quarter. Sales rose to $2.68 billion
from $2.66 billion.
   ``Our third quarter reflects an improvement in the U.S. tire
business from the disappointing year-earlier period,'' Goodyear
Chairman Tom Barrett said in a statement.
   Goodyear said earnings in the latest quarter were held down by
higher taxes on foreign earnings.
   For the first nine months of 1989, Goodyear earned $192.1
million, or $3.33 per share, after accounting for a second-quarter
$95 million loss from sales of the company's South Africa
subsidiary and an unused pipe held by Goodyear's All Amrican
Pipeline subsidiary. Sales were $8.1 billion.
   That compared with earnings of $293.7 million, or $5.13 a share,
for the first three quarters of 1988. Sales were just under $8
billion.
