<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1255EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Earns-Oil     10-24 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Oil,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco's Profit Rose 11 Percent In Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. said today its earnings rose 11
percent in the third quarter, helped by substantially higher
results in the company's exploration and production business.
   For the three months ended Sept. 30, Texaco earned $305 million,
or $1.10 a share, compared with $274 million, or $1.12 a share, a
year earlier.
   Revenue dipped 4 percent to $8.36 billion from $8.68 billion,
the result of the company's recent asset restructuring,
   Texaco said the lower per-share earnings in the third quarter
reflected a higher number of outstanding shares of common stock as
well as a new preferred stock for which the company must set aside
reserves.
   In the first nine months, Texaco's earnings more than doubled to
$2.13 billion, or $8.19 a share, from $1.01 billion, or $4.14, a
share, in the comparable 1988 period.
   Revenue was down slightly at $26.42 billion from $26.67 billion.
   Nine-month earnings benefited from a gain of $1.2 billion, or
$4.87 a share, from the sale of Texaco Canada Inc. in the first
quarter. The sale was part of a massive restructuring involving the
sale of some $7 billion in assets.
   Texaco completed the asset-sale portion of the restructuring
earlier this year, nearly a year after emerging from bankruptcy
protection. Texaco had filed for protection from its creditors
under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy laws in April 1987 to
avoid having to post a potentially damaging multibillion-dollar
security bond in its fight with Pennzoil Co.
   Pennzoil had sued claiming Texaco's 1984 acquisition of Getty
Oil Co. interfered with Pennzoil's prior contract to buy part of
Getty. A Houston jury awarded Pennzoil a $10.3 billion judgment.
Texaco appealed but eventually settled with Pennzoil for $3 billion.
   Texaco last week announced its first major acquisition since the
restructuring _ a $476.5 million purchase of Tana Production Corp.,
the Corpus Christi-Texas-based subsidiary of TRT Energy Holdings
Inc. with large natural gas and oil properties.
   James W. Kinnear, president of the nation's third-largest oil
concern behind Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp., said Texaco in the
third period completed the distribution to shareholders of a
portion of the proceeds from the restructuring.
   It also initiated a stock buyback plan under which the company
proposes to repurchase, ``subject to market conditions,'' $500
million of its common stock by August 1990. Texaco also retired
approximately $1 billion of debt, Kinnear said.
   Higher crude oil prices during the third period boosted Texaco's
exploration and production earnings substantially from $68 million
in the 1988 period to $185 million in the latest quarter.
   The company's chemical's business also showed strong gains _ $68
million vs. $45 million a year earlier.
   Lower gasoline prices and higher crude costs, however, hurt
Texaco's refining and marketing business during the period.
Earnings in that sector were cut in half to $180 million from $373
million in the third quarter of 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891024-0253 </DOCNO>
