<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Jaguar 1stLd-Writethru   10-24 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Jaguar, 1st Ld-Writethru,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Ford saying it is prepared to bid for
all of Jaguar.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. might try to buy Jaguar PLC
outright when British government restrictions on investors' shares
in the luxury automaker expire at the end of 1990, the U.S.
automaker said Tuesday.
   Meanwhile, Jaguar said Ford was continuing to build its stake in
the British luxury carmaker and had boosted its holdings to 12
percent from 10.4 percent.
   Ford filed documents Monday with the Securities and Exchange
Commission declaring that it might bid for all of Jaguar,
spokeswoman Lin Cummins said.
   Whether a bid would in fact be made was not immediately known.
``It isn't saying we will do it, and it isn't saying we won't,''
Cummins said.
   Under British regulations, no investor can acquire more than 15
percent of Jaguar until the end of 1990. The British government
imposed that restriction when it privatized Jaguar in 1984.
   SEC regulations require a company to state its intentions when
it acquires 5 percent or more of another company, and that led to
Monday's filing by Ford, Cummins said.
   Jaguar has said it wants to remain independent.
   The latest stock purchase coincided with talks between Jaguar
and General Motors Corp. on an operating agreement that is expected
to include a commitment from GM to take a small equity stake in
Jaguar.
   Jaguar said Ford owned 21.9 million Jaguar shares by the close
of trading Friday. Ford reported holding 19.0 million shares Oct.
17.
   Ford said on Sept. 19 it planned to buy up to 15 percent of
Jaguar and has bought Jaguar shares steadily in the open market
since receiving U.S. regulatory approval earlier this month.
   Ford notified Jaguar of its SEC filing Monday by telephone but
has not met with Jaguar officials, Cummins said. ``We are amenable
to discuss the issue with them, but no new meetings have been
scheduled.''
   She said the company would not comment on GM's talks with Jaguar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
