<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     10-24 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0558</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined broadly in heavy trading
today as the collapse of the UAL Corp. buyout helped unnerve an
already shaky market.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials spiked downward as much
as 85 points in the morning before partially rebounding. It was
down 48.36 points to 2,614.55 by 2 p.m. EDT.
   In addition to the UAL buyout failure, analysts said traders
were worried about lower-than-expected corporate profits in the
third quarter and signs of economic weakness in the government's
latest report on factory orders.
   ``Volatility rules the day,'' said Barton Biggs, chief
investment strategist at Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
   ``I think we're going to see a lot of this skittishness until we
sort out the leadership in this market,'' said Peter Barry,
director of research at Fahnestock &amp; Co.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by 11 to 2 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 246 higher, 1,348 lower and 313
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 164.94 million shares as of 2
p.m. on Wall Street.
   UAL plunged 32| to 145} by 2 p.m. UAL's board of directors said
late Monday it has decided to keep the parent company of United
Airlines independent for now as it examines alternatives to a
$300-a-share employee-management buyout plan that collapsed earlier
this month.
   The announcement that the UAL group was unable to get financing
for the deal helped trigger a 190.58-point drop in the Dow
industrials on Oct. 13. The market bounced back last week, gaining
a record 119.88 points total, but the Dow average slipped back by
26.23 on Monday.
   Analysts said the news that UAL would remain independent
affected other transportation stocks and generally triggered the
morning selloff. Computerized program trading also contributed to
the decline.
   In Chicago, the plunge in stock prices sent S&amp;P 500 stock-index
futures down the 12-point limit permitted under ``circuit-breaker''
rules designed to slow heavy market selloffs. Index futures prices
rebounded after trading resumed.
   The government's report today of a slight decline in durable
goods orders during September today did nothing to dispel concerns
over lower-than-expected corporate profits for the third quarter.
   Orders for ``big ticket'' durable goods, held back by slumping
demand in the transportation category, slipped 0.1 percent in
September, the Commerce Department reported.
   Analysts said the August and September orders reports were
skewed by a big swing in demand for automobiles, which surged in
August only to drop back to a more normal level in September.
   Treasury bond prices rallied, following a recent pattern of
showing strength when stocks weaken. The benchmark 30-year bond was
up nearly } point at midday, equal to $7.50 per $1,000 in face
value.
   Airline stocks were down. AMR was off 4[ at 66{, Delta down 1}
at 65} and Pan Am was off [ at 3{.
   Among other active issues in early trading on the NYSE were
Phillips Petroleum, down ] at 22}; AT&amp;T, down ~ at 42[; Chevron,
down 1\ at 63|; and General Electric, down 1 at 55[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 3.10 points at 187.80. On the American Stock Exchange the
market index was down 4.44 at 375.02.
