<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0022 10-24 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0022,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Sharply Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing indices;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed sharply lower Tuesday on the
London Stock Exchange in a reflection of Wall Street's steep drop.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index shed 40.4
points, or 1.85 percent, to finish at 2,149.3.
   It closed above the session low of 2,147.0, which was posted
when the Dow Jones industrial average skidded 85 points within
minutes late in London trading. At London's close, the Dow Jones
average was 51.23 points lower at 2,611.68.
   The key London index began its downward course after it
registered a session high of 2,197.0 two hours into official
trading.
   Volume was a modest 405.4 million shares, up from 276.8 million
on Monday, which had been a record low.
   Dealers in London said the initial downward pressure came from
mildly disappointing British trade figures for September and a
worrisome report by the Confederation of British Industry that a
decline in orders for manufactured goods was depressing business
optimism and investment plans for the coming year.
   The trade and CBI reports refocused attention on Britain's high
interest rates and helped fuel concerns over prospects for a
recession, dealers said.
   The Financial Times 30-share index fell 33.3 points to close at
1,739.3. The Financial Times 500-share index lost 21.71 points to
close at 1,193.91.
</TEXT>
