<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-24 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harvest Pressures Grain Futures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans drifted
lower Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as the fast-moving
Midwestern harvest continued to bring new supplies to the market.
   Corn harvesting was 63 percent finished as of Sunday in the top
17 producing states compared with 46 percent a week earlier, 77
percent a year earlier and a 55 percent 5-year average, the
Agriculture Department said late Monday in its weekly crop-progress
report.
   The soybean harvest was 66 percent complete in the top 19
producing states compared with 55 percent a week ago, 70 percent a
year ago and a 57 percent 5-year average, the USDA said.
   The harvest should continue to advance rapidly since good
weather for outdoor work is expected in the Midwest through
Saturday.
   At the close of trading, wheat futures were \ cent to 3} cents
lower with the contract for delivery in December at $4.06} a
bushel; corn was unchanged to } cent lower with December at $2.40{
a bushel; oats were \ cent to 1{ cents lower with December at
$1.45{ a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 1\ cents lower with
November at $5.61} a bushel.
