<DOCNO> AP891024-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1618EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Sears     10-24 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Sears,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quarterly Earnings Down 15.6 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. Tuesday said its
third-quarter profit fell 15.6 percent, reflecting a sharp drop in
retailing income and a storm of claims filed against the Allstate
Insurance Co. by victims of Hurricane Hugo.
   The claims of more than $250 million represented the greatest
single storm-damage loss in Allstate's history, Sears said in
announcing its quarterly results.
   Sears earned $257.5 million, or 75 cents a share, in the three
months ended Sept. 30, compared with $305 million, or 80 cents a
share, in the comparable 1988 quarter.
   The per-share earnings reflected a stock-buyback program
announced a year ago that has reduced the number of outstanding
shares to 343.1 million compared to 379.8 million a year ago, Sears
said.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 4.8 percent to $13.2 billion from
$12.6 billion, the Chicago-based company said in a news release.
   Income from the Sears Merchandise Group, the nation's largest
retailing operation, plunged 25 percent to $82.9 million from
$110.5 million, Sears said.
   Revenue from the retailing division edged up 1.3 percent to $7.6
billion from $7.5 billion in 1988's third quarter.
   Sears attributed the retailing results to a soft market for
big-ticket durable goods, such as home appliances, and higher
interest costs in the credit segment of the merchandise group.
   Two retail analysts expressed differing opinions on whether the
performance of the merchandise group indicated that Sears'
``everyday low pricing'' strategy is failing.
   ``My opinion is that they probably have to do more promotion to
get the customers in the door,'' said Walter Loeb of Morgan Stanley
&amp; Co.
   But John Landschultz of Cowen &amp; Co. said the results ``weren't
bad at all.'' The real test of the new retailing strategy will come
in the second half of 1990, he said, after Sears finishes reshaping
its stores into collections of ``superstores,'' offering low-cost,
brand-name items in general groupings such as women's clothing,
major appliances or menswear.
   ``They're still in an adjustment period,'' Cowen said.
   Sears spokesman Douglas Fairweather was upbeat about the
strategy, which Sears began implementing last March to better
compete with discounters such as K mart Corp. and Wal-Mart Stores
Inc.
   ``We're very pleased with the results of everyday low pricing,
but that durable goods trough is very real and very significant,''
he said.
   Allstate's income fell to $126.1 million from $202.7 million,
largely as a result of damage claims from Hurricane Hugo, which
battered the southeastern U.S. coastline in September.
   The claims exceeded $250 million but because of reinsurance _
the practice among large insurance companies of farming out some of
their risk to smaller insurers _ the negative impact on Sears'
third-quarter net income was only $80 million, the company said.
   Allstate spokesman Greg Rossiter said it was ``a natural
conclusion'' that the company would also be hit with a lot of
damage claims from the earthquake that struck northern California a
week ago.
   But Rossiter said he could not predict the dollar amount of the
earthquake claims.
   The Dean Witter Financial Services Group reported net income of
$35.7 million for the quarter, up 32 percent from $27.1 million in
1988. Those results included a 71 percent increase in income from
Discover Card operations, which totaled $23.3 million.
   Third-quarter income from the Coldwell Banker Real Estate Group
jumped to $81.2 million from $22.2 million last year, reflecting a
nearly four-fold increase in after-tax gains from sale of
properties.
   For the nine months ended Sept. 30, Sears reported overall net
income of $906.4 million, or $2.56 per share, compared to $1.34
billion, or $3.52 per share, for the first nine months of 1988.
   Nine-month revenue rose 8.2 percent to $38.6 billion from $35.7
billion.
   The nine-month results for 1988 include a first-quarter
accounting change that resulted in a $550,000 increase in the
reported net income, Sears said.
</TEXT>
