<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     10-24 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0208</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market went for another rough ride
today, dropping steeply in morning trading only to finish the day
about even.
   The collapse of the UAL Corp. buyout helped unnerve an already
shaky market, and the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks
briefly tumbled as much as 85 points in the first 1{ hours of
trading.
   After partially rebounding, the Dow Jones average was down
between 40 and 50 points for most of the session, then rallied in
the final hour.
   Contributing to the late recovery were separate rumors about
billionaire investor Donald Trump: one that he was interested in
buying UAL, the parent of United Airlines, and one that he was
considering renewing his bid for AMR Corp., the parent of American
Airlines.
   In addition to the UAL buyout failure, analysts said traders
were worried about lower-than-expected corporate profits in the
third quarter and signs of economic weakness in the government's
latest report on factory orders.
   Underlying the market's volatility is continued nervousness that
Wall Street has not entirely recovered from the Friday the 13th
crunch, when the Dow Jones average fell 190.58 points.
</TEXT>
