<HEAD>Stocks Plummet, Bounce Back In Late Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with closing Dow ; picks up 7th
graf, The UAL....</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street rose a session of bucking stock
prices today, watching shares plummet in early trading and bounce
back up in a late rally to finish the day little changed.
   The widely watched Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks,
down as much as 85 points in early trading, finished down just 3.69
points at 2,659.22.
   Broader market indicators also fell in heavy trading, with
declining issues outnumbering advancers ones by almost 7 to 2 on
the New York Stock Exchange. Big Board volume totaled 237.96
million shares, compared with 135.86 million in Monday's session.
   Analysts said news that UAL Corp.'s board of directors had
decided late Monday not to proceed with a buyout plan by an
employee-management group affected other transportation stocks and
helped trigger the morning selloff.
   UAL finished down $8.37{ at $170, after having been down down
more than $32 a share earlier in the day.
   Computerized program trading involving stock-index futures also
contributed to the decline, market watchers said.
   The UAL group's Oct. 13 announcement that it was unable to get
financing for its $6.75 billion buyout played a role in the
190.58-point drop in the Dow industrials that day and turmoil in
stock markets worldwide.
   The market rebounded from that drop, with the Dow industrials
gaining a record 119.88 points last week.
   Market watchers also said the government's report today of a 0.1
percent slight decline in durable goods orders during September did
nothing to dispel concerns over lower-than-expected corporate
profits for the third quarter.
</TEXT>
