<FIRST>r f AM-GM-TVSponsorships     10-24 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GM-TV Sponsorships,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Plans to be Sole Sponsor of Several TV Specials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. said Tuesday it is making a
multimillion-dollar commitment to become the sole sponsor of
several television specials over the next two TV seasons.
   John McNulty, a spokesman for the automaker in Detroit, said the
programs will be billed on the broadcast and cable television
networks that carry them as ``GM Mark of Excellence Presentations.''
   He said GM is committing about $11 million to the project this
TV season and an unspecified amount for next TV season starring in
the fall of 1990.
   McNulty said GM spent about $8 million last year to be the sole
sponsor of similar shows, and feels that consumers who have watched
the shows tend to remember the sponsor and usually have an improved
opinion of the company.
   The new programs will include ``The American Playwright's
Theater'' series of plays on the Arts &amp; Entertainment cable
network; the annual ``Kennedy Center Honors'' specials on CBS,
``The American Film Institute Life Achievement Award'' special on
ABC and NBC's planned movie ``The Old Man and the Sea.''
   GM will be the sole advertiser on telecasts of these programs,
which are variously scheduled for later this year through 1991.
   In addition, GM said it had agreed to be the sole corporate
underwriter of Public Broadcasting System programs including the
``A World of Ideas with Bill Moyers'' series, the ``Live from
Lincoln Center'' series of music and ballet performances and a
planned 10-hour movie epic called ``The Civil War.''
   McNulty said GM has over the past five years of devoted a large
portion of the money it spends on ``corporate image'' advertising _
as opposed to ``product'' ads that tout specific cars _ on sole
sponsorships.
   ``It is one company's attempt to underwrite and exclusively
sponsor programs we believe are worthy to carry our name ...'' he
said.
   McNulty declined to say how much GM spends on corporate image
advertising.
   The trade journal Advertising Age recently estimated that GM
spent nearly $1.3 billion on all types of advertising last year,
making it the third-biggest advertiser behind consumer products
companies Philip Morris Cos. Inc. and Procter &amp; Gamble Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
