<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-24 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down; Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BC-LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished lower against most major
currencies Tuesday, depressed by volatility on Wall Street and
expectations of lower U.S. interest rates.
   A steep morning plunge of more than 80 points in the Dow Jones
industrial average touched off a heavy but brief flurry of dollar
sales that subsided once the stock market started to recover later
in the day.
   David Jaques, a vice president at Barclays Bank PLC in New York,
said the dollar didn't manage to recover all of the ground lost
during the temporary stock market selloff. The Dow industrials
closed with a loss of 3.69 points at 2,659.22.
   He said currency dealings were lethargic in the early going,
with traders lacking a compelling reason to buy or sell. News of a
0.1 percent decline in September orders for U.S. durable goods
created barely a ripple in the currency markets because the figure
virtually matched advance estimates.
   The durable goods report tended to support the view that
economic growth is flattening out to such an extent that the
Federal Reserve might decide to pump it up with more generous
credit.
   Looser credit would push down interest rates. Declining U.S.
interest rates generally weigh down the dollar.
   The dollar began its trading day in Tokyo with a fall to 142.10
Japanese yen from 142.40 yen at Monday's close. Later, in London,
it declined further to 141.95 yen. It was quoted at 141.50 yen in
New York, down from 141.90 yen on Monday.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6065 from $1.5945 late
Monday. A pound cost $1.6075 at the end of New York trading,
compared with $1.6030 on Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
quotes, included: 1.8358 West German marks, down from 1.8470;
1.6095 Swiss francs, down from 1.6190 Swiss francs; 6.2370 French
francs, down from 6.2740; 1.1713 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1704;
and 1,345.75 Italian lire, down from 1,356.00.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8390 West German marks, down from 1.8550; 1.6120
Swiss francs, down from 1.6270; 6.2475 French francs, down from
6.3050; 2.0860 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0965; 1,349.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,364.50; and, 1.1723 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1720.
   Gold prices rose. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
for current delivery settled at $370.20 a troy ounce, up $3.20 from
Monday's settlement. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a 4
p.m. EDT gold bid of $368.70 an ounce, compared with Monday's late
bid of $366.25.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $367.75 a troy ounce
from $365.75 bid late Monday.
   In Zurich, Switzerland, gold rose to a closing bid of $367.50
from $365.60 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 37 cents to close at a bid of
$366.91.
   Silver bullion prices rose in London to a late bid price of
$5.12 a troy ounce, up from $5.09 late Monday. On New York's Comex,
silver bullion for current delivery settled at $5.148 an ounce, up
from $5.089 on Monday.
</TEXT>
