<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-24 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recession Fears Fuel Copper Selloff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices nosedived Tuesday for the third straight
day, dropping to 2{-month lows on New York's Commodity Exchange on
selling fueled by perceptions of a weakening economy.
   On other futures markets, precious metals advanced; stock-index
futures retreated in a day of wild trading; grain and soybean
futures fell; oil futures were mixed; and livestock and meat
futures were mixed.
   Copper futures settled 0.9 cent to 4.6 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December down 4.5 cents at $1.151 a pound,
its lowest daily close since Aug. 11.
   ``It was a bloody, bloody day,'' said James Steel, a metals
analyst with Refco Inc., a large commodities brokerage.
   The decline began early and accelerated as prices fell through
successive levels of technical support. The December contract
traded as low as $1.134 before rebounding shortly before the close.
   Copper prices have fallen nearly 12 percent in the past seven
trading sessions, largely in reaction to an improving supply
picture.
   But analysts said Tuesday's selloff was more a reflection of
economic anxiety prompted by the stock market's volatility and by a
government report Tuesday that orders for durable goods fell 0.1
percent in September.
   On the stock market Tuesday, the Dow Jones average of 30
industrial stocks briefly tumbled 85 points in the first 1{ hours
of trading, partially rebounded, then was down 40 to 50 points for
most of the session before closing with a modest 3.69-point loss.
   ``I believe the copper market is fearing a recession,'' said
Peter Cardillo, a commodities trading adviser with Josephthal &amp; Co.
in New York. ``As an industrial metal, copper would suffer if a
recession came along.''
   Stock-market jitters and a weaker dollar helped the precious
metals as some investors ditched stocks and shifted assets into the
perceived safety of gold.
   Gold settled $3.20 higher across the board on the Comex with the
December contract at $373.40 a troy ounce; silver was 5.4 cents to
5.7 cents higher with December at $5.195 a troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures tripped a circuit-breaker on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange when the December S&amp;P 500 contract fell the
permitted 12-point limit, to 335.95, early in the session.
   The drop triggered a rule prohibiting selling at prices below
that level for 30 minutes, but trading halted only momentarily
before buying entered the market and prices rebounded.
   The rule is one of several circuit-breakers designed to slow a
market collapse.
   The contract for December delivery of stocks tracked by the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled 1.45 points lower at 346.50.
Each point is worth $500.
   Grain and soybean futures drifted lower on the Chicago Board of
Trade as the fast-moving Midwestern harvest continued to bring new
supplies to the market.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 3{ cents lower with December at $4.07
a bushel; corn was \ cent 1\ cents lower with December at $2.40 a
bushel; oats were \ cent to 1 cent lower with December at $1.45\ a
bushel; soybeans were 2\ cents lower to 1 cent higher with November
at $5.60} a bushel.
   Oil futures finished mixed on the New York Mercantile Exchange
with the November gasoline contract down sharply amid rumblings of
OPEC overproduction.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 4 cents lower to 1
cent higher with November at $18.60 a barrel; heating oil was .08
cent lower to .08 cent higher with November at 58.45 cents a
gallon; unleaded gasoline was .69 cent lower to .05 cent higher
with November at 52.79 cents a gallon.
   Cattle futures fell moderately on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, giving back Monday's gains. Pork futures were mixed.
   Live cattle settled .20 cent to .58 cent lower with December at
75.22 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .45 cent lower
with October at 82.80 cents a pound; live hogs were .13 cent lower
to .05 cent higher with December at 47.67 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .25 cent to .60 cent higher with February at
52.87 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
