<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Oil 1stLd-Writethru f0213 10-24 0812</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Oil, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0213,0834</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mobil, Chevron, Shell Earnings Fall; Texaco's Profit Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES with 4 final grafs to include Sun Co. earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. reported an 11 percent rise in third-quarter
earnings Tuesday, while Mobil Corp., Chevron Corp. and Shell Oil
Co. said earnings declined.
   The results reflected the benefits of Texaco's post-bankruptcy
restructuring as well as the mixed impact of higher crude prices,
which helps oil companies boost earnings on the exploration and
production end of their business but hurts the ``downstream'' end
of refining and marketing.
   Crude prices have been hovering between $19 and $20 a barrel,
about $3 higher than the same time last year.
   Mobil's earnings slipped 4 percent in the three months ended
Sept. 30 to $532 million, or $1.30 a share, from $557 million, or
$1.36 a share, in the comparable 1988 period. Revenue for the
nation's second-largest oil concern totaled $13.64 billion, up 4
percent over $13.12 billion a year earlier.
   In the first nine months, New York-based Mobil earned $1.4
billion, or $3.32 a share, down 16 percent from $1.6 billion a year
earlier. Revenue reached $41.69 billion, up 2 percent from $40.99
billion.
   Contributing to the lower quarterly earnings, Mobil said, was a
decline in chemical results and a $40 million provision for
restructuring of its U.S. exploration and production business.
   Mobil spokesman John Lord declined to give details of the
restructuring except to say that it would involve the transfer and
termination of employees over a two-year period ``in order to
reduce costs and focus efforts in areas where the projected
financial returns are most attractive.''
   Texaco earned $305 million, or $1.10 a share, in the third
quarter, up 11 percent from $274 million, or $1.12 a share, a year
earlier. Revenue dipped 4 percent to $8.36 billion from $8.68
billion, the result of the company's recent post-bankruptcy court
restructuring,
   Texaco, based in White Plains, N.Y., said the lower per-share
earnings in the third quarter reflected a higher number of
outstanding shares of common stock as well as a new preferred stock
for which the company must set aside reserves.
   In the first nine months, Texaco's earnings more than doubled to
$2.13 billion, or $8.19 a share, from $1.01 billion, or $4.14, a
share, in the comparable 1988 period. Revenue was down slightly at
$26.42 billion from $26.67 billion.
   Besides strong gains in the company's exploration and production
businesses, Texaco benefited from the restructuring, which lowered
its corporate losses, including interest expenses from the payment
of debt, by $117 million in the period.
   ``There are so many changes going on internally that the
financial data really isn't comparable with a year ago. It's almost
misleading to compare it with last year,'' said oil industry
analyst Rosario Ilacqua, with the investment firm of Nikko
Securities Co. International Inc.
   Texaco completed the asset-sale portion of the restructuring
earlier this year, nearly a year after emerging from bankruptcy
protection. Texaco had filed for protection from creditors under
Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy laws in April 1987 after
losing a high-stakes court battle with Pennzoil Co. that cost
Texaco $3 billion.
   Chevron Corp., headquartered in San Francisco, earned $417
million, or $1.22 a share, in the third quarter, down slightly from
$420, or $1.23 a share, a year earlier. Revenue jumped 11 percent
to $8 billion, from $7.2 billion.
   In the nine-months, Chevron's earnings declined 29 percent to
$1.13 billion, or $3.31 a share, from $1.6 billion, or $4.66 a
share, in the year-earlier period. Revenue totaled $23.9 billion,
up about 9 percent from $22 billion.
   Shell's third-quarter earnings fell 7 percent to $340 million
from $364 million a year earlier. Revenue dipped to $5.40 billion
from $5.47 billion.
   Nine-month earnings grew by 11 percent to $1.14 billion, from
$1.03 billion, while sales at Houston-based Shell increased 3
percent to $16.44 billion from $15.94 billion.
   Shell is wholly owned by the Royal Dutch-Shell Group of
Companies, based in both London and the Hague, the Netherlands. The
company does not report per-share earnings.
   Sun Co. said its earnings jumped 18 percent in the third
quarter, due largely to higher earnings from the company's Canadian
subsidiary and increased exploration and production results
overseas.
   Sun earned $85 million, or 80 cents a share, compared with $72
million, or 67 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue totaled $2.73
billion, up 11 percent from $2.46 billion.
   Nine-month earnings totaled $271 million, or $2.54 a share, a
turnaround from the $69 million loss, equal to 66 cents a share,
recorded in the year-earlier period. Revenue in the first nine
months rose 14 percent to $8.30 billion from $7.28 billion in the
1988 period.
   Sun said the absence of $10 million of losses from domestic
exploration and production operations in last year's results
contributed to an improvement in the latest figures.
</TEXT>
