<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     10-24 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Finish Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices closed mixed in lackluster
trading Tuesday as the market awaited new statistics on oil
inventories.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
finished 4 cents lower at $19.72 per 42-gallon barrel. The contract
lost 39 cents in Monday's session.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for November delivery slipped 0.69
cent to 52.79 cents a gallon while the December contract lost 0.47
cents to end at 52.31 cents a gallon.
   Domestic heating oil, meanwhile, recovered slightly from sharp
declines on Monday. Contracts for November and December delivery
each gained 0.3 cent. The November contract settled at 58.45 cents
a gallon, while the December contract closed at 58.87 cents. On
Monday, the contracts fell 2.02 cents and 2 cents, respectively.
   Analysts said the market continued the anemic performance of the
last several days, reflecting concerns about the growing supply of
crude on world markets and reports suggesting that the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries is continuing to increase its
output.
   Energy brokers said the market was focusing on new American
Petroleum Industry inventory statistics due out after the close of
trading.
   ``The expectation is that they will be up across the board,''
said Chris McCormick, a futures trader with Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc.
</TEXT>
