<FIRST>r f AM-NorfolkSouthern     10-24 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norfolk Southern,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norfolk Southern Announces $1.65 Billion Repurchase of Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norfolk Southern Corp. announced Tuesday a
3-year plan to repurchase 45 million shares of its publicly owned
stock at market price.
   The deal is worth around $1.65 billion.
   The transportation company currently is in the midst of a 20
million-share repurchase program that ends at the end of this year.
   ``We believe our stock purchase program over the last two years
has been successful and that an expanded program of purchases
should serve to enhance stockholder value,'' said Arnold B.
McKinnon, chairman and chief executive officer.
   Norfolk Southern's third-quarter earnings report is to be issued
Wednesday in New York.
   The company has 172.2 million shares publicly held.
   Deborah Noxon, a company spokeswoman, said Norfolk Southern has
purchased 19 million of the 20 million shares in the first
repurchase plan, and expects to buy back the remaining shares by
the end of the year.
   If the remaining 1 million shares and the newly authorized 45
million shares all are acquired, the number of publicly held shares
will be reduced by 26 percent, Ms. Noxon said.
   She said the company began its repurchase program in 1987 after
efforts to acquire the Conrail system and Piedmont Aviation fell
through. Norfolk Southern had $1 billion in cash reserves and
believed its best return was to buy back its own stock.
   Ms. Noxon said the latest repurchase would be financed by the
remainder of that reserve, some borrowed funds, and anticipated
income.
</TEXT>
