<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1917EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 2ndLd-Writethru f0241 10-24 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0241,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, ``I would ...,'' to RESTORE dropped word ``not.''
Picks up 15th graf pvs, `Aside from ...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>United Airlines' Parent Helps Keep Stock Market in Turmoil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street added to its casino image Tuesday in
a heart-thumping session that saw the Dow Jones 30-stock industrial
average plummet 85 points in the morning but rally to finish nearly
even.
   The Dow Jones average closed with a narrow decline of 3.69
points at 2,659.22.
   Broader measures of the market showed bigger declines than the
Dow average. Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones more than
3 to 1 on the New York Stock Exchange.
   The market's wild behavior was attributed to speculation over
the fate of buyout plans for UAL Corp. and continued skittishness
dating from the Friday the 13th plunge, when the Dow industrials
fell more than 190 points.
   Adding to the market's volatility was computer-driven program
trading, which seems to compress up and down trends into far
briefer periods of time.
   ``This is clearly a market that you can't turn your back on for
10 minutes,'' said Barton Biggs, chief investment strategist at
Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
   UAL led the market downward in the morning and back up late in
the day, when rumors spread that several potential buyers including
Donald Trump were accumulating stock in the parent of United
Airlines.
   The initial decline in UAL's stock came after the announcement
late Monday by UAL's board that it had decided to stay independent
for now as it examined alternatives to a $300-a-share
employee-management buyout plan that collapsed earlier this month.
   The stock of UAL fell more than 30 a share in the morning but
recovered to finish down only 8] at 170.
   The worst period for the market came at midmorning, when the Dow
Jones average fell more than 50 points in less than half an hour to
touch its low of 85 points off.
   In Chicago, the S&amp;P 500 stock-index futures contract fell the
12-point limit permitted under ``circuit-breaker'' rules designed
to slow heavy market selloffs. Index futures prices rebounded after
trading resumed.
   Adding to traders' nervousness Tuesday were lower-than-expected
third-quarter profits from several major companies and worries
about an economic slowdown. The Commerce Department reported that
orders for ``big ticket'' durable goods slipped 0.1 percent in
September.
   Peter Barry, director of research at Fahnestock &amp; Co., said he
was alarmed by reports that UAL takeover speculation was the main
factor in the market's rally in the final hour.
   ``I would truly hope that an event such as that (a new offer for
UAL), true or not, would not be enough to turn the entirety of
financial assets, stocks and bonds, on its ear. That would raise
questions about the underpinnings of the market, wouldn't you
say?'' Barry said.
   Aside from UAL, other actively traded issues included Security
Pacific, which fell ~ to 44{; Philip Morris, up | to 44{; Chase
Manhattan, down ~ at 38~; and AMR, down 1} at 68~.
   At the close, among New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, there
were 360 issues up, 1,213 down and 381 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to a heavy 237.96
million shares, up from 135.86 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 283.28 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the nation's stock markets as a whole fell
$18.69 billion, or 0.55 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.85 to 190.05.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 0.75 to 392.83, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index fell 1.13 to 343.70.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market fell
5.52 to 461.70. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 376.36, down 3.10.
</TEXT>
