<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 2106EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Cray     10-24 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Cray,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Increase in Third-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supercomputer maker Cray Research Inc. on
Tuesday reported a 35.4 percent increase in third-quarter earnings,
but said the results still lag behind expectations.
   The company, which earlier this month announced plans to lay off
400 workers or 7 percent of its workforce, reported earnings of
$30.65 million, $1.04 per share, for the quarter ended Sept. 30.
That compares with 1988 third-quarter earnings of $22.61 million or
73 cents per share.
   Third-quarter 1989 revenues were $210.16 million, up 44.7
percent from $145.21 million in the same period a year ago.
   Earnings for the first nine months of the year total only $36.57
million or $1.24 per share, compared with $68.1 million or $2.19
per share for the same period a year ago. Nine-month revenue
totaled $454.56 million compared with $425.42 million for the first
nine months of 1988.
   ``Since much of our current backlog is for 1989 deliveries, we
do not have great visibility into 1990,'' said Marcelo A. Gumucio,
Cray's president and chief operating officer.
   ``With the visibility we do have, along with an assessment of
our prospect list, we have concluded it is prudent to plan for next
year on the assumption that revenue again will be flat.''
   He said based on the company's revised projections, earnings
results will likely be 40 percent to 45 percent lower than the
company's 1988 performance of $156.6 million.
   Cray said customers accepted 17 systems, with total contract
value of about $175 million, during the third quarter. The value of
systems ordered during the quarter totaled about $145 million, and
the value of the order backlog at the end of the quarter was about
$315 million compared to $340 million at the end of the second
quarter.
</TEXT>
