<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 1934EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MackChairman     10-24 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mack Chairman,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mack Chairman Resigns As Third-Quarter Loss Expected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John B. Curcio, whose authority at the
wheel of Mack Trucks Inc. plunged along with company profits for
the past nine months, has relinquished his last title with the
truck maker.
   With the company on the verge of announcing a third-quarter loss
it expects to be about $50 million and looking at projected losses
in the final three months of the year, Curcio resigned Monday as
chairman.
   Curcio lost the post of president to newcomer Ralph Reins in
June when expectations of a loss in the second quarter were
announced, and then chief executive to the heir apparent in
September when the third-quarter projection was disclosed.
   Curcio's resignation will be effective with the election of his
successor, possibly as soon as Nov. 2, when the Mack board of
directors will hold a special meeting, Reins said.
   The push to remove Curcio apparently has been led by Renault's
truck operations, which owns about 45 percent of Mack's stock and
has four directors on Mack's 10-member board.
   ``Heads will roll at Mack,'' Phillipe Gras, chief of Renault's
truck operations, promised a French newspaper after the
third-quarter projections were announced.
   Curcio, 56, moved out of his office at Mack's world headquarters
in Allentown Friday, concluding a 10-year stay in the sixth-floor
executive offices.
   Curcio is the third key executive to leave the company in recent
months, following the departures of Louis J. LaFontaine, executive
vice president of administration, and John J. Costa, executive vice
president of manufacturing.
   To fill their respective places, Reins recruited William C.
Craig, a vice president of human resources at Volkswagen of
America, and Don DeFosset, president of off-highway products and
driveline division at Rockwell International Corp.
   Mack's earnings dropped 77 percent in the first quarter to
$1.203 million then further to a $18.42 million loss in the second
quarter.
   ``Curcio was running it, and he stumbled, '' said Frank
Prezelski, an analyst for Deutsche Bank Capital Corp. of New York.
``When you're a strong-willed central manager as he was, there's no
one else to blame. It's unfortunate, but he has to take
responsibility.''
   According to Prezelski, Renault lost its patience with Curcio's
regime early last month, when Gras learned of Mack's continuing
problems with its new E-7 engine and an industry-wide decline in
the truck market.
   ``This truck industry is a never-ending battle,'' Curcio said in
a telephone interview Monday with The Morning Call of Allentown
from his home. ``It's time for someone else to be on the front
lines.''
   ``Mack is in good hands,'' Curcio said.
</TEXT>
