<FIRST>u f AM-Honeywell     10-24 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honeywell,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honeywell Sells Some Yamatake-Honeywell Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc. on Tuesday announced the sale
of 16 percent of the outstanding common stock of its Tokyo-based
partner, Yamatake-Honeywell, for $280 million.
   The interest in Yamatake-Honeywell was acquired by a group of 10
Japanese financial institutions and industrial corporations, the
controls maker said.
   On Oct. 17, Honeywell said it had reached an agreement to sell
the 16 percent stake as part of the company's program to enhance
short- and long-term shareholder value, announced in July.
Honeywell said proceeds from the sale would be used in the
company's announced program to repurchase up to 10 million of its
own shares.
   A second sale of additional Yamatake-Honeywell outstanding
common stock is being negotiated, Honeywell said.
   ``This action follows through on two objectives we set for this
part of our value-enhancement program,'' said James J. Renier,
Honeywell chairman and chief executive officer.
   ``We unlocked part of the value of our investment in
Yamatake-Honeywell for our shareholders. At the same time, we are
maintaining the excellent long-time partnership with
Yamatake-Honeywell that has led to successful cooperative worldwide
research and development, marketing and distribution strategies.''
