<FIRST>r f AM-Mesa-StatesWest     10-24 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mesa-StatesWest,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mesa Rejects StatesWest Proposal to Combine Two Airlines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARMINGTON, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mesa Airlines on Tuesday rejected a
proposal by Phoenix-based StatesWest Airlines to combine the two
companies.
   Mesa's board of directors considered the proposal too vague and
ill-defined to constitute an offer or merit further consideration,
said Gary Risley, Mesa's vice president for corporate affairs.
   Mesa's board decided not to refer the Oct. 16 proposal to its
financial adviser, Risley said.
   StatesWest's proposal ``did not set forth the source of funds
for the proposal or describe the terms of the StatesWest securities
which the proposal contemplated would be issued to Mesa
shareholders by StatesWest,'' he said in a news release.
   StatesWest had offered about $15.3 million in cash and
StatesWest securities for all of Mesa's common stock that
StatesWest did not already own.
   The offer, made in a letter from StatesWest Chairman Rudy
Miller, called for $7 a share in cash plus securities of StatesWest
with a value of $3 a share.
   Risley has said Mesa has 1.65 million shares of stock
outstanding.
   StatesWest acquired 7.25 percent of the stock in May, and Miller
said he had recently purchased some additional stock.
   Mesa officials said earlier this month they had no interest in a
friendly takeover proposal by StatesWest. Mesa later announced it
was examining the possibility of buying Air Midwest of Wichita, Kan.
   StatesWest services cities in Arizona, Southern California and
Nevada.
   Mesa services cities in New Mexico, Colorado, Wyoming, Texas and
Arizona. A Mesa subsidiary, Milwaukee-based Skyway Airlines,
operates in Iowa, Indiana, Illinois, Michigan and Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
