<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 2132EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-QuakerOats     10-24 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Quaker Oats,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quaker Oats Reports 24 Percent Gain In Quarterly Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quaker Oats Co. announced a 24 percent gain in
its fiscal first-quarter profit Tuesday, citing strong improvement
in its domestic and international food businesses.
   Chicago-based Quaker reported net income of $55.7 million, or 70
cents a share, for the three months ended Sept. 30, compared with
$45 million, or 57 cents a share, for the same period a year ago.
   Results for the prior year's first quarter were restated to
reflect an accounting change that resulted in a charge of $6.4
million before taxes and $3.7 million after taxes, Quaker said.
   Quarterly sales rose slightly to $1.44 billion from $1.43
billion a year ago, the company said.
   Operating income from North American food operations soared 66
percent to $62.8 million from $37.8 million despite only a $300,000
increase in sales, to $901.4 million, Quaker said.
   The improvement resulted from lower advertising and
merchandising costs as a percentage of sales, and from better
productivity, the company said.
   ``We are taking a more focused approach to our advertising and
merchandising expenditures by targeting high-margin, value-added
products with our marketing dollars,'' said Chairman William D.
Smithburg.
   Quaker reported operating income from international food
operations at $38.6 million, a 55 percent gain over the $24.9
million reported in last year's fiscal first quarter.
   Operating income from Quaker's Fisher-Price toy subsidiary fell
32 percent to $28.9 million from $42.7 million, mainly due to lower
shipments of toys, the company said.
   First-quarter financing costs, including interest expenses and
foreign exchange, rose by $13.1 million to $30.7 million, mainly
due to borrowing for the fiscal 1989 acquisition of Continental
Coffee Products Co. of Chicago, Quaker said.
</TEXT>
