<FIRST>r f BC-Dunkin'Donuts     10-24 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dunkin' Donuts,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dunkin' Donuts Starts Accepting Purchase Bids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANDOLPH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dunkin' Donuts Inc. announced Tuesday it
has set up procedures to accept bids to buy the company from
interested parties, but one potential buyer alleged the company
isn't seriously considering offers.
   The international doughnut shop chain, which battled takeover
attempts for months before deciding in September to accept bids on
a friendly basis, set a Nov. 10 deadline for receiving bids.
   The move came after a Canadian partnership filed a motion Monday
to bring to early trial its lawsuit against the doughnut chain,
alleging the company reneged on its promise to receive friendly
bids.
   ``We've been responding to the fact that they are bringing up
litigation again,'' said Maureen Burgess, a spokeswoman for Dunkin'
Donuts. Several companies have expressed interest in buying the
company, which is based in this Boston suburbn, she said.
   Dunkin' Donuts officials, however, refused to say the company
was for sale.
   ``No determination has yet been made to sell the company,
although such a sale is one alternative being considered,'' said
Robert M. Rosenberg, chairman and chief executive officer, in a
statement released Tuesday.
   DD Acquisition Corp., a Canadian partnership that has pursued
Dunkin' Donuts since June, asked the Delaware Chancery Court on
Monday to move up a trial date for its lawsuit against Dunkin'
Donuts, currently set for Nov. 1 or later.
   The suit challenges a series of extensive efforts Dunkin' Donuts
undertook to prevent its acquisition.
   The trial date was postponed after Dunkin' Donuts announced
Sept. 29 it would begin looking at alternatives, including a merger
or leveraged buyout, to try to increase its stock price.
   DD Acquisition offered Dunkin' Donuts $45 a share, or $308
million, in late August, up from an offer of $43 a share tendered
two weeks earlier.
   Dunkin' Donuts reported a 34 percent drop in third-quarter
earnings, much of it attributed to costs associated with battling
the hostile takeover.
</TEXT>
