<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-Procter&amp;Gamble     10-24 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Procter &amp; Gamble,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>P&amp;G Sales, Earnings Up for Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Procter &amp; Gamble Co. said Tuesday a 6 percent
increase in sales and settlement of a cookie formula infringement
suit gave the company a 38 percent increase in its fiscal
first-quarter earnings.
   For the quarter ended Sept. 30, P&amp;G had a profit of $551
million, or $1.66 a share, on sales of $5.57 billion. During the
same period last year, the company earned $400 million, or $1.18 a
share, on sales of $5.26 billion.
   The per-share figures are adjusted to reflect a 2-for-1 stock
split stockholders approved this month.
   The company received a $125 million settlement during the
quarter in a patent-infringement lawsuit it filed accusing three
food companies of infringing on P&amp;G's formula for chewy cookies.
   P&amp;G received the settlement from Keebler, Nabisco and Frito-Lay
under a consent judgment signed by U.S. District Judge Joseph
Longobardi in Delaware last month.
   P&amp;G sued the companies in 1984, contending they obtained Procter
&amp; Gamble's formula for Duncan Hines chewy cookies by spying on the
company, then introduced similar cookies.
   P&amp;G cut back on production of the cookies in 1987, and has a
small share of the cookie market.
   The consumer products giant, which had sales of $21.3 billion
last year, makes and markets a variety of laundry and cleaning
products, personal-care products, pharmaceuticals, food and
beverage products, and products for business and industry.
</TEXT>
