<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-89 2327EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru f0291 10-24 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0291,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Share Prices Bounce Back</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was lower against the Japanese yen
Wednesday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
bounced back.
   The dollar was changing hands at 141.63 yen at late morning
after opening at 141.57 yen, down 0.53 yen from Tuesday's
142.10-yen finish. It was moving in the narrow range of 141.55 to
141.75 yen by late Wednesday morning.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues regained 71.90
points, or 0.20 percent, to move to 35,598.45 to end the morning
session. On Tuesday it shed 58.97 points Tuesday.
   The Nikkei rebounded as the yen's recovery against the dollar
reassured Japanese market players, said Yoshiro Inoue, a stock
analyst with Nomura Securities.
   ``Participants bought mainly domestic core industries issues,
including housing, railways and constructions,'' he said.
   ``After the market crash in New York almost two weeks ago
Japanese investors started buying domestic core industry issues and
avoiding import-export related issues, which had been the market
leaders,'' Inoue said.
   In currency dealings, the dollar started lower after a similar
downswing in New York overnight as American investors sold the
currency. The dollar in New York ended at 141.56 yen, down from
141.90 yen the previous day.
   Many Japanese market players expect the dollar to fall more,
considering a recent downtrend in U.S. interest rates, said a
trader with a major Japanese commercial bank, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   But the dollar was unlikely to fall too quickly because
institutional investors tended to buy the dollar whenever it fell
during trading, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
